<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0001 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-TEXASTEC     01-16 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-TEXASTECH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas A&AMP;M beats Texas Tech on disputed buzzer-beater
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ Talk about escaping with a win.
</P>
<P>
   After a bizarre finish Saturday night, Texas A&AMP;M hurriedly left
the United Spirit Arena with an 88-86 victory over Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were on their team bus on the way to the Lubbock
airport even as a lengthy conference involving the officiating crew
and Texas Tech coach James Dickey was ongoing. The object of the
meeting was whether a put-back basket by Andy Leatherman beat the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   From the team bus, Aggies coach Melvin Watkins called from a
cellular phone to the press room at the arena and was put on a
speaker phone. Not exactly your run-of-the-mill postgame news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Aggies scram in a hurry in order to make sure they
weren't called back to the court in the event the referees
determined Leatherman's basket came after the buzzer?
</P>
<P>
   ``You always worry about that,'' Watkins said. ``The one referee
(Charles Range) told me the basket was good, but you're always
concerned when there's that much discussion. But really, at that
point, what else do we have to stay around for?''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech's James Ware hit a 3-pointer to tie the score at 86
with 11 seconds to play. The Aggies' Bernard King fired up a
desperation shot with about 1.6 seconds left on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   King's shot glanced the bottom of the net. Leatherman, a 6-2
reserve walk-on guard, grabbed the ball with less than one second
left and put in an uncontested layup. TV replays indicated
Leatherman's shot came after the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the confusion began.
</P>
<P>
   Range ruled that Leatherman's basket beat the buzzer, and Dickey
went ballistic. Referee Eddie Jackson seemed to think the clock was
all zeroes when the basket went through.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief on-court conference, the referees appeared to rule
that Leatherman's shot was after the buzzer and an overtime was in
order. Then Watkins went ballistic. He and Range met in the tunnel
leading to the Aggies' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Range came back to the court and told the other two referees and
Dickey that the game was over. Dickey went ballistic again, taking
off his sport coat, firing it over his head and stomping about the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, meanwhile, raced to the Aggies' dressing room, told his
players to throw on their clothes and get on the bus. Several
players had no time to waste on showers, the word was.
</P>
<P>
   For about 30 minutes, Dickey, Texas Tech athletic director
Gerald Myers and the three referees held a meeting off the court.
About 5,000 of the 14,324 fans remained in their seats, and the
Tech players huddled around their bench.
</P>
<P>
   At long last, Myers, as red-faced as the sweater he was wearing,
came out and told the public-address announcer to tell the fans the
game was over and the Red Raiders had lost 88-86.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the game, the officials met with a pool reporter and
gave a different version of the story Watkins had given during his
conference call. Range did admit there was disagreement over
whether the ball had gone in before the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if it was safe to say the referees agreed, Range
said, ``No, it's not safe to say that. It's safe to say I made the
call. My partners raised some questions with me. Based on that
questioning, I went to the monitor (to watch the replay.)''
</P>
<P>
   According to a source who was privy to what was said in the
meeting, however, the referees said they could not use a replay to
determine if the shot beat the buzzer. They can only use the replay
to determine if the clock was turned on properly at the start of
the play. A check of the Big 12 handbook found no mention of when
replay can or cannot be used.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said Range told him Leatherman's basket was good, and
the game was over. When asked if he told Watkins that, Range said,
``No, I did not tell him that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey also said he was told by the referees they couldn't use a
replay to determine if the basket beat the buzzer. However, he said
that Texas Tech would file an appeal with the Big 12 Conference and
send in tapes of the final play.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of the call being overturned?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's not good,'' Dickey said. ``Most of us know how it
is in sports. Once it's over, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversial finish nearly overshadowed an outstanding
effort by the Aggies, who snapped a four-game losing streak by
matching their best offensive output of the season. Carlton Brown
came off the bench to score 22 points in 21 minutes _ 18 of them in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Aggies reserves outscored the Texas Tech bench 47-6.
Leatherman added 12 points and Andy Slocum had nine. King, held
scoreless in the first half, scored 15 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies led 47-41 at the half, the first time they had the
lead after 20 minutes in their last eight games. They trailed 22-10
after 10 minutes, but Brown got hot and the Aggies (5-9, 1-2 Big
12) had the Red Raiders (9-4, 0-2) on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the second half, the Aggies increased their
lead to 62-50. Each time Texas Tech made a small run to close the
lead, the Aggies answered. When King hit a 3-pointer from beyond
the top of the key with 50 seconds left in the game, Texas A&AMP;M went
ahead 83-78.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Raiders fought back and tied the score on Ware's
3-pointer, and overtime appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Leatherman had other ideas. He slid under the basket unnoticed
and pushed in the game-winning shot. Was it before or after the
buzzer? Watkins, on his cell phone from the team bus, didn't even
want to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory,'' Watkins said. ``What else would you
consider it?''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
