<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7380 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-TEXAS-T     01-16 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-TEXAS-TECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL BASKET LIFTS TEXAS A&AMP;M PAST TEXAS TECH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ The shot by Texas A&AMP;M's Andy Leatherman kissed
the glass and ripped through the net at 7:09 p.m. yesterday evening
at Texas Tech's United Spirit Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes of mass confusion ensued before the Big 12's
three-man officiating crew determined Leatherman's attempt occurred
before the buzzer sounded and indeed counted as the game-winning
basket during the Aggies' 88-86 upset of the red-faced Red Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Aggies coach Melvin Watkins did not wait for the final verdict
and added new meaning to the phrase ``start the bus.'' The
victorious Aggies (5-9, 1-2) departed the arena hurriedly, and
several players did not shower before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my team to go to the locker room and let's go,''
Watkins informed reporters during a conference call from a cellular
telephone while aboard the Aggies' team bus. ``What else did we
need to hang around for?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, suppose the officiating crew altered the original decision
of Charles Range, who signaled without hesitation that Leatherman's
shot counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the indication at one point that we were going to play
the overtime,'' said Red Raiders coach James Dickey, who
disappeared into the arena's bowels with officials for about 30
minutes after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Aggies guard Bernard King took what appeared would be the final
shot of regulation, but his rushed, off-balance attempt failed to
draw iron or glass. The basketball fell harmlessly into the hands
of an alert Leatherman, who scored uncontested.
</P>
<P>
   The jubilant Aggies and their coach rushed toward the visitors'
dressing room before disorder began. Dickey pleaded with officials
to view the replay from television monitors located at courtside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the parameters of using replay are, but I do
believe the bottom line is to get it right,'' Dickey said. ``We're
not talking about an out-of-bounds call or where the shot clock is
at.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials viewed the replays and appeared to reverse Range's
original decision, but Range also conferred with Watkins in the
corridor that leads to the arena's floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I made a decision. The basket is good. Will you
support me?''' Watkins recalled of their conversation in the
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm supporting you,'' Watkins recalled telling Range.
``Then, I left. I don't know what they were talking about after
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Range did not share Watkins' perception of that conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not tell him that the game was over,'' Range said.
</P>
<P>
   Official Paul Janssen said the crew went to the monitor to make
sure the clock started on time when the Aggies inbounded the ball
with 8.6 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to get into all these extraneous things,''
Janssen said. ``We conferred. Charlie counted the shot as good, and
the game is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech athletic director Gerald Myers plans to file a report
with the Big 12 and let the conference office determine if any
action will be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked a lot of Sundays,'' Myers said. ``It will be
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Aggies were on their bus, the Red Raiders (9-4, 0-2)
waited on the court for 45 minutes before being informed of the
officials' final decision. Many of the 14,324 spectators waited
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve forward Carlton Brown helped the Aggies pull the upset
by scoring 18 of his team-high 22 points during the first half, and
the Red Raiders _ who led the Big 12 in field goal-percentage
defense _ allowed Texas A&AMP;M to shoot 48.4 percent from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we were as good defensively as we have been,
and they were good offensively,'' said Dickey, who did not address
the media until 8:05 p.m. ``Brown really helped them off the bench,
and King hit some big shots at the end. They kept us on our
heels.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just wait and see what happens with the appeal
process,'' Dickey said, ``but I would say it's not good.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
