<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-16 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS JIMMY FADES, JAGS BURST FORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ It was stunning. It was brutal. And for
Jimmy Johnson, it was a coaching career 180 degrees from his glory
days with the Cowboys. This time, a dazed Jimster was on the
stunned and brutalized end of a playoff nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Put-it-in-three-inch-headlines seemed so long ago and far away.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a mere three inches of headline would not properly
explain what 62-7 was all about. But the expected repercussions
just might. A multitude of NFL timelines could follow immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning of an era: If the Jacksonville Jaguars are really this
good, then the Lombardi Trophy arrives here in two weeks, and might
stay awhile. Before yesterday, the Jaguars were generally regarded
as a soft No. 1 seed in the AFC playoff bracket. From ``soft'' to
62-7 playoff winners is a gigantic leap over NFL mankind.
</P>
<P>
   End of an era, Part I: Johnson's coaching career is expected to
give way to a beach in the Florida Keys. Jimmy meets today with
Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga. The only question seems to be if
this retirement will be voluntary. Huizenga, by the way, departed
yesterday's game early in the second half, apparently in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   End of an era, Part II: It was a trying season for future Hall
of Fame quarterback Dan Marino. But at no time has he appeared as
old, tired and worn out as yesterday. Unlike Johnson, however,
Marino can't seem to take a hint. Even a 62-7 hint. ``I still feel
I can win games in this league,'' he said, after throwing two
interceptions and losing a fumble, all in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, 62-7 also benefited the Cowboys from the
standpoint of who might be coming and going in Miami. Legitimate
head coaching candidates for Jerry Jones' new vacancy have been
hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   But Dolphins assistant head coach Dave Wannstedt, a longtime
Jones favorite, indicated after the game he was interested. Word
from Miami earlier in the week had said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to talk to Jerry,'' Wannstedt said. ``Everyone knows
how I feel about that area and about that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt was the Cowboys' defensive coordinator at the start of
the dynasty era, moved to the Bears as head coach for six seasons,
and was hired by Johnson early last year to be his No. 1 assistant
and possible replacement as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   But Wannstedt's contract in Miami was for only this season,
which was at his request to keep options open for another head
coaching job. If Johnson retires, Huizenga might choose to go with
an entire new staff, particularly after 62-7.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had any offensive-coordinator candidates in mind for
the Cowboys, Wannstedt answered, ``I sure do.'' But he also said
he'd had no contact this week from anyone with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, based on yesterday, the Cowboys could use any member
of the Jaguars' offensive staff.
</P>
<P>
   Marino's horrible day can explain Miami's not being competitive
on one side of the ball. But the Dolphins' once-proud defense was
steam-rolled by Jacksonville, which already had put up 31 points by
one play into the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Blame me, was the Jimmy explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today was because of poor judgment on my part,''
he said. ``I should have given the players an easy week of
practice. Instead, we worked hard, really had good practices, but
we left it all on the practice field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of me, we were dead-legged right from the start. I
give full credit to Jacksonville, but we weren't fresh out there,
and I'm to blame for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins opened the first round of the playoffs a week ago
with a 6,000-mile round trip to Seattle. After that victory, the
turnaround was quick, playing the first game of the second round
here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also had preached his usual ``keep it conservative
and turnover free'' sermon for Jacksonville. Even as an 8 1/2-point
underdog, the Dolphins were given a good chance for the upset.
Jacksonville was a 14-game winner in the regular season but had
defeated no team with a winning record and lost twice to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   When Jacksonville drove for a touchdown after taking the opening
kickoff, the blowout was about to begin. Marino then threw a
mindless interception on his first possession, resulting in a
Jaguars' field goal. Marino followed that by having the ball
knocked loose, and Jacksonville defensive end Tony Brackens scored
on the fumble he caused.
</P>
<P>
   It was quickly 17-0, and much worse for the Dolphins would
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been on this side of it before,'' said Johnson, who
quickly bolted the postgame interview room without taking a
question.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Jimmy didn't want to be asked about his football
future. After 62-7, there doesn't appear to be one.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 0103EST &QL; 
