<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DEFEAT WOLVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS -- The Lakers ended an intimate relationship this
week end, and as with anyone in a transitional phase, a wardrobe
change was in order. Their accessory of choice Saturday should have
been the hard-hat.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the rest of their lives, following the end of
their am azing 16-game winning streak, included a date with the
equally hot Minnesota Timberwolves. And it took a grind-it-out,
workmanlike effort to restore their winning ways, which they did
with a 104-91 victory at Target Center.
</P>
<P>
   After losing at Indiana on Friday with a flurry of late miscues,
the La kers dominated the final minutes against Minnesota, holding
the Timberwolves to 11 points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A bounce-back from the emotional low of seeing their streak
snapped? Yes. But coach Phil Jackson said the victory was all about
playing steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get emotional,'' he said. ``It was just a
take-care-of-business type of game. This was a game in which we had
to go out and prove to ourselves that we're going to take care of
business and not get flustered if they have a run, and not get
taken out of the control phase of ou r game. And we did a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Kobe Bryant put it, ``We just didn't want to lose two in
a row. We wanted to nip it in the bud. We lost one, big deal --
come out, win, get back on the right track again.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, fighting off fatigue and a slight shooting
slump, led the way Saturday with a game-high 26 points on 11-of-20
shooting and added 19 rebounds, seven assists and five blocked
shots.
</P>
<P>
   But it was what he did in in the fourth quarter that made the
difference -- scoring eight points on 4-of-7 shooting and making a
defensive stan d when the Lakers desperately needed to put the
Timberwolves away.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal admitted to being tired on the three-game road trip, but
Jackson kept him fresh for the finish, using John Salley to spell
him in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs was tired,'' O'Neal said. ``I asked him for that rest,
and he gave me a couple minutes. Salley came in and did a pretty
good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Neal, Bryant again struggled with his shot, scoring 22
points on 8-of-18 shooting. Glen Rice added 17 points, and Derek
Fisher scored 14 .
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by as many as 17 points in the first half, the
Timberwolves used a 31-23 third quarter to forge an 80-80 tie
heading into the final period. Kevin Garnett and Terrell Brandon
scored 11 points each in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were energy-short there in the second period, and
we came out and struggled in that third quarter,'' Jackson said.
``They did a nice job of getting the game back by putting (Joe)
Smith on Shaq and creating a situation inside, getting 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt confident that we still had the game controlled at
some level in the fourth quarter. Defensively, we got ourselves
together. Derek did a nice job on Brandon and we were able to hit
some outside shots.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Fisher again. He hit four 3-pointers in the fourth
to score 12 of his 14 points while managing to contain the speedy
Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers scored the first nine points of the quarter, and when
Fisher hit from 26 feet out for his third 3-pointer, the cushion
was back to 15 points, 97-82, with less than five minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he took it personally that his guy wasn't even
checking him,' ' O'Neal said of Fisher, who was left open when
Brandon double-teamed the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get offended or anything like that when people do
that,'' Fisher said. ``I just wanted to come back in and be
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers fell short of a 3-0 road trip, and returned home
early this morning without a truncated winning streak, but retain
the best record in the NBA at 32-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to come in, punch the clock, go home to L.A.
and play in Staples Center again,'' Bryant said. ``We miss our
home. That's our castle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
