<SLUG> BC-BKN-PORTLAND-DALLAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY STATES CASE TO PIPPEN AS MAVERICKS BEAT BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Maybe it's time Scottie Pippen reconsiders his stance
on Michel Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who Pippen said last week doesn't deserve All-Star
consideration, admitted he had a point to prove in the Mavericks'
113-105 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers at Reunion Arena
last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a little incentive,'' Finley said. ``I wanted to
prove not only to him, but around the league that I deserve to be
on the All-Star team.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's 32 points and Hubert Davis' three fourth-period
3-pointers enabled the Mavericks (12-24) to hold off the
fast-charging Blazers before the Mavericks' first home sellout
(18,148) of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hubert made some big 3-pointers, and he and Mike took over in
the fourth,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson said after the team's
second consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also had plenty to say about Pippen's comments regarding
Finley, the NBA's 12th-leading scorer at 22.6 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie has a lot to say about a lot of things,'' said Nelson,
who moved within two victories of 900 in his career. ``That's his
prerogative. I've said all year that Mike is an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first negative I've heard about Finley from another
player. If \RFinley\S had something to prove tonight, I think he
proved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who said he is friends with Pippen and the two work out
together in the summer, said Pippen's opinion may stem from sour
grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie is basically an All-Star not having an All-Star
season,'' said Finley, who was 13-of-25 from the field, including
2-of-4 on 3-pointers. ``And I'm somebody that can take his spot
\Ron the All-Star team\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen scored a Blazers-high 22 points and remained unconvinced
of Finley's All-Star credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be difficult to make the All-Star team off a bad team,''
he said. ``It's a true fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's last 3-pointer, a 26-footer, pushed the Mavericks lead
to 102-96 with 3:49 left. Portland point guard Damon Stoudamire had
just cut the Mavericks lead to three points moments earlier with a
3-point play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to make a run,'' said Mavericks
forward Cedric Ceballos, who scored 17 points. ``They have depth
and a lot of weapons. It was great for us to hold our composure and
match their intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland (28-9) pulled with 107-105 with less than a minute to
play, but the Mavericks made six of their last seven foul shots to
secure the victory. The victory snapped the Blazers' eight-game
winning streak against the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks led from late in the first period to the end, but
had to fight off several Portland runs. The Blazers, who played the
night before in Phoenix, looked sluggish in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key was getting on them early, especially with them coming
off a back-to-back,'' Mavericks guard Erick Strickland said.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland helped keep the Blazers at bay when the visitors made
a charge early in the third period. Rasheed Wallace's jumper pulled
Portland within 70-58 _ the closest the Blazers had been since
midway through the second period. Strickland answered with a
3-pointer, a free throw off Wallace's second technical foul and
another three-pointer. Wallace was ejected in the third quarter
after being called twice for technical fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland's spurt was sandwiched around two Pippen foul shots
and pushed the Mavericks back up to 15 (77-62). Strickland would
score 11 of the team's last 13 points in the third, as the
Mavericks went into the final period up 83-71.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks jumped out to a 10-point lead (22-12) late in the
first period and watched the advantage grow for the rest of the
first half. Finley sliced through the Blazers for 17 first-half
points and the Mavericks shot 52.1 percent over the opening 24
minutes. The 18-point lead at the half (61-43) was the Mavericks'
second-largest at the break this season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
