r s BC-BKN-PHILLS-COMMENTARY     01-16 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PHILLS-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLS TRAGEDY SHOWS WHAT IS WRONG WITH SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DON BOWMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death of Charlotte Hornets basketball player Bobby Phills on
Wednesday was a terrible, tragic waste.
</P>
<P>
   It also pointed out all that is wrong with athletics today.
</P>
<P>
   Phills, by all reports, was a giving, community-minded player
who definitely did not fit in with the current profile of many
``thug'' athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, according to police statements, Phills and
teammate David Wesley decided to drag-race their Porsches,
resulting in the fatal crash. On a dangerous road with a 45-mph
speed limit, Phills, going more than 75, lost control and slid into
oncoming traffic. He was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets were given permission by the NBA to postpone their
next two games and will wear armbands to honor Phills for the rest
of the season. And that's all justifiable and good.
</P>
<P>
   But the team went a step too far. Phills' number is going to be
retired Feb. 9, becoming the first player to have his number
retired in the team's 11-year history.
</P>
<P>
   That's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As good a person as Phills seems to be, he has been given a
special honor _ special consideration _ because he is an athlete.
And while his death is a tragic waste, he doesn't deserve that.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people were injured in the accident. ``They'' could
have been killed instead of Phills. And if they had, would the
Hornets still be retiring his number? Do you think the families of
those two people will be cheering Phills' induction into Hornets
history?
</P>
<P>
   The way athletes are perceived by the American public _ and
justice system _ sometimes boggles the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Muhammad's wife dies in childbirth, and his teammates talk
about how difficult it is for Muhammad. Meanwhile, he's being
investigated by the police and is facing misdemeanor battery
charges after allegedly roughing up her and her 6-year-old son a
few days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad is still playing. His wife's father has publicly asked
how the Colts could give tougher punishments to players for use of
marijuana than domestic violence. There was a report Muhammad was
fined $10,000 at one point, but the Colts have denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Rae Carruth's pregnant girlfriend is gunned down and killed, and
his teammates talk about how difficult it must be for poor Rae,
who, by the way, refused to talk to the police on the day it
happened. Now he's on trial for murder, facing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes, above everything else, are people, not gods. There are
a tremendous number of them who contribute greatly to society. Troy
Aikman and Emmitt Smith of the Cowboys give back a great deal to
the community. Royce Clayton and Rusty Greer of the Rangers are
also very involved in local causes. The Cardinals' Mark McGwire is
actively involved financially and emotionally in trying to help
battered children.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many athletes who have been brought up believing
they're something special _ and have gotten away with things the
normal person couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Phills was ``not'' an antisocial, lawbreaking person,
although he reportedly had several other speeding violations. His
death was a tragedy. In fact, I have a feeling he would be appalled
that his number is being retired after his death, considering how
it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   And by retiring it, the Hornets are sending a bad message _ and
compounding the tragedy more.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
