<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-T     01-16 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLTON FISK A RARE FIND IN COOPERSTOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk will join an elite group this summer. The few, the
proud, the Hall of Fame catchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hall voters, including members of the Baseball Writers
Association of America as well as the Veteran's Committee, had
elected 180 major-leaguers before this year. The number included 58
pitchers, 54 outfielders (18 left fielders, 16 center fielders and
20 right fielders,) 24 corner infielders, although only nine third
basemen, 19 shortstops and 14 second basemen.
</P>
<P>
   And only 11 catchers.
</P>
<P>
   Why the prejudice against backstops?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe because it's been referred to as the player wearing the
tools of ignorance,'' said the man who'll make it a dozen when he
goes in this July. ``A lot of players, a lot of writers, a lot of
fans don't truly know what it takes to catch every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Who, indeed, can know what it takes to squat behind the plate
for nine innings? Or what it does to the knees? Or the toll it
takes, physically and mentally? Who can know what it takes to go
through all that and then also contribute with the bat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Catching is such a unique position,'' said Fisk, who did more
of it than anyone who ever played the game. ``Sometimes lost in the
translation is just how difficult catching is. As a result, some of
what you do gets lost in the shuffle.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what generally gets lost is a catcher's ability to
swing the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame voters, and baseball fans in general, can
appreciate the defensive attributes of catchers. They can
appreciate Bob Boone's seven Gold Gloves and the six consecutive
Gold Gloves won by former Ranger Jim Sundberg from 1976 to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   But they also realize few catchers have Hall of Fame offensive
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Boone threw out more than 45 percent of runners attempting to
steal with California in 1982-88, including 58 percent his first
year with the Angels. But he was a career .254 hitter with
single-season highs of 12 homers and 66 RBI. He dropped off the
ballot this year when he didn't get the required five percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sundberg dominated the American League defensively for several
seasons, but he was a .248 career hitter with single-season highs
of 12 homers and 65 RBI. His one and only year on the ballot was
1995, when he got one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catching is so different than any other position on the
field,'' Fisk said. ``A lot of people can catch a little bit, be
platooned a little bit, but to catch a lot and be part of both ends
of the game, I don't think a lot can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hall of Fame voters are guilty of anything when it comes to
catchers, it's not asking the question of whether they dominated
their position offensively and defensively for a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   Using that criteria, 11-time All-Star Gary Carter would make it.
Instead, he was a badly beaten also ran on the ballot. Lance
Parrish also would have to be considered when he makes it on to the
ballot in a couple of years. Instead, he's not likely to get much
attention.
</P>
<P>
   So until Ivan Rodriguez _ assuming he stays on his current
career track _ and Mike Piazza _ assuming he doesn't switch to
first base and play the bulk of his games there _ retire, the
small, elite group of Hall of Fame catchers isn't likely to grow
anytime soon. Cap question The question of which cap Fisk would
wear on his Hall of Fame plaque came down to which team smoothed
over hard feelings from his playing days.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk came up with the Red Sox and played in Boston for 11 years,
but departed under a cloud of bitterness after the 1980 season when
he became a free agent because the club missed the deadline for
mailing him a contract.
</P>
<P>
   He moved on to Chicago, where he played 13 seasons for the White
Sox. But he became upset when he was released in 1993 at age 44 and
wasn't allowed into the clubhouse to mingle with his former
teammates during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The bitterness toward the Red Sox largely is gone; Fisk is
employed as a special assistant to Boston general manager Dan
Duquette. The hard feelings toward the White Sox remain.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite playing more seasons in Chicago, Fisk is going in
with a Red Sox cap. Staying or going? The Ken Griffey trade talks
are alive and well. Or they're dead in the water.
</P>
<P>
   It's certain that if Griffey is dealt, he's going to Cincinnati.
The superstar center fielder has made it clear he'll exercise his
veto power if the Mariners trade him to any team other than the
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Trade talks fell apart during the winter meetings when the Reds
refused to include second baseman Pokey Reese in any package. No
deal, Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden announced. Nothing
further to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a deal issue to me,'' Mariners GM Pat Gillick said.
He said he hasn't talked to Bowden but ``our organization has.''
</P>
<P>
   So the talks are alive, right? Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed,'' Bowden said. ``We have not reopened any
discussions with them.'' Role model? Long-distance carrier IDT
Corp. is interested in entering into a long-term endorsement
agreement with Pete Rose. The company reportedly wants to build the
campaign around the parallels between the hit king's determination
to overcome his ban from baseball for gambling and IDT's goal to
gain a market share against established phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of ourselves as a company that really hustles, and he
was the most hustling player there was,'' said Howard Jones, IDT's
founder, chairman and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was a great ballplayer who might have got more out of
limited talent than anyone who ever played the game. It can be
argued that his sins weren't any greater than the many who have
besmirched the game by abusing drugs, alcohol or wives.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose also is an unrepentant, compulsive gambler and doesn't
deserve to be pitching anyone's product. Wrong remedy You don't
have to be a politically correct, left-wing idiot to realize that
Braves reliever John Rocker was wrong to make his bigoted remarks.
But ``off his Rocker'' is just a cute line, not a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Various hates and prejudices ultimately are a moral decision,
not a matter of mental defect. If baseball thinks that being
ostracized by fans and having to deal with his own teammates isn't
punishment enough, it should come up with a remedy other than
psychiatric testing. ] Keeping up with the Joneses The Mets
cornered the market on pitchers named Bobby Jones when they traded
Masato Yoshii to the Rockies for left-hander Bobby M. Jones. They
already had right-hander Bobby J. Jones, a right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   The two Joneses made a little bit of baseball history when they
started against each other on May 11. It was the first time
starting pitchers with the same name faced each other since April
16, 1899, when Cincinnati's John B. Taylor met Chicago's John W.
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second time the Mets have had pitchers with the same
name. In 1962, Robert L. Miller and Robert G. Miller pitched for
the team. Hot stove embers If the Rockies pitching doesn't improve,
it won't be because of lack of effort by GM Dan O'Dowd. He's added
Masato Yoshii, Rolando Arrojo, Julian Tavarez, Mike Myers, Jose
Jimenez, Manny Aybar and Rick Croushore this off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Trachsel's one year, $1 million deal with Tampa Bay could
be worth as much as $4.5 million if he meets all his performance
bonuses. Even so, it could be a bargain for the Devil Rays.
Trachsel lost 18 games last year, but he's one of only eight
pitchers to make 30 or more starts and pitch 200 or more innings in
each of the last four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox shortstop Mike Caruso looked like a future star when
he batted .306 as a rookie in 1998. But after hitting .250 with
more errors _ 24 _ than extra-base hits _ 17 _ last season, he's
about to lose his job to the erratic Jose Valentin.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
