<HEADER>
A7391 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-HOCKEY-REPORT-TEX     01-16 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOCKEY-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUBBED BELFOUR VICTIM OF ALL-STAR SCAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wild, wacky world of trying to make the game of hockey
more appealing to the TV-viewing masses, the NHL has taken the
unprecedented move of ``not'' sending their best players to the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not a typo.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Gary Bettman's politically correct All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   They want the biggest name players, i.e. Vancouver's Mark
Messier despite a less-than-spectacular season. They want a player
from every franchise, i.e. Atlanta's Petr Buzek, despite being a
healthy scratch only a couple of games before selections were
announced. They want the players fans vote for, i.e. Buffalo's
Dominik Hasek despite missing most of this season with a groin
injury.
</P>
<P>
   They're the players want even if they aren't the best players.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the quick and dirty version of why Stars goalie Ed
Belfour isn't an All-Star despite having an All-Star season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as \RBelfour\S was last year, he's been even better
this year,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said on the day the
selections were announced.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't say it, but without Belfour, the injuries that
plagued the Stars at the beginning of the season likely would've
buried them. Consider, too, on selection day the Stars were coming
off back-to-back games where they allowed 80 shots yet escaped with
three out of a possible four points, and you can see why Hitchcock
would say that the goalies have been the Stars' best players.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, for his part, wasn't saying much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   What can you do? Etc., etc., blah, blah, blah ...
</P>
<P>
   He understands the way the system works. He got caught in a
numbers game, and not the right numbers, either. In the end, it
didn't matter that his goals-against average (2.21) going into last
night's game was significantly lower than one of the two at-large
selections, New York Rangers goalie Mike Richter (2.69).
</P>
<P>
   What mattered was the NHL needed a player from the Rangers. They
felt like they had to honor a team that had underachieved with the
largest payroll in the league. Why? Who knows.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Belfour wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Former Stars and now St. Louis Blues goalie Roman Turek took it
on the chin, too. He has the best goals-against averages in the
league at 2.05, yet he was bypassed for Washington's Olaf Kolzig
and his 2.51 goals-against average. Why? You guessed it. They
needed a Capitals presence on the team to pull in the Washington
market.
</P>
<P>
   Does anybody really believe that Kolzig is going to help the NHL
pull a 20-share in the nation's capital? Or Richter for New York?
</P>
<P>
   Uh, let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's an idea: Have one player from every team represented
in the Skills Competition on Saturday. Have the best players play
in the All-Star Game on Sunday. Get it? Stars of league play in
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   No fan voting. No sending big-name players just for the sake of
their big names. No Colin Cambell in conjunction with general
managers doing the selecting.
</P>
<P>
   Have the players vote instead. They know better than anybody
who's having a good season. They know better than anybody who's
hard to play against. They know better than anybody who deserves to
go.
</P>
<P>
   And you bet, they would've known to put Belfour and Turek in.
Spotlight
Oilers' Marchant eager to continue what he started
Stars fans have an enduring, albeit frustrating, image of Edmonton
Oilers forward Todd Marchant.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Cup playoffs. First round. Stars vs. Oilers. Game 7.
Overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Marchant, in a single motion, ended Dallas' 1997 season a couple
of rounds sooner than expected, silenced a frenzied crowd and
forever burned an image into Stars' fans minds when he scored on
Stars goalie Andy Moog.
</P>
<P>
   A Stanley Cup and 33 months later, Stars fans will be happy to
know that Marchant still ranks that game-winning goal as his
biggest moment in hockey. The image is still burned in his mind,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what every player or kid dreams of doing, aside from
wining a Stanley Cup,'' Marchant said. ``When you are out playing
on the pond or in the backyard or out in the street, you are always
talking about situations and it is always the Stanley Cup playoffs,
Game 7 in overtime. So to actually go out and doing something like
that reaffirms all those dreams you had as a kid. It's a dream that
came true.''
</P>
<P>
   His goal didn't just win a game either. It started a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that goal, Stars and Oilers has become one of the
best rivalries in the Western Conference. That the two teams have
met in the playoffs for three consecutive seasons has also helped
the rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Could another playoff meeting be on the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   No, not with the way the Oilers began the season. Yes, with the
way they have been playing lately. And Marchant said he would like
nothing more than to play the Stars again if the Oilers qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's in the Western Conference finals,'' Marchant said.
</P>
<P>
   And does he imagine himself scoring another such goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a moment in time that kind of came out and that you are
being associated with,'' Marchant said. ``You bet I want to do it
again.''
Around the East Finding an apartment in New York? Hard.
</P>
<P>
   Finding one in a New York Islanders-approved way? Impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders general manager Mike Milbury ripped his young
goaltender Roberto Luongo for his apartment-hunting on game day.
The 7-3 loss to the Boston Bruins that night added to Milbury's
anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid was out looking at apartments the whole day,'' Milbury
said. ``Hel-lo? You can't do that in the NHL and show up for the
game. I love his composure and confidence, but this is not Val D'Or
\RLuongo's junior team\S. This is the NHL. You've got to prepare
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Luongo, meanwhile, said he went to one apartment and followed
his usual game-day routine from there.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Penguins coach Herb Brooks took the label ``players'
coach'' to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he confronted and shoved a Colorado Avalanche
broadcaster for accusing Penguins left winger Matthew Barnaby of
faking an injury. The confrontation made the 5 o'clock news just
about everywhere, and the NHL has suspended Brooks pending a
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby, for one, was pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect that,'' Barnaby said. ``He's standing up for our
team, and we've got to stand up for him. As a player, it's really
nice to know that your coach goes to bat for you.''
Around the West Maybe goalie Nikolai Khabibulin isn't going to play
for the Phoenix Coyotes this season after all.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck in the fourth month of a holdout from the Coyotes,
Khabibulin signed with the Long Beach Ice Dogs of the International
Hockey League. The minor-league contract leaves room for him to
return to the NHL, but also shows he isn't afraid to miss this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin and the Coyotes are reportedly $2 million apart. The
27-year-old goalie wants $5 million a season, and the Coyotes are
offering $3 million. Khabibulin requested a trade in November, but
the Coyotes have said they have no plans to deal or sign him. They
acquired veteran goalie Sean Burke from the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary Flames defenseman Steve Smith had no feeling in his legs
and arms as he lay on the ice. He had collided with teammate Bobby
Dollas, causing his neck to snap forward and then back.
</P>
<P>
   As he lay there, he said he felt fear.
</P>
<P>
   So when the doctors removed a neck brace in a couple of weeks,
he says he'll begin to contemplate whether he'll retire. He's 36
and has been inundated with injuries the past couple of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is up and around, and that's good to see,'' Flames general
manager Al Coates said. ``But we have that two-week window until we
have to reassess where he is.''
nn
</P>
