<HEADLINE>
PHILLS' LIFE WAS ABOUT MORE THAN BASKETBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody should be so fortunate to have a person like Bobby
Phills in their family.
</P>
<P>
   If every sports franchise was stocked with a Bobby Phills, there
would be no talk of surly attitudes, back talk, trash-talking or
locker-room lawyers. Phills was the epitome of what NBA
commissioner David Stern would like all of his players to be.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Phills' death has been so difficult for players,
coaches and NBA employees to accept. The Charlotte Hornets guard,
who was killed in a car crash Wednesday, was a class act.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an absolutely great, great person, someone I'm
genuinely proud to say has been a very good friend of mine for
several years,'' said Golden State forward Chris Mills, who used to
play in Cleveland with Phills. ``He's the type of person who would
do anything to help a teammate, friend or stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes this tragedy very hard to accept or understand. I
was in complete shock, and now several hours later, I don't want to
believe it happened, especially to someone with as much class and
dignity as Bobby Phills.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed throughout the NBA, as everyone
mourned the loss of a man who was involved in community projects in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Phills' heroics extended off the court. He tried to save a
Charlotte man who caught on fire while riding a motorcycle. Phills
was playing golf nearby, and helped extinguish the flames.
</P>
<P>
   The man eventually died, but his family credited Phills with
giving them a chance to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many pro athletes, Phills was grounded, self-assured and
didn't need sports to validate his life.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fratello, who coached Phills during his first NBA season
(1992-'93), remembers telling Phills he probably didn't have room
for him because the team had 13 guaranteed contracts. Fratello told
Phills to go home and talk it over with his agent.
</P>
<P>
   Some 24 hours later, Phills returned and told Fratello: ``I want
to stick it out here. You're stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Understand something,'' Fratello said. ``He was prepared to be
cut. So many kids wouldn't be able to handle being waived.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bobby thought enough of himself, he was confident enough
in his heart, that if he was out in the street, he would have
succeeded in anything. He was going to be a vet, he was going to be
a doctor. He could have done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Phills' dad, Dr. Bobby Phills, is the dean of agriculture and
home economics at Florida A&AMP;M. He taught his son well.
</P>
<P>
   ``As athletes, you learn that mortality is not promised,'' said
Seattle's Chuck Person, who played in Charlotte with Phills. ``When
something like this happens to our fraternity brothers, it hits
home and puts things in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Phills will be buried today in Baton Rouge, La. During a
memorial service Friday in Charlotte, Phills' 3-year old son, Bobby
Ray III, said it best: ``Daddy is in heaven with the angels.''
\Nsubheds:AROUND THE EAST \Nagatea:Orlando Magic coach Doc Rivers
can appreciate the aggressive attitude Toronto Raptors forward
Charles Oakley brings to the court.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Rivers saw Oakley's value up close when they were
teammates on the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best teammates I ever had,'' Rivers said. ``I
really didn't care for him until I got to New York and saw how
valuable he was. As an opponent, you just thought he was a guy who
would cheap-shot you, but he did it with a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to cheap-shot his own teammates in practice. He did it
to get people ready to play. They love him in Toronto. With him
around, that's why you don't see anyone undercutting Vince Carter.
It won't happen with Charles around.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Indiana Pacers have broken the Los Angeles Lakers'
16-game winning streak, the Pacers have emerged as favorites to win
the East.
</P>
<P>
   In successive games, the Detroit Pistons' Grant Hill scored 42,
42, 31 and 40 points and was selected NBA Player of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep saying we've got the best player in the NBA,'' Pistons
coach Alvin Gentry said. ``Or the best non-center in the NBA for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto guard Vince Carter said it didn't bother him that the
Milwaukee Bucks' Ray Allen received the final 2000 Olympic guard
spot over him last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the first chance Carter got to show the USA Basketball
committee that they made a mistake, he scored a franchise-high 47
points as the Raptors beat Allen and the Bucks, 115-110, Friday.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:AROUND THE WEST \Nagatea:Maybe coaching does have
something to do with a team's success.
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Grizzlies, a team given up for dead under coach
Brian Hill, have been revitalized under Lionel Hollins. The
Grizzlies completed a 4-1 East Coast road trip that included
victories over Miami, New Jersey, Toronto and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what we were a couple of weeks ago, yes, it is
an outstanding road trip,'' said Hollins, who replaced Hill on Dec.
16. ``I don't know if it's the best in NBA history, but it's the
best in the Grizzlies' history and that's all I care about.''
</P>
<P>
   With lots of free time, former Golden State Warriors coach P.J.
Carlesimo has become engaged to girlfriend Caroline Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Timberwolves forward Wally Szczerbiak is back in the
lineup, and the Timberwovles can thank Lisa Giannone for the
assist.
</P>
<P>
   Giannone is a physical therapist in the San Francisco area who
gained recognition for her work in 1997 with San Francisco 49ers
wide receiver Jerry Rice. Szczerbiak, who was activated from the
injured list Tuesday, recently worked with Giannone in the Bay
Area, then followed the rehabilitation program she prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak strengthened the muscles around his sore kneecap,
letting them handle more of the load in running and cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels 10 times better,'' he said. ``No pain at all.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ... Elliott planning return to Spurs by
next month San Antonio Spurs forward Sean Elliott is eager to get
back on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   And the Spurs are eager to have him back.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have been unable to fill his slot, which is why the
defending NBA champions have struggled at times this season.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott recently spent four days in a hospital because of the
flu. But doctors said it was unrelated to the kidney transplant he
had Aug. 16, which has kept him out of action this season.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott would like to start practicing with the Spurs in two
weeks, with his eye on returning near the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be a situation of, `Can I?' '' Elliott said.
``It's, `I'm going to.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott did not participate in any basketball-related activities
from Dec. 7 to Jan. 2. However, he resumed running this past week
and has been overly pleased with his progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been night and day,'' Elliott said after one run.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days ago, Elliott scrimmaged with Derrick Dial and Felton
Spencer, but didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play that long because it didn't take long for me to
hit the wall,'' Elliott said. ``And I hit it head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said he has been cleared by his doctors for ``friendly
contact.'' But Spurs coach Gregg Popovich won't allow Elliott to
scrimmage with the team until he is assured Elliott won't be at
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Popovich said he believes Elliott's chances of
playing this season are ``not very realistic.'' That's not what
Elliott wants to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell whether I can come back or not unless I get out
there and mix it up,'' Elliott said. ``There's been enough of
watching me run line drills. You can't tell whether I'm going to be
able to come back that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like playing basketball. I can sit there and
run on the treadmill a couple miles and run lines, but it's nothing
like playing in a game.''
nn
</P>
