<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-TELESCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED JONES STILL PUTS ON A SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roy Jones Jr. made history Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. He became
the first male member of the Radio City Rockettes.
</P>
<P>
   Barely an hour before he was scheduled to defend the undisputed
light heavyweight title from the challenge of David Telesco, there
was Jones on the stage at Radio City Music Hall, high-kicking with
a dozen Rockettes to open HBO's telecast in a fashion that seemed
to indicate Telesco's presence was not weighing heavily on his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   An entrance that took nearly 15 minutes as Telesco paced in the
ring only added to that impression, and by the time Whitney Houston
had turned the national anthem into a 2-minute-51-second medley,
the challenger was in an angry frenzy. Soon afterward, he was in a
fog that would envelop him all 12 rounds, as he fell victim to
Jones's speed even though the champion had fractured his left wrist
in a motorcycle accident 3 1/2 weeks ago and had rejected the
advice of his father and others who had urged him not to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad even said don't do it, but I said, `Dad, I have to do
it. I've got a big date in New York,' '' Jones said after winning a
one-sided decision with one hand, a decision in which none of the
three judges gave Telesco even one round. ``If I had both hands,
I'd have knocked him out early.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't, but he ended any doubt about what was going to happen
early. In less than a round, Jones proved that the only thing slow
about him was his entrance. From the opening bell, he slammed one
right hand after another into Telesco's cheeks, turning both sides
red in less than three minutes. They were redder 45 minutes later,
when Telesco had to listen to scores of 120-108, 120-107, and
120-107. The Globe card did not dispute those tallies.
</P>
<P>
   Things did not improve for Telesco in Round 2, and by the end of
that round he looked like someone who wished Jones had taken a
little longer to get into the ring. But now he was stuck with Jones
in front of him, knowing he could do little to get rid of him and
not much more to prevent Jones from slapping him with that right
lead whenever he wanted . . . which was often.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently growing bored, Jones spent much of the fifth round in
one of the neutral corners, taunting Telesco and waving him to
attack. When Telesco did, he landed a few body shots but paid a
dear price for it as Jones continued to crack him with those
relentless rights and then mocked him when he tried to return fire.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern continued almost unbroken until Jones finally hurt
Telesco badly with a body shot midway through the 10th round. By
the end of that round, he had Telesco's long-swelling left eye
closing badly and his ribs aching _ but in no more trouble than
he'd been from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Which, frankly, was trouble enough.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, what was weighing heavily on Derrick Jefferson's mind
was the chin of David Izon.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of eight rounds, Jefferson pounded that chin
to no avail, and as the rounds wore on, Jefferson wore down,
building a seemingly insurmountable lead at the same time the gas
was leaking from his tank.
</P>
<P>
   After battering Izon repeatedly without finishing him, Jefferson
had won his seventh straight round, after which his troubles began.
Not long after the eighth round started, he landed one last big
left hook, and with it what was left of his energy leaked out and
he was like a shut-down nuclear reactor. He was devoid of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson did last the rest of the round, but 11 seconds into
the ninth, referee Arthur Mercante Jr. finished what Izon's chin
had started, stopping the fight immediately after a flurry sent
Jefferson falling backward into the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to take his shots, he has to take mine,'' Izon
(25-3, 21 KOs) said later. ``In the seventh, I was thinking of
kneeling down, but I knew this guy would get tired. I endured all
that he gave me. I knew if I endured it, he wouldn't be able to
endure what I would give him later.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had him in the seventh round,'' said Jefferson
(22-1-1). ``After that, I was exhausted and cramping. I just didn't
pace myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the evening, Providence's Brian Barbosa (27-4, 19 KOs)
easily defended his NABO middleweight title by dropping Maurice
Brantley three times in the first round. The final knockdown came
at 2:44 and ended the night early for Brantley (22-3).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
