<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-NETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER LEADS CELTICS ONTO RIGHT ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There's no way to overstate this one.
The Celtics won on the road and they won it thanks to a dominating
performance by the oft-maligned Antoine Walker. He was exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   How exceptional? Well, on his way to the locker room after his
39-point, 11-rebound submission, he was stopped and glad-handed by
actor Danny Aiello, who was a courtside observer. He then passed by
his coach, Rick Pitino, who was talking in the hall and saying,
simply, ``This was, by far, his best offensive and defensive game
of the season.'' He then came into the locker room sat next to
Kenny Anderson, who was telling someone, ``It was probably the best
defensive game I've seen from him since I've been in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Walker not only put up the aforementioned
numbers in the Celtics' nerve-wracking 99-96 victory over the New
Jersey Nets Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, he basically won the game in the final
23 seconds all by himself. With the game tied, 94-94, he got inside
and tipped in an Anderson miss. Then, after a Jersey timeout, he
stole an inexcusably lazy inbounds pass by Kendall Gill and went in
for an uncontested dunk. That settled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question,'' said Walker, who was 17 of 29 from the
field, ``this was a huge win. We're very ecstatic about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Paul Pierce, ``He carried us. It was nice to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics acted like you'd expect them to act after winning
for just the third time in 17 road games: as if they had won the
NBA title. There was an emotional side to this one: The Nets had
seemingly recovered from their horrible start, were starting to win
at home, and were tied in the standings with the Celtics going into
the game.
</P>
<P>
   And, truth be told, the Nets could have won this one. Given the
Celtics' penchant for road collapses, it's almost a surprise they
didn't. Jersey had a 45-21 advantage in free throw attempts but was
undone by 38 percent shooting and 18 turnovers, the last two of
which were ghastly and cost the Nets the game.
</P>
<P>
   After erasing a 5-point deficit in the fourth _ that qualified
as a big lead in this game _ the Nets had the ball with the score
tied at 94. Stephon Marbury (17 points on 5-of-16 shooting) was
starting to feel it; he had scored Jersey's last 5 points,
including a flip from the line to tie it at 94. So what did he do?
He lost the ball. No one made him do it. He just lost the ball.
That gave the Celtics the opening, and Walker snuck in for the tip
of Anderson's miss.
</P>
<P>
   There was still plenty of time left (22.7 seconds), however, and
the Nets called time. Gill then tried to lob a pass into Keith Van
Horn, but Walker anticipated the lazy delivery and made the easy
steal and subsequent dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a free shot and I took it,'' Walker said of his only
steal. ``Finally, a little luck went our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gill, ``The man (Van Horn) was wide open. I didn't see
Walker until the very end. He came out of nowhere. It was a good
play on his part. I give him credit. He suckered us into that
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker was clearly the supernova on this night. Time and again
he would torch the defensively challenged Van Horn, who virtually
all night had to play him straight up. That's almost cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised they did that,'' Pierce said. ``He was taking
it to them every time it was one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics also got some help from their press, which
Pitino has been reluctant to deploy lately. He went with it more
than in the recent past, and it produced big plays. Said Pitino,
``The press has given us a big lift.''
</P>
<P>
   The press forced a big turnover that led to a Pierce steal and
dunk and a 92-87 lead with 3:14 to play. The Celtics didn't score
again for nearly two minutes, by which time New Jersey had tied the
game on two Gill free throws and 3 points by Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics then got lucky. Walker lost the ball in traffic, got
it back, and converted while getting fouled. He missed the free
throw. Marbury then hit his flip to create the final tie.
</P>
<P>
   The press, however, didn't force Marbury's critical turnover. It
didn't force Gill's stupid pass. Those were instances of the Nets
reverting to what they were over the season's first 17 games (2-15)
rather than the last 16 (13-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a focus-and-concentration issue,'' New Jersey
coach Don Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics didn't care. As Anderson put it, ``We just needed a
win on the road, regardless of who we played.''
</P>
<P>
   They got it. They left for Washington a group of happy fellows.
</P>
</TEXT>
