<SLUG> BC-FBN-TAMPABAY-WASHINGTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTCHED KICK ALLOWS TAMPA TO ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ We'll never know if Redskin kicker Brett Conway would
have boomed a 52-yard, game-winning field goal through the
uprights. He never got his toe on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's 15-year veteran lineman Dan Turk botched the snap
and with it went Washington's chance to advance to the NFC
Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay took advantage of three Washington blunders and
rebounded from a 13-0 deficit to advance with a 14-13 win over the
Redskins. Long-maligned as the Sacramento Kings of the NFL, the
Bucs ended a quarter-century of futility with the franchise's first
January victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa's 22-year-old Shaun King threw the game-winning touchdown
pass with 7:29 left in the game and became the first rookie to win
an NFL playoff game since Pat Haden beat the Cowboys for the Los
Angeles Rams in 1976. The Sun King, now 5-1 as a starter since
taking over for Trent Dilfer (shoulder), was stifled for 2 1/2
quarters, then delighted the patient 65,835 with two touchdown
drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he was pressing a little bit,'' said Tampa coach Tony
Dungy, referring to his quarterback's 4-for-16 start. ``It was just
a matter of waiting for him to make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa's first TD came on a highlight-reel pinball run by
snowplow fullback Mike Alstott. King floated a 1-yard TD pass to
John Davis for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   In the nation's capital, this will be the one that got away. The
Redskins smothered the Bucs for the first 40 minutes, but the tide
reversed when John Lynch picked off Brad Johnson with five minutes
to play in the third quarter. A Johnson fumble led to the second
Tampa touchdown, but the game was still winnable.
</P>
<P>
   On their final, fateful drive, the Redskins took over on their
38 with 3:05 left. They moved the ball to the Bucs' 33, then lined
up for the field goal on fourth-and-3 with 1:17 left. Conway had
already drilled a 48-yarder, and this time had the wind at his
back.
</P>
<P>
   But Turk's snap bounced a couple of times before it got to
holder Johnson. Johnson had no choice but to scramble and was
sacked before he could get off a throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I short-armed it,'' Turk said of the snap that bounced the
Redskins right out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad never had a chance,'' Washington coach Norv Turner said.
``The timing was gone. One guy didn't get the job done, not the
whole special-teams unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was Tampa's ninth in 10 games. The Bucs could host the
NFC Championship Game next Sunday if the Vikings beat the Rams
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we wouldn't mind ugly wins all the way to the Super
Bowl,'' said Dungy.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins had the NFL's second-ranked offense and did not
score fewer than 17 points in any game this season. But Saturday,
Washington's offense failed to score a touchdown and only gained 26
yards on 27 plays in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   It often takes the deliberate Bucs some time to get rolling. The
first quarter was a 0-0 snorefest. It was like a Bruins scrimmage
or any Revolution game. Punters Mark Royals (Tampa Bay) and Matt
Turk took turns in a boring battle for field position. The Bucs
managed only one first down in the period and the vaunted running
duo of Warrick Dunn and Alstott combined for 12 yards on six
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Thrills were sparse in the second quarter, particularly for
Tampa fans. In the middle of the quarter, the Redskins started a
drive at Tampa Bay's 44 and lurched to the 10 on seven plays before
Conway kicked a 28-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   There were 11 punts in the first half, six by the conservative
Bucs. First-half scoring droughts were a Buccaneer trademark in
1999 and the locals had faith the hometown team would score in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   But it Washington that scored first. Brian Mitchell, the
Redskins' all-purpose runner, took the second-half kickoff and went
100 yards up the right sideline for the game's first touchdown. The
highlight of the run to paydirt was a stiff-arm to the face of
Tampa kicker Martin Gramatica. It was the longest kickoff return in
NFL postseason history, topping 99-yard gamebreaker by Green Bay's
Desmond Howard in the 1997 Super Bowl (remember that one?), and the
first allowed by Tampa in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   There were already questions about King's ability to put points
on the board when he was picked off by Darrell Green with 10
minutes left in the third. Conway converted the game's first
turnover into a 48-yard field goal to take a 13-0 lead with 8:10
left in the third period as Raymond James Stadium went silent. The
favorites were in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington committed the next two turnovers (interception,
fumble) and the Bucs turned them into a pair of touchdowns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
