<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ Even tying the game in the final minutes of
regulation could not end the Kings' misery, which passed the
one-month mark Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It gave the Kings a point in the standings, which is no small
feat these days, but Luc Robitaille's goal in the final minutes of
regulation only led to an overtime score by Jeff Friesen and a 3-2
loss to the San Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dec. 14, the Kings are 2-10-1, dropping them into a tie
with Calgary for the seventh playoff spot in the Western
Conference. If the Mighty Ducks, who lost again, weren't playing so
badly, this slump could be far more devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I look at is the point we got tonight,'' said Jamie Storr,
who returned to the Kings net after missing a month with a
concussion. ``We were in a spot to come away with nothing. If we
were horrible, that is one thing. But we are still playing hard and
knowing that makes this a little less frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The new overtime rules award a point for regulation ties even if
the team loses in overtime. But there was little reward for the
Kings' power play, which was 0 for 6 until Robitaille's goal.
</P>
<P>
   And they had little answer for the Sharks' top player, Owen
Nolan, who scored twice, including a short-handed goal on the first
shot Storr has faced since Dec. 15 against the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had some momentum when they killed off a five-on-three
penalty to Brad Chartrand and Mattias Norstrom in the second
period. And they were looking at a five-minute man advantage after
a high-stick penalty to former King Tony Granato, who bloodied
Norstrom's upper lip. But less than three minutes later, Rob Blake
was whistled for interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blake was the best guy on the ice tonight; he played just a
terrific game,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``But we need to get more
out of our top people.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes Ziggy Palffy, who did not know if he could play
until testing his lower back in pregame warmups. Palffy had an
assist on Robitaille's goal with 1:33 left in regulation, but he
only had two shots and was on the ice for both of Nolan's goals.
</P>
<P>
   While Nolan set the tone early, the Kings' inability to counter
hurt. Without Jozef Stumpel, out at least two weeks with a knee
injury and Glen Murray, who could be sidelined three weeks with a
bruised chest muscle, the first and second lines were ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Smolinski, the club's leading scorer with 38 points,
centers the second line with Murray. He already was playing without
his other winger Donald Audette and was limited to just one shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' first goal came from Chartrand, who is getting
playing time after having some injuries of his own.
</P>
<P>
   His goal pleased Andy Murray and not just because Chartrand is a
personal favorite. Chartrand scored it after getting flattened by
Andy Sutton in the Kings' end. Chartrand got off the ice and
streaked toward the Sharks' end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not use the word frustrated about what we are going
through,'' Murray said. ``I would say disappointed. Frustrated
means were are confused and we don't know what we are doing out
there. There is no problem with the effort this team is giving.''
</P>
<P>
   He is pleased enough to give the team today off despite its
third consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   But scoring remains a problem. In the Kings' first three
power-play opportunities, they had just one shot and put themselves
in a deep hole by falling behind 2-0 to Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough greeting,'' said Storr, who allowed the first
one 1:36 into the game. ``But things got better from there.
Really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
