<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN17-COX     01-16 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite track record, Norwood risks status over patients' rights
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He's a card carrying member of the National Rifle
Association, and proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   He's fiercely opposed to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks 10 percent of the federal budget should go back into
taxpayers' pockets.
</P>
<P>
   He will go to his grave admiring Ronald Reagan above all other
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   So, why are Republican leaders so mad at Charlie Norwood?
</P>
<P>
   It's not just because the Georgia congressman took on his party
leadership on patients' rights. It's because he beat them. And he
did it by building a bipartisan coalition in concert with his
liberal Democratic co-sponsor, Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.).
</P>
<P>
   The Norwood-Dingell bill, which gives patients the right to sue
managed care companies for making medical decisions that wrongly
deny care, passed the House last year, to the embarrassment of the
GOP leadership, which opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie has a strong sense of right and wrong, but he's paying
a heavy political price for it,'' says Dingell, an unabashed
admirer of Norwood's political courage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Norwood defeated incumbent Democrat Don Johnson in
Georgia's 10th District as part of Newt Gingrich's Republican
revolution. On the litmus-test issues for Republicans then and now,
Norwood qualifies as the perfect poster boy, someone who could be
counted on to toe the party line. He grew up in Valdosta, graduated
from Georgetown dental school and served in Vietnam, where he won a
Combat Medical Badge and two Bronze Stars for his actions in
combat. Somebody in his family has served in every American war, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, war and football shaped much of who Norwood is. He
played offensive tackle for the late Wright Bazemore, the legendary
coach at Valdosta High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't making A's as much as if you could tackle good,''
Norwood recalls.
</P>
<P>
   And when he tackled his party hierarchy last year and won, he
hailed it as a battle akin to taking Hamburger Hill. But Norwood
barely had time to savor the 275-151 victory before his friend,
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, slapped him down by refusing to
appoint him to the House-Senate conference committee where the
final battle will be fought. The Senate health care reform bill
doesn't include the controversial right-to-sue provision.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Norwood has nothing but kind words for Hastert: ``Maybe
he didn't want to throw me into that brier patch.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dingell makes no bones about the insult. The House rules
call for a majority of conference committee members who reflect the
House position. Yet only one of Hastert's appointees voted in the
end for the Norwood-Dingell provision.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it's Norwood's sense of moral right, a favorite GOP
buzzphrase, that led him to risk bucking his party. He argues that
insurers should be held accountable for their decisions, just like
ordinary folks.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood is convinced that direct accountability for
decison-making that affects people's lives is inherent in
conservative philosophy, and he still regrets that the party didn't
jump on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want big government making health care decisions
for you, why would you want big corporations doing it,'' he says.
He doesn't disavow his Southern populist roots.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood longs to spend more time on his 40 acres along the
Savannah River near Augusta, where he has ``about the best
smokehouse and venison in Georgia.'' He saves Sundays for his
family _ including two small granddaughters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he knows the biggest battle of his political life is
looming, and that a lot of his staunchest opponents are on his own
team.
</P>
<P>
   The mild-mannered Norwood, however, is tougher on the inside
than many people know. But Dingell knows.
</P>
<P>
   It usually takes a certain ``ripening'' to frame a conscience
while in Congress, Dingell says. But Norwood came with one built
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's conservatives like Charlie,'' Dingell says, ``who will
provide the leadership to eliminate the mean spiritedness around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
