A7443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN17-COX     01-16 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Digital manipulation of images on CBS news shows hurts
credibility
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When Time magazine was caught digitally doctoring
O.J. Simpson's picture on its cover to make him appear menacing,
the deception was properly condemned as unethical.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, ABC was properly skewered in 1994 for using fakery to
make viewers believe that Cokie Roberts, wrapped in a coat, was
giving a report on the scene at Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Roberts was standing inside the ABC News Washington
Bureau in front of a projection of the Capitol behind her. ABC News
anchor Peter Jennings introduced Roberts as reporting from Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Purposeful deception of readers and viewers undermines
credibility of serious journalism. Such deceit must be vigorously
censured to maintain the public's trust. Serious journalists must
bend over backward to give accurate, truthful reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Time and ABC apologized for their deceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The other day the New York Times revealed that CBS has hired a
company to digitally change scenes, which it has been doing
regularly on ``The Early Show'' and its newsmagazine ``48 Hours.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, the network used digital deception in the
scene shown behind CBS News anchor Dan Rather.
</P>
<P>
   A big billboard in Times Square behind Rather during the Dec. 30
and 31 live ``CBS Evening News'' telecasts advertised CBS with its
logo.
</P>
<P>
   That CBS billboard wasn't there. It was a digital fake. Worse,
CBS used the fake CBS billboard to cover up a real NBC-sponsored
sign and a Budweiser advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, when the CBS trickery was uncovered, Eric Shapiro,
director of the ``CBS Evening News''; Andrew Heyward, president of
CBS News; and Leslie Moonves, CEO of CBS Television, defended the
practice and promised to do more of it.
</P>
<P>
   This could be an example of desperate people taking desperate
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Early Show'' is stuck in third place in the morning
news-entertainment network contest. The ``CBS Evening News'' also
is in trouble in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   CBS hired Princeton Video Image to help plant digital branding
into its broadcasts. Since Nov. 1, CBS has been using this service
to put CBS logos and counterfeit CBS billboards in live scenes to
make viewers believe the logos and billboards actually are on
buildings, a horse-drawn carriage, a landmark fountain and other
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to do things without ruining the
neighborhood,'' Steve Friedman, executive producer of ``The Early
Show,'' told the New York Times. ``And we haven't even scratched
the surface of its uses yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, the director of ``CBS Evening News,'' said, ``The
technique, I find, works best if you put it someplace where there
is intended to be something.''
</P>
<P>
   That's profound. If you are going to deceive your audience, do
it where you can get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward described the digital deception as ``a whimsical and
creative way to display our logo in various and unlikely places.''
</P>
<P>
   The CBS News president said the digitally faked CBS sign that
covered the real NBC Jumbotron on Times Square was ``an extension
of electronic signage,'' which is lame.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves, Heyward's boss, said, ``Any time there's an NBC logo up
in our network we will block it again.'' Later he attempted to
downplay his call for dirty tricks by saying that if the NBC logo
was part of a news story _ ``if somebody used an NBC logo to commit
a murder _ we wouldn't cut it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rather, who knew about the fake images implanted in the live
scene behind him, did not object at the time. Now he says, ``I did
not grasp the ethical implication of this, and that was wrong on my
part.'' At the very least, Rather said, CBS should have pointed out
to viewers what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, knock off the deception and dirty tricks. It drags
us all down.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
