<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX     01-16 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motor safety rarely has the pedestrian in equation
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ His name was Boomer, short for Boomerang. The
part-Siamese porch cat would disappear for days but always return.
Then one night, after becoming such a fixture that he'd ceased
wandering, he didn't come home. I found him dead in the beam of a
street light, and cursed the imbecile who wouldn't slow down on our
lightly traveled neighborhood street.
</P>
<P>
   The other day while driving, I had to brake for a man with
weathered skin and a limp. Either he was ignoring the ``don't
walk'' or the words didn't translate. Had I plowed over his body no
one would have looked askance at me. He'd have been in the wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, though. When I looked at the pedestrian, for a half a
second I didn't see a man. I saw Boomer.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrians get confused. They make bad judgment calls. Boomer
should have known better than to get caught between headlights. So,
too, this man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proceed at your own risk,'' we all know when the issue is
safety on our streets. But pedestrians, particularly the young and
distracted, don't always weigh the risk.
</P>
<P>
   We do a miserable job in tending to their safety, whether it is
in providing sidewalks to get them to school or instructing them
how to walk safely. If you have no sidewalk, walk on the shoulder
facing the nearest oncoming lane _ to make eye contact with the car
closest to you. This is serious. Understand?
</P>
<P>
   Similarly we send youngsters out on bicycles without instructing
them that bikes are vehicles just like cars. Ride with traffic on
the far right side. Riding opposite traffic courts tragedy. Drivers
turning into traffic aren't expecting a bicycle to come hurtling at
them from the far right.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to convey these simple rules is a serious social
shortcoming. But another thing we don't do is internalize the
precautions drivers need to avoid killing a child who gets caught
in the crosswalk, or one whose bike wobbles into harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Some tragedies are unavoidable. City arteries are meant for
conveying traffic at a robust speed. But neighborhood streets are
meant to be shared, to have cars backing out of driveways, balls
bouncing out of the front yard, 8-year-olds trying two wheels
without training wheels.
</P>
<P>
   People who drive through neighborhood streets too often do it
oblivious to physical laws about stopping in time.
</P>
<P>
   A car traveling at 40 mph is going 60 feet per second. Assuming
reaction time to be 2.5 seconds, the vehicle will travel 150 feet
before even an alert driver hits the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   This makes 40 mph on a neighborhood street a deadly speed.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian study found that the average driver traveling at
40 mph who has a pedestrian 100 feet straight ahead will still be
traveling 38 mph should they hit. The pedestrian is as good as
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The same study says that the average driver who is going 25 mph
will have stopped in those 100 feet.
</P>
<P>
   So a rule of thumb for motorists, alongside the rules we must
drum into the heads of pedestrians and bicyclists, is to go no
faster than 25 mph on a neighborhood, nonartery street. That speed
is better.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we can all think of nonartery streets that get treated like
arteries. So do police. It would be useful for police to do a
little ``consciousness-raising'' along those stretches to remind
motorists where they're driving.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for hope in this regard. Every time I take the
boys to school in the morning, I go through the stretch of New Road
fronting Crestview Elementary. To a remarkable extent, motorists
doggedly observe the 20 mph limit and the flashing yellow lights.
Or at least the numbskulls who want to ignore the lights have no
way to speed on, because both lanes have slowed to a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   We all need reminders, either by flashing light or by ingrained
images of the innocent. Mine has four legs.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
