<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES17-COX     01-16 2783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ordinary life in America a haven for Kosovars
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If for a fleeting moment, they feel more like hostages
than refugees, they need only remember what landed them in this
poor southeast Atlanta neighborhood between a prison and a
junkyard.
</P>
<P>
   Hate.
</P>
<P>
   Oppression.
</P>
<P>
   War.
</P>
<P>
   Now, husbands are off to work, children at school, older sons
and daughters out getting driver's licenses or at jobs or looking
for jobs, and the Kosovar women stay behind. Pounding bread dough
on the kitchen table, washing socks in the bathtub, listening to TV
shows they can't really follow. Most hesitate to leave their modest
apartments and venture into their neighborhood because of their
limited
</P>
<P>
   English and fear for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the women have each other for comfort, companionship,
conversation. Gathering in their plain living rooms, they swap
pieces of information about their children's schools, a job lead or
another supermarket discovery. Vanilla-scented air freshener to
spray in the bathroom, can you believe it?
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosova, I was afraid for my daughter when she left for
school. I would never know if she would return home alive,''
Sheribane Jusufi (SHAY-rah-bana You-SU-fee) says through her
daughter, Adelina, who uses the Albanian pronunciation customary in
Kosovo, the southern province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Adelina serves as an interpreter one recent evening when several
women gather at the Jusufi apartment. ``Maybe the policemen will
kill her.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``policemen'' were Serbian, intimidation their job.
Beginning in 1989, the police and other armed Serb forces
systematically stripped Albanian Kosovars of most of their jobs,
schools, mosques, government institutions and, most thoroughly,
their dignity.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, they endured interrogation, arbitrary arrests and
torture. Then the harassment erupted
</P>
<P>
   into full-fledged war and a chaotic human retreat. Almost 20,000
Kosovars a day streamed across borders to safety, overwhelming
refugee camps and carrying tales of horror and narrow escapes:
Serbs pouring gasoline near them and threatening to strike a match.
Soldiers holding guns to their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Family history stolen with torches to homes. It's a lot to think
about, let alone live through.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the nine families forming the tiny Albanian village
in an Atlanta apartment complex do not mind concerning themselves
with the mundane routine of the working poor in America.
</P>
<P>
   Getting up at 4 a.m. to catch a van shuttle to a dismal factory
job in Lawrenceville, Ga. Riding a bicycle
</P>
<P>
   home at 1 a.m. after an eight-hour shift washing dishes. Waiting
for six hours at Grady Memorial Hospital to see a doctor.
Scrutinizing prices and calculating savings on the endless cereal
offerings at Kroger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a freedom country now and we do not have to be
afraid,'' says Hanemsha Berkolli, 48, a mother of five. ``And the
money situation is better here than in Kosova.''
</P>
<P>
   TACKLING ENGLISH
</P>
<P>
   Refugee: a person who flees from home or country to seek refuge
elsewhere, as in a time of war or of political or religious
persecution. (Webster's New World College Dictionary)
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after the Kosovars arrived, the transition is still
difficult. Their new and confusing world sometimes seems to spin
around them. They've come to rely on their children, who are much
quicker students of English, to help with grocery shopping, talking
to doctors and answering the phone. During the summer, volunteers
spent many hours teaching English to families, and the learning
accelerated for children once they started school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are doing well but I worry about depression with
the adults,'' volunteer Lyn Almon says. ``The ones who don't have
jobs aren't progressing with English and they seem stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 51 Kosovar Albanians at the apartment complex arrived
knowing English: Adelina Jusufi, 17, youngest in a family of four
children, and Remzi Grajqevci, (RAM-see Gri-JEFF-see) 38, married
and a father of two young daughters. Grajqevci eventually was hired
by Catholic Social Services as a
</P>
<P>
   refugee caseworker, while Adelina is often called upon by the
families to unravel mysteries ranging from instant coffee to
prescription instructions.
</P>
<P>
   What's in this brown plastic bottle? (Hydrogen peroxide.) Why do
I have to keep signing papers my children bring home from school?
Can you read this government form to me?
</P>
<P>
   ``I started learning English when I was 12 in Kosova,'' Adelina
says. ``Maybe, I thought, I would like to go to college here, but
never did I ever think my family would be living in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   SO MUCH LEFT BEHIND
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not look back, and do not dream about the future either. .
. . Your duty, your reward, your destiny are here and now.'' _ Dag
Hammarskjold, former United Nations secretary-general
</P>
<P>
   Shoes pile up outside doors of Kosovar dwellings. Tiny stuffed
animals given to the kids by soldiers at Fort Dix, N.J., sit atop
donated TV sets. Report cards, drug prescription records and
telephone
</P>
<P>
   numbers get neatly tucked away in table drawers and hanging
baskets. Basic food items _ flour, salt, sugar, eggs by the two
dozen _ line kitchen shelves and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   But what's absent is most noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   No wedding photos, no family heirlooms, no framed artwork, no
well-worn blanket draping a chair. ``I used to have many, many
plants in my home in Kosova,'' Rukije (RU-kee-a) Berkolli said one
Sunday when a visitor surprises her with an ivy plant wrapped in
green aluminum. ``But we can't take nothing, nothing when we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Half the Albanians in the complex are from the Berkolli-Kaleshi
families, headed by four men _ two brothers, a cousin and a
brother-in-law. As is common in Kosovo, the extended clan all lived
near one another in Pristina, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   A TOUGH NEIGHBORHOOD
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Berkollis were among the first Kosovar families to
arrive in Georgia and to be placed by Catholic Social Services, one
of several metro Atlanta resettlement agencies assisting refugees.
Because many had large families and wished to live near relatives,
the apartment complex was the best choice, said Rebecca Kloss of
Catholic Social Services. Its rent is low, $520 monthly, and the
complex is near supermarkets and public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But with the low-income, transient neighborhood comes the usual
problems of crime and concern. Four donated bicycles were stolen
one by one from a family this summer; another refugee woke up to
find that vandals had broken into his used Jeep and jammed the
ignition in a futile attempt to steal it. And there's constant
worry about drug dealing in the streets that form loops around the
clusters of two-story brick duplex apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most say they wouldn't want to live elsewhere in Atlanta
just yet, especially if it means not being
</P>
<P>
   surrounded by other Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, all our brothers and sisters are in the apartment
complex,'' said Feride (Fa-RE-dee) Berkolli, sister-in-law to
Hanemsha and the mother of a son and daughter. ``We want to stay
together.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the families started, resettlement agencies picked up
rent and other expenses for the first three months. The families
began learning English and other basic skills, such as using
American currency, getting around Atlanta by bus and rail and where
and how to shop for food. They applied for Social Security cards,
food stamps and Medicaid to cover health care.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny steps slowly are adding up. Getting a factory job making
car window parts, then a better opportunity working at a restaurant
preparing catered food. For some wives and adult daughters, picking
up part-time jobs at a hotel cleaning rooms. Passing the Georgia
driver's license test. Learning to navigate Atlanta's maze of
streets behind the wheel of a donated car or a cheap, used one.
Getting children registered for school. Opening checking accounts.
Mastering a MARTA bus schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after six months, some families are reaching goals: better
jobs, better language skills, more independence, less frustration.
Children are excelling in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their teachers tell me they are making progress way beyond and
faster than their Hispanic and Asian counterparts,'' said Julie
Jabaley, 31, an Atlanta resident who's devoted countless hours to
helping the families since July.
</P>
<P>
   Jabaley's name is one the families know well, along with
Maryellen LeDuc, Christina Risco-Turner, Michael Gaertner, Jerry
Pace, Greg Paye, Mohamad Muataz Malak of Muslim Social Services and
Lyn Almon, Tom Reichert and Lenora Lockwood with downtown Sacred
Heart Church. Collectively, they are known as ``the volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   AN ARMY OF VOLUNTEERS
</P>
<P>
   None knew one another before they started visiting the Kosovar
families nearly every day, taking them shopping for clothes,
teaching them to hunt for bargains at supermarkets, shuttling them
to dental and doctor appointments, helping them with everything
from finding a job to making instant mashed potatoes. They've also
been responsible for the family's few moments of worry-free joy:
turning their boys and girls into princesses and pirates for
Halloween; organizing outings to Braves and Hawks games and pizza
joints; laughing over the Thanksgiving misinterpretation of
``Thanks, give me.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the small army of volunteers, some families say they
would be much worse off because promises made in refugee camps have
yet to unfold in the Land of Opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many were told misleading and inaccurate information when
making a decision about whether to come to the United States,''
Jabaley says. ``They lived pretty much a middle-class existence and
here they're virtual paupers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grajqevci family, whom Jabaley helps, also compare their
lives to Kosovar families elsewhere who were matched with churches
or neighborhoods. Because one group of people is assisting one
family instead of one individual helping a community of families,
``it gives them a huge advantage,'' Jabaley says. ``Some sponsors
raise enough money to pay rent for a year, or they've found them
jobs before the families even arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything is relative. All the Kosovar refugees in Georgia
have enjoyed far more attention, donations and support than any
other previous group of persecuted people. And, of course, the here
and now trumps the past, no matter what hand of charitable cards
they hold.
</P>
<P>
   Most challenging for the volunteers is finding tolerable jobs
for the refugees, who were accountants, teachers, postal workers.
Halim Kaleshi, 35, worked as a mason at construction jobs in
Kosovo, a job that shouldn't be hard to replicate in booming
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't have a way to get to construction sites, so he
took the first job that came along to support his wife and three
children, ages, 8, 4 and 1. It was at Auto Ventshade Co., a car
parts assembly plant in Lawrenceville where four of the Kosovar men
still work. A co-worker from outside the neighborhood
</P>
<P>
   picked them up, charging $25 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job was easy, but I couldn't learn English there,''
Kaleshi said. ``Everyone speak Vietnamese.''
</P>
<P>
   Making ends meet was another problem. Kaleshi's wages, $8.30 an
hour, had to cover $520 rent, $200 for utilities and the phone,
$100 monthly car insurance, gas, diapers, other drugstore items and
food not bought with $320 in food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Kaleshi and his wife, Shyhrete, (Sur-RAY-tah)
found full-time jobs in the cafeterias of the College Park school
district. The pay is 30 cents an hour less than the factory job,
but now there are two paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the refugees, he sends whatever money he can to
relatives in Kosovo to help them rebuild and get through the winter
with heat and food. He wants to fly back to Kosovo to visit his
mother and siblings in the spring. The working parents have
discovered the practical side of not having a
</P>
<P>
   grandmother next door: $600 a month now goes to a baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   THE RIGHT DECISION?
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have learned in Bosnia, when conflict ends, the more
difficult job of winning the peace begins.'' _ Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright
</P>
<P>
   As they do every year, Albanians celebrated Flag Day on Nov. 28
in recognition of Albania's 1912 declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
   In Fayetteville, 250 metro area Kosovar Albanians gathered at
Providence United Methodist Church to sing songs, laugh at skits
and pose with the Albanian flag, which is dominated by a two-headed
black eagle.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, similar joyful scenes unfolded across the
countryside, villages and cities. But just after midnight, a crowd
in Pristina pulled three Serbs, a man and two women, from their car
and assaulted them before hundreds of witnesses. The man was shot
dead and the women sustained multiple injuries,
</P>
<P>
   according to a NATO statement that warned that ``incidents like
this can only stand in the way of Kosovo's development into a
democratic society.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, civil war is no longer tearing Kosovo apart.
Peacekeeping NATO personnel numbering 50,000 are seeing to that. Or
trying to.
</P>
<P>
   But not a day goes by without reports of Serbian homes torched,
Albanian men shot in bars, caches of grenades and automatic weapons
seized, fingers blown off detonating mines and revenge killings on
both sides of the long-simmering feud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a tense situation,'' relief organizer Ramiz Duka
recently told a gathering of Atlanta's Kosovar refugees. ``And
everyone is saying they are not the guilty ones. Everyone is
suddenly looking innocent now.''
</P>
<P>
   An Albanian who's lived in the United States since 1983, Duka is
coordinating relief efforts to rebuild mosques and cultural centers
in Kosovo with the group Albanian-Islamic Cultural Center of Staten
Island. Every two months, he accompanies huge donations of food and
clothing to the region, seeing firsthand the destruction and dire
living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That country is devastated. You just can't believe it,'' he
says. ``In the mountainous region of Drenica,
</P>
<P>
   every single home is destroyed. People are trying to survive
living outside but they won't be able to. NATO thought it would
have eight months to rebuild homes and do it after this winter but
people returned so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, 90 percent of the Albanians who fled Kosovo have
returned, NATO officials estimate. Nearly one-third of the 365,000
homes in Kosovo sustained major damage, leaving 840,000 people in
need of shelter. More than 200 international aid groups are
frantically working under the direction of Atlanta-based CARE USA
to deliver shelter kits, food, firewood and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected that many people to return so quickly to
Kosovo,'' Duka says. ``NATO wasn't in place to start helping them
rebuild, so they started themselves. I've never seen a will to go
back and to have peace and such love for their country like the
Kosovars (have).''
</P>
<P>
   Among Georgia's 600 Kosovar refugees, the feeling is the same.
It's evident in their faces when they're
</P>
<P>
   asked whether they will stay or go back home. The question
brings a range of answers from ``I'm never going back'' to ``Maybe
in five years'' to ``Just to visit, no stay.''
</P>
<P>
   It also invariably triggers images of their relatives _
brothers, sisters, aging parents and others they try to call every
week in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sad for my mother,'' says Rukije Berkolli, 42, a mother
of five, ages 7 to 20. She pulls out an old black-and-white photo
from a plastic wallet sleeve, the only item she grabbed in March
when the ``leave or be killed'' order from Serbs started her
family's journey to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe her 62-year-old mother will die before she sees her again.
Maybe they'll save enough money for a visit next summer to check on
her mom and whatever is left of their house. Or maybe she and her
husband, Mitat, will give up on life improving here and return to
the mountainous countryside that is ravaged but at least familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll stay and she'll see her sons, Besim, Selatin and
Nexhmedin, go off to college or her little girl, Nerimane, grow up
and become CNN's next Christiane Amanpour. Maybe this is the best
place for her oldest child, Behar, deaf since birth and now working
at Heaping Bowl and Brew restaurant in East Atlanta, to find a
career to match his sharp mind and outgoing personality.
</P>
<P>
   But right now in her apartment home, the soup needs stirring,
the phone is ringing and her sister-in-law just dropped by.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
