<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-ELECTION (Santiago, Chile) _ Chileans go to the polls to
choose their next president. The race between conservative Joaquin
Lavin and socialist Ricardo Lagos is expected to be close. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI-MANDELA (Arusha, Tanzania) _ Nelson Mandela began his
duties Sunday as the new mediator for the conflict in Burundi with
an extraordinary attack on the nation's warring leaders _ seated in
a long row in front of him _ for failing their people and shaming
all of Africa. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINE (Jerusalem) _ Israel is delaying the handover
of land on Thursday because it can't get ready in time. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECTIONS (Undated) _ There is a Sunday deadline for the
United Nations to name the leader of a team that would restart arms
inspections in Iraq, but there has been a deadlock over who will be
chosen. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EPA-BIOTECH-CROPS (Undated) _ In a decision anxiously awaited by
farmers, environmentalists and the biotech industry, the
Environmental Protection Agency on Friday announced a series of new
regulations to be enacted this spring for the planting of Bt corn,
a plant genetically engineered to produce its own insecticide. The
new measures were viewed by many as an acknowledgment by the agency
of the rising concern over the safety of biotech crops. By Carol
Kaesuk Yoon.
