<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-GORE-0117     01-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GORE-0117 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE SETS RACIAL HEALING AS TOP PRIORITY
 &HT;    with GORE Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN, N.H. _ An exhausted Al Gore peered out of his frosted
car window at the darkened, snow-covered mountains of New
Hampshire's frigid North Country.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president, who had just completed a long day of
campaigning with three hours of questioning by several hundred
residents of this small mill town, quickly warmed to a reporter's
questions on the legacy of the late Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and
his own commitment to improving race relations in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Healing is within our reach,'' Gore told Cox Newspapers as his
motorcade cautiously worked its way along an icy highway through
these mountains late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing his scheduled appearance today (Monday) at
Atlanta's Ebenezer Baptist Church to celebrate the national holiday
honoring King, Gore vowed that if he is elected president there
will be ``no higher priority'' in his administration than promoting
that healing.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit to Atlanta, Gore will unveil administration
plans to seek $1.5 million in new federal funding to help preserve
the King birthplace and burial site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important part of America's heritage and history and
has educational and inspirational power to pass on to each new
generation lessons about the life of Dr. King and the message of
Dr. King,'' Gore said of the preservation effort.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passing of more than three decades since his
assassination, King's message is ``as powerful as ever and needs to
be heard now more than ever before,'' the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Why now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because healing is within our reach and because the rest of
the world is in a transformative process with so many other peoples
looking to the United States for signs of hope that they can
transcend racial and ethnic and religious differences and embrace
the highest common denominator of the human spirit,'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said President Clinton's race initiative, a year-long
``national conversation'' focusing on racial reconciliation efforts
in local communities, was ``a good beginning.'' He said that, ``if
entrusted with the presidency,'' he would continue that effort,
though ``not exactly in the same form.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Gore also said:
</P>
<P>
   It is ``unfair'' for Bill Bradley, his rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, to accuse him of racial politics in the
1988 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``just indefensible'' for the Confederate flag to fly atop
any public building.
</P>
<P>
   Although was ``deeply offended'' by recent comments of Atlanta
Braves pitcher John Rocker about minorities, gays and foreigners,
Rocker still has a chance to ``kind of turn this thing around''
with people like Andrew Young and Hank Aaron on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action programs will ``stand the test of the fair
judgment of the American people'' in the upcoming presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   Former Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Colin Powell has ``earned
the right'' to not be held ``personally accountable'' for
Republican Party ``shortcomings'' on race-related matters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's vow to use the bully pulpit of the White House to ``bring
our people together'' comes in the wake of recent accusations that
his past and present pursuits of the Democratic Party's
presidential nomination have involved racial demagoguery.
</P>
<P>
   The latest occurred just days ago when Bradley , Gore's sole
opponent in the primaries, charged that Gore is responsible for
first interjecting Willie Horton into the national political
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was misleading and unfair,'' Gore said of Bradley's charges
about Horton, a black Massachusetts prisoner who became a symbol of
racial politics 12 years ago in then-Vice President George Bush's
campaign against Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Horton was among the violent offenders who were furloughed under
a program initiated by Dukakis as governor of Massachusetts in the
1980s. During the furlough, Horton committed rape.
</P>
<P>
   During a 19888 debate, Gore criticized the furlough program. But
he never mentioned Horton or his race. In fact, ``I didn't know his
name,'' Gore said during the interview. ``I talked about the
program as a whole without reference to race in any way, shape or
form.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's campaign manager, the late Lee Atwater, vowed before
the 1988 general election to ``make Willie Horton Michael Dukakis's
running mate.'' And GOP activists subsequently ran television ads
critical of Dukakis that featured Horton's threatening police mug
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis has come to Gore's defense by chastising Bradley for
asserting that Gore was to blame for Horton's emergence in the 1988
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``To suggest that Al Gore was responsible for this is not only
wrong but quite unfair,'' Dukakis said. ``The guy who's responsible
for it was George Bush, and we all know what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also has come under fire from Powell, the former chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, for recent comments by Gore campaign
manager Donna Brazile accusing the Republican Party of racial
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Powell accused Brazile, who is also black, of playing ``the race
card'' by saying Republicans would rather have their pictures taken
with black children than feed them.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, when asked if Powell should be called upon to defend
the GOP's positions on racial matters, said the general has
``earned the right to focus on his 'America's Challenge' program,''
which promotes volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Powell has already ``expressed enough disagreement
with some of the policies of his party,'' specifically, its
opposition to affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   `` I don't feel the need to try to make him a spokesman for the
shortcomings of the Republican Party,'' Gore said of Powell. ``I
think he is a great man. I disagree with his membership in the
Republican Party, but I think he has a right to do that without
being held personally accountable for all the mistakes that they
make.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard can be reached at scotts(at)coxnews.com or (202)
887-8332.
</P>
<P>
   (For a complete transcript of Cox Newspapers' interview with
Vice President Al Gore, along with in-depth political reporting,
opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox News Campaign 2000 Web site:
http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
