<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-MCBAIN-IS-HUNTER-AZR &LR;      01-16 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCBAIN-IS-HUNTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MYSTERY WRITER, NOMS DE PLUME CAN'T COVER UP TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     BOOK REVIEW: 
 ``THE LAST DANCE: A NOVEL  OF THE 87TH PRECINCT'' 
 By Ed McBain  (Simon &AMP; Schuster, Inc. $25.00) 
 
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evan Hunter is Ed McBain.
</P>
<P>
   He's also been Richard Marsten, Curt Cannon, Hunt Collins and
Ezra Hannon.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Salvatore A. Lombino. With his father's blessings,
he legally changed his birth name to Hunter when he began to
publish in the early '50s because at that time there was still much
bigotry against Italian-Americans and it extended to publishing.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Hunter's multiple-name reality is like his layered
career. Under the tutelage of literary agent Scott Meredith, he
sold feverishly to the pulp magazines. Later, he hooked up with
film director Alfred Hitchcock and wrote the screenplay for ``The
Birds.'' But he really wasn't a screenplay writer, nor a
pulp-fiction hack. Hunter knew characterization as well as
brainless action.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, ``Cop Hater'' appeared, the first of more than
four-dozen titles in his bestselling 87th Precinct series.
Featuring Detective Steve Carella (who serves most often as the
author's alter ego), Hunter created an ensemble of characters who
deftly moved in and out of conflict against the backdrop of Isola,
a fictitious megacity that even the most dense readers understand
is Hunter's New York City.
</P>
<P>
   He penned the series with the name Ed McBain. It's the name most
of the world knows him by today because the 87th Precinct was no
ordinary, genre crime fiction. There was a poetry and incisiveness
to the writing that inspired a whole generation of writers and
producers, including those of the enormously popular cop shows
``Hill Street Blues,'' ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue that what Hunter writes in his straight novels
(he wrote ``The Blackboard Jungle'' and ``Sons'')``'' as well as in
crime fiction is nothing less than literature, although the
literary community has never embraced him.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview from his new home in Connecticut, Hunter
said he's passed the stage of worrying about critics and those who
anoint fiction as literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt early on in my career that I was going to take all the
prizes,'' Hunter said. ``Now I know I'm not going to get the
Pulitzer or the Nobel.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Hunter will be in town at The Poisoned Pen in
Scottsdale for the signing of his newly released ``The Last Dance''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25), the 50th float in the 87th Precinct
parade.
</P>
<P>
   This one is a winner, too, perhaps even more hard-edged and
suspenseful than the series average. What starts out as an apparent
suicide by hanging evolves into a gritty homicide over copyrights
for a major musical production.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said his inspiration came from a musical that he has been
working on over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, and copyright, was much on my mind,'' Hunter said. ``I'm
a writer, and copyright is the only thing of value that any writer
has in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter is now 73 years old, but his voice has the mellifluous
lilt and mischievous energy of a man half his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do feel great,'' Hunter said. ``You know, inside
every 70-year-old fat lady crossing the street and dodging a bus
there's a 16-year-old kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said a typical day is waking at 8, hitting the treadmill
for an hour while watching the morning news, then breakfast, then
heading off to his in-home office where he writes from 10 till 6,
breaking only for lunch with his wife, Dragica. He said that when
he first began writing, he logged many more hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I vowed if I was ever able to make a living writing, I'd never
work at night or on the weekends again,'' Hunter said. ``I lock
that studio door at six and won't go back in no matter what sirens
I hear beckoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was concerned with studies that suggest readers are
disappearing, he replied, ``I'm more concerned that writers are
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he can't recommend any up-and-coming crime-fiction
writers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the title of his latest work, Hunter said it will not be
his last 87th Precinct novel. He plans on calling that one
``Exit,'' to be published after he passes on to that big substation
in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't written it yet,'' Hunter said. ``I have a 100
more titles crowding my head, and I can't wait to start writing
them all.''  &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Thomas.Ropp(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8820. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
