<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BC-COX-GORE-Q&AMP;A-0117     01-16 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-COX-GORE-Q&AMP;A-0117 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With BC-COX-GORE-0117
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a complete a transcript of an interview with Vice
President Al Gore on Saturday, January 15:
</P>
<P>
   in Berlin, N.H. with Scott Shepard of the Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do you think this new involvement of the federal
government in preserving Dr. Martin Luther King's birthplace and
burial site is necessary?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's an important part of America's heritage and history and
has educational and inspirational power to pass on to each new
generation lessons about the life of Dr. King and the message of
Dr. King - a message that is as powerful as ever and needs to be
heard now more than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why now?
</P>
<P>
   A. Because healing is within our reach and because the rest of
the world is in a transformative process with so many other peoples
looking to the United States for signs of hope that they can
transcend racial and ethnic and religious differences and embrace
the highest common denominator of the human spirit. And Dr. King
embodied that fundamentally American message and unlocked more of
the American potential for insuring that we have harmony and
diversity and that we are true to our own highest ideals.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The last time the federal government got involved in a
project related to Dr. King, it was the Park Service's plan to
build a welcome center in the King Historic District. That led to a
conflict with the King family and, since then, has sparked some
debate over whether the King family is trying to profit
commercially from Dr. King's legacy. Do you have any concern that
this will be repeated?
</P>
<P>
   A. I know of no reason to feel that the resolution sometime back
hasn't been acceptable to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You remarked today that as a youth you were excited by the
civil rights movement in the 1960s. What did you mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. I said it embraced my hopes and inspired me. I think that's
true of so many in my generation because a young person who sees
clear injustice and feels the tides of battle in the struggle
against injustice is naturally drawn toward that struggle.
</P>
<P>
   My generation growing up in the 1950s in the New South - of
course I was raised in two places but always identified with the
New South - it was quite dramatic feeling the clear distinction
between right and wrong as the struggle was playing out in the
public arena - hearing some older members of the communities where
we lived attempting to justify the unjustifiable.
</P>
<P>
   My father was a hero to me in having the courage to be on the
right side of most of those questions. But there's no doubt that in
many parts of the South young people saw more clearly than their
elders and felt the essential justice of Dr. King's cause more
easily than an older generation still struggling with the residue
of prejudice from the past. To see so clearly and to feel so
intensely and to have the hope that justice was within reach, that
was thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Q. People generally agree that President Clinton has a very
strong core commitment to improving race relations in the United
States and, for that reason, started his race initiative. Do you
think that accomplished as much as it could have or did it fall
victim to the impeachment process?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think it was a good beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you continue it, if you are president?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not in exactly the same form. But yes, any president who does
the job well will wage a constant battle to bring our people
together. And if I'm entrusted with the presidency, I will have no
higher priority.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What was your first personal encounter with racism?
</P>
<P>
   A. When I was very young, I don't even know how young, three or
four, we used to drive back and forth from Carthage, Tenn., to
Washington, D.C. We would make that four, five, six times a year.
When my sister and I were little, my mother had an African American
woman who worked for her and helped take care of us. She would make
the trip with us, all of us in the car.
</P>
<P>
   I remember when we were not able to stop at some places because
she couldn't be served. We couldn't stay overnight at some places
because she would not be allowed to stay. What I remember most
about it was the conversations between my mother and father about
it and this fine woman who was such an important part of my
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where were you when you heard the news of Dr. King's
assassination?
</P>
<P>
   A. We were driving a car from Boston to Washington on spring
break and we heard the news on the car radio. We got to Washington
and I remember going to pick up my mother downtown at a store and
people were crashing in the plate glass windows along the sidewalk
and I went in to get her and got her into the car and drove her
home.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last fall, you spoke from the same pulpit where Dr. King
delivered his last sermon before his assassination. Monday you will
be speaking from his pulpit at Ebenezer Baptist Church. How does
that feel to stand in places like that?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's humbling to know that no matter how hard you work to
prepare the speech you'll never have even the one one-thousandth of
the eloquence that Dr. King brought to that place. So it's a truly
humbling experience in that sense. But it's an honor to be able to
speak from a place where he stood, of course. And it gives you an
extra desire to say something that will push the limits of what you
are able to say.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you think when you see the Confederate flag?
</P>
<P>
   A. I see the pain that it's causing some of my fellow Americans
who interpret it as a hateful reminder of cruel theories of racial
superiority and misguided determination to hold fast to an ideology
of discrimination. I know that there are some who display it who
have a mix of other intentions. But I also know that some who
display it mean to convey exactly the message that is painfully
received by many, especially African Americans. I just think there
is no excuse for having it atop a public building that is supposed
to open and accommodating to all citizens without trace of
prejudice or discrimination. It's just indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did you feel this week about Sen. Bradley blaming you for
injecting Willie Horton into the 1988 presidential campaign against
Michael Dukakis?
</P>
<P>
   A. I didn't even mention his name. I didn't know his name, to
tell you the truth. I raised the policy issue. What I said was 11
convicted murderers who were given a furlough decided that the two
week passes weren't enough for them and so they left and never came
back and two of them committed other murders and I didn't think
that was a great idea. And I asked (Dukakis), 'didn't you make a
mistake there?' Basically, that was the question. I never mentioned
the name of the prisoner. I didn't even single out an individual
case. I talked about the program as a whole without reference to
race in any way, shape or form. As Mike Dukakis said in response to
Sen. Bradley this week, that was just misleading and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you feel that way, too?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, I think it was misleading and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do you think he did it?
</P>
<P>
   A. You would have to ask him that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Colin Powell recently objected to the comments of your
campaign manager (Donna Brazile) about how the Republican Party
uses prominent African Americans for publicity but does little in
terms of policy to help African Americans. Why didn't you or any
other Democrat use the occasion to challenge Colin Powell to defend
his party's record on race?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think he has earned the right to focus on his America's
Challenge program and he's expressed enough disagreement with some
of the policies of his party in the past that I don't feel the need
to try to make him a spokesman for the shortcomings of the
Republican Party. I think he is a great man. I disagree with his
membership in the Republican Party, but I think he has a right to
do that without being held personally accountable for all the
mistakes that they make.
</P>
<P>
   Q. One obvious disagreement is affirmative action, which raises
the question: How much of an issue will that be in the general
election?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know. I support it, as you know. And I think the case
is overwhelming for why it's still needed. But there's no doubt
it's controversial. And the Republicans have signaled that they
intend to make it an issue. But that's all right. We ought to be
able to defend and debate tough issues. If they're really in the
best interest of the country, and I'm convinced they are, they'll
stand the test of the fair judgement of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about the controversy over (Atlanta Braves pitcher) John
Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know him and I don't have a basis for making a
personal judgment. I was deeply offended by his comments. But I
have a great deal of respect for Andy Young and Hank Aaron. And I
was impressed with the conclusion drawn by the two of them. And I
would say that if he does more convincing of people like that, then
he's got a chance to kind of turn this around.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does this incident reflect anything about our society as a
whole?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. It reflects the basic belief that America is all about
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
