<HEADER>
A7508 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-AGE-AZR &LR;      01-16 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I'M DICK CLARK, YOU'RE DICK CLARK: SOMEONE BORN TODAY MAY LIVE TO
BE 150 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 (EDITORS: STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY, with
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Many readers of this article, particularly those at midlife or
younger, probably expect to live through a good half or more of the
new century.
</P>
<P>
   What they may not be counting on, however, is the speed of
medical progress:
</P>
<P>
   Some people who are middle age today, right now, may well live
through the entire &QC; 
21st century and may be reading another article like this 100 years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   The average lifespan was 47 years when the 20th century began.
It is now 76 years, thanks to public health improvements,
antibiotics, vaccinations, heart surgery, cancer treatments and
other breakthroughs. Some scientists say the American lifespan
could double by the end of the century, thanks to fundamental
tinkering with the root causes of aging and disease.
</P>
<P>
   A world of 150-year-olds doesn't mean a world of tottering
frailty: Extended longevity will be the result of robust health,
extending well into the ninth decade of life and beyond. Retirement
will be a quaint notion, some say, as might retirement communities.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 70,000 Americans who are 100 years old or
older. That number has tripled since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   (In Arizona, there are about 500 centenarians, some keeping
schedules that would put 30-year-olds to shame _ such as former
state Rep. Polly Rosenbaum of Globe and Phoenix, who turned 100 in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Based on current medical science and not allowing for any
advances, the number of Arizonans ages 85 and older is expected to
increase to 455,831 in 2050 from 83,381 in 2000.) If this all seems
like an extended pre-death limbo that you're really not looking
forward to, be cheered by the probability that, in this coming
``I'm Dick Clark, You're Dick Clark'' era, things such as wrinkles,
gray hair, old skin, old muscles, old brain cells, old eyes, old
spouses and poor memories could be things you get fixed at the spa
with pills, creams, injections and flavored sorbets.
</P>
<P>
   Although all that may sound like science fiction, there is some
science making some of it likely.
</P>
<P>
   As a new century begins, scientists studying aging are
cautiously optimistic about making major progress soon in
addressing the cause of aging and the diseases associated with
aging. They have had astonishing success in recent years in
increasing the lifespans of laboratory species such as worms and
fruit flies. Genetic advances also offer tremendous potential.
</P>
<P>
   Although some on the fringe of the scientific world are
predicting lifespans of 200 or more within the next 50 years, most
of those doing the more serious aging research _ people who can't
afford to be quoted on the cover of the ``National Enquirer'' _
aren't saying they agree or disagree.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, however, they are beginning to say fairly amazing
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hunch is that there's a 75 percent chance that someone born
today will live to be 150,'' said Steve Austad, a University of
Idaho biologist specializing in aging and the author of ``Why We
Age.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it at a meeting of eminent academic researchers on aging
who gathered last year at the University of California School of
Medicine at Los Angeles to talk about some of the likely advances
in the next 10 to 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   And at that same meeting, the previously unspeakable was spoken:
``Over the next couple of decades, we will be able to unravel the
mechanism of aging,'' said Cynthia Kenyon, a professor of
biochemistry and biophysics at the University of California-San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that with just a few genetic alterations, scientists
have created worms and fruit flies that have lifespans twice the
norm and that die healthy and vigorous _ the worm or fly equivalent
of being 90 and looking 45. Even mice have lived 40 to 60 percent
longer than normal with a simple genetic tweak. Once more is known
about why and how we age, then the work of delaying it could begin.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INCREMENTAL INCREASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith Campisi of the Berkeley National Laboratory at the
University of California-Berkeley, one of the leading experts on
cancer and aging, sees average lifespans increasing in increments,
as the diseases that kill us are eliminated. She isn't about to
predict future lifespans, however. If she underguesses, she'll live
to regret it.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't exactly throw cold water on the happy talk, however:
``I expect we will be able to ameliorate and perhaps reverse some
of the disabling conditions that plague the last decade or so of
human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Stem cell research in particular, she said, offers the potential
replenishment of cells lost due to aging, trauma or disease.
</P>
<P>
   Most age researchers are more excited about quality of life than
quantity of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What many people don't realize is that we are talking about
having 90-year-olds who are as functional as 50-year-olds,'' said
Kenyon, of UCSF.
</P>
<P>
   Quality of life may be safer to talk about because the culture
may not be ready for the idea of more of us living to 120 or
beyond. When Judith Campisi explained to a group in San Francisco
that her aging research could dramatically extend the lives of
people, the problem of overpopulation came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception that what we are doing is bad for all humankind
can't be ignored,'' she worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is huge hypocrisy around this issue,'' said Steve Austad
of the University of Idaho. ``Some of the same people who respond
that too many people will live too long are lined up at the drug
counters buying melatonin and other supplements purported to have
anti-aging powers.''  &QL; 
ETHICS OF AGING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Arnold, director of the gerontology program at Arizona
State University, worries that without thoughtful discussions now,
only the rich will be able to benefit from some of the scientific
advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethics will become a major point of discussion where science,
medicine, economics and aging interface,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree that major health-policy decisions need to be made
before some of the stem-cell treatments are ready for the market,
which may not be too far off.
</P>
<P>
   For a price, injections will be able to rejuvenate joints,
muscles, organs, skin, even brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, the biggest challenges facing aging America will
be psychological,'' said Ken Dychtwald, a psychologist and author
of the new book ``Age Power.'' ``America has always considered
itself a young nation, a new society _ not an old one.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dychtwald predicts that it will happen: ``We are the
beneficiaries of a Wild West of organ cloning, cyborg body parts,
nutricuticles and biotech manipulations of the biological clock to
the extraordinary extent that some baby boomers will live well past
100 with the look and feel of 50 and 60-year-olds.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1631EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
