<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-DOMINATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANIES MUST LEARN TO COEXIST AFTER AOL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Barbara Ransford happily reported that she
was now on the Internet, having just signed up with America Online,
her son-in-law, Bill Joy, was quick to correct her. Joy, a Sun
Microsystems co-founder who helped build the Internet in the 1970s,
explained that America Online was actually a proprietary network
that allowed access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a level of detail that didn't matter to her,''
recalled Joy. ``She wanted me to meet her on a chat list. I told
her it didn't work on my computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange between a member of cyberspace's old guard and a
``newbie'' underscores the fact that to its 20 million paying
subscribers, America Online is the Internet, the cyberspace
entrance of choice for more Americans than the next dozen largest
Internet service providers combined. Roughly one of every two
households in the United States sees the online world through the
prism of AOL, according to AOL's own figures.
</P>
<P>
   The company's announcement last week of a $165 billion merger
with Time Warner further solidifies its domination of cyberspace by
linking large amounts of content _ everything from magazines and
books to cartoons, movies and recorded music _ to its ever-growing
audience.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal was announced, analysts, journalists and
investors asked, ``Who's next?'' Speculation abounded: Would Yahoo
merge with Disney? Would Microsoft swallow Viacom, which is already
merging with CBS?
</P>
<P>
   But a great deal of head-scratching produced no obvious
pairings, primarily because America Online is an unusual hybrid
that has thrived with a mix of virtual communities and copious
proprietary content and services. And, yes, access to the Internet
_ but almost incidentally and usually carefully choreographed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elsewhere on the Internet, access and content have diverged as
businesses,'' said Chris Charron, an analyst with Forrester
Research, a market research company in Cambridge, Mass. ``The
Mindsprings and Earthlinks and AT&AMP;T Worldnets have been
unsuccessful in the content space,'' he said, referring to other
leading Internet service providers. Other content providers, he
added, have been unsuccessful at providing Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   That this strange hybrid has come not only to dominate the
Internet but to personify it sends a strong signal to its
competitors, which include portal sites on the World Wide Web like
Yahoo and Lycos, as well as hundreds of Internet service providers
large and small. The message is this: Find a way to co-exist with
this behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many assets under one roof, or within one company, the
threat is certainly substantial to any other company in the same
space,'' said Anya Sacharow, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, a market research firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While not entirely ruling out the possibility of a merger in the
future, Tim Koogle, Yahoo's chief executive, said his company
preferred to build a broad set of partnerships with hundreds of
content providers. ``We will try very hard not to do anything that
limits the flexibility we have or decreases the comprehensiveness
of our platform,'' Koogle said.
</P>
<P>
   Koogle pointed out that by the end of December, Yahoo had 120
million users, up from 105 million at the end of September. Yahoo
charges no fee to its users.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to AOL's image, people do not think of Yahoo as the
Internet but rather as part of the World Wide Web, which itself is
a part of the Internet. This, said Koogle, suits him just fine. The
newest generation to come online, he said, ``knows what the Web is
and knows what Yahoo is.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Yahoo's strong fourth-quarter earnings report last
week validates not only its independent status but also its
strategy of making wide-ranging but limited deals with partners and
emphasizing the Yahoo brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That card of agnosticism may take on greater value in light of
the AOL-Time Warner deal,'' said Charron. ``They can say, `We are
truly the only open portal.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo isn't running scared by any means,'' said Michael
Graham, an Internet analyst with Robertson Stephens in San
Francisco. ``Their business is different from AOL's, and they're
going through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves everyone else, portals and Internet service
providers alike, facing tough competition from an AOL-Time Warner
colossus.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AOL-DOMINATE-2NDTAKE-     01-16 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-DOMINATE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Warner colossus. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Basically, the broad-based portals in this middle space are in
for some trouble,'' Charron said of companies like Excite(AT)Home,
Lycos and Snap.com. ``They're in a tough position because they're
trying to support a very expensive cost structure, they're trying
to develop, and they're battling against the Yahoos and AOLs, who
are doing it better and have more access to capital and
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the analysis of business models and strategies, much
of the magic of America Online, say observers, lies with its utter
simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why Steve Case has really won the war at the end of
the day,'' said John W. Sidgmore, vice chairman of MCI Worldcom,
referring to America Online's 41-year-old chairman and chief
executive. ``Steve knew that most customers really want simple
access, user friendliness and a tool that's very easy to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all who use America Online love its self-conscious
simplicity. Gregory Dreicer, a historian of technology and
currently a fellow at the Center for Scholars and Writers at the
New York Public Library, dislikes America Online's user interface,
especially the advertising windows he encounters when he logs on.
But has no plans to defect after using the service for the past 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, Dreicer among them, stay with AOL because they are
creatures of habit.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Dougherty, a consultant to nonprofit organizations in
Austin, Texas, is also lukewarm on the America Online environment,
but she does not want to give up her e-mail address because unlike
most other services, AOL does not forward e-mail to users after
they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Li, a senior analyst with Forrester Research who
follows America Online, said she keeps trying to persuade her
husband to switch to a more sophisticated set of Internet access
tools, but he is ``addicted'' to America Online. ``If I left him
alone he'd be totally, hunky-dory happy with AOL,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   America Online does not reveal what percentage of customers drop
the service, but a Forrester study conducted last year estimated
the company's annual churn rate _ the number of paying subscribers
who cancel the service _ at just 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Betty, chief executive of Earthlink, said he was not
worried about competing with AOL after a Time Warner merger.
``America Online is an online service, not an ISP,'' or Internet
service provider, said Betty, whose company's advertisements have
sought ``AOL graduates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe a debt of gratitude to America Online,'' Betty said,
``because they're the trailblazers, and they continue to
communicate the importance of the Internet to the masses. They
could even be said to be responsible for increasing the penetration
of PCs in households.''
</P>
<P>
   So, while many Internet purists are rankled by the popular
confusion of AOL with the Internet, the distinction remains
irrelevant to the likes of Ms. Ransford. She says her only
frustration with America Online arose when she was visiting her
daughter and Joy recently at their home in Colorado. She was unable
to check her personal financial portfolio using her hosts'
computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have the most updated version of AOL,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
