<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-     01-16 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO LURE PRESTIGIOUS BEAUTY GOODS TO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's purchase of Beauty.com by Drugstore.com for $42
million in stock marked the first of what could be a rash of
consolidations among online retail categories cluttered with
well-financed _ but poorly patronized _ Web stores.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty category, which includes retailers of perfumes and
cosmetics, certainly qualifies as cluttered, with about 300 sites
with similar names selling similar goods. Add to that list a string
of established mass market retailers like Wal-Mart and CVS that
have begun selling the same items online, and the opportunity for
meaningful market share looks slim.
</P>
<P>
   But these purveyors of glamour have concerns more pressing than
the sheer number of competitors. Analysts say that any online
retailer hoping to make a dent in the estimated $15 billion beauty
market cannot hope to succeed without the cooperation of the Big
Three of the beauty industry _ Lancome, Estee Lauder and Clinique,
which is a unit of Estee Lauder Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Those three brands account for roughly 70 percent of the
so-called prestige beauty goods market, which itself is estimated
at about $4 billion. Not only are those brands crucial for
attracting customers, analysts say, but they provide a much more
reliable source of profit than cheaper mass market goods widely
found on the Web. Besides carrying lower profit margins, mass
market beauty products are also proving a tough sell online, given
that shipping charges can equal the cost of the products
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinique and Lancome sell their goods through their own
Web sites _ and Estee Lauder is expected to do so this year _ all
three companies forbid retailers to sell their brands online. That
has left online retailers to choose between selling more obscure
prestige brands or mass market brands like L'Oreal's Maybelline and
Procter &AMP; Gamble's Cover Girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies like Estee Lauder see their brands as the crown
jewels,'' said Lisa Allen, an analyst with Forrester Research.
``They pay close attention to things like how and where they're
displayed, who they're next to.''
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder, which sells exclusively to upper-crust retailers
in the traditional world, would not risk tarnishing its image by
displaying goods in drugstores alongside mass market brands,
analysts said. Likewise, the company's executives are loath to do
the same thing online, where most beauty sites sell a wide range of
brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Saks, you buy the whole ambience,'' said Karen Shoenbart,
group president of the NPD Group, a research and consulting firm.
At an online site, she said, ``you could get a jar of moisturizer
for $30, or $10 within a few clicks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can prestige brands differentiate themselves at an online
store?'' she added. ``Why pay $30, not $10, if you're not enjoying
this shopping experience that much more?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Angela Kapp, vice president of the online division of
Estee Lauder Cos., said: ``The great danger for prestige brands is
commoditization. We have to be very careful about that because our
brand equity is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder is ``in the process of defining its overall
strategy'' with regard to the Web, Ms. Kapp said, but the company
``has no plans to sell to Internet pure plays,'' using industry
vernacular for Internet-only merchants.
</P>
<P>
   So the question, analysts said, comes down to whether the
prestige brands can afford not to sell through online retailers
indefinitely, or whether the lure of online profits will outweigh
the fear that the Web will damage brand image.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Allen of Forrester Research said manufacturers of prestige
cosmetics ``should recognize they can still have some control of
their brand while allowing retail partners to sell online.''
</P>
<P>
   She offered an example: ``They can create a microsite, ship it
to the retailer and tell them it's the only way they can display
the products online. That way they protect the crown jewels and use
the Web for what it's good at: marketing, growing the customer
database, doing research and educating existing clients and sales
personnel about the products.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a company microsite _ a collection of Web pages
within another company's site _ is precisely the approach taken by
BeautyJungle.com, a beauty goods retailer that made its debut in
November. BeautyJungle sells products through five different
boutiques within its store, depending on the pedigree of the item
in question. Within the Elite Street boutique, for example,
manufacturers can create so-called ``brand rooms'' _ pages with
large advertisements intended to convey the brand's message.
</P>
<P>
   Elite Street also offers a higher level of customer service than
other boutiques. It features e-mail product consultation, and in
the future will allow for instant messaging or chat consultations,
said Edward LaHood, the company's chief executive. By contrast, the
Main Street boutique, which sells beauty products commonly found in
drugstores, is self-service.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood said he hoped BeautyJungle's Elite Street strategy,
combined with heavy investments in customer service and fulfillment
operations, would ultimately persuade prestige brands to sell to
his site. But he said the company had other sources of revenue in
case those brands continued to shun online retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among those sources is a business-to-business component,
wherein BeautyJungle will create beauty-related sites for other
retailers or manufacturers, and also handle fulfillment and
customer service. LaHood said the company was ``in discussions''
with about 20 potential clients, with the first deal signed by
Bolt.com, a site for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Declining to say how much the company would charge for such
services, LaHood asserted that the revenues from the
business-to-business effort would ``eclipse those from the
business-to-consumer side'' within two years.
</P>
<P>
   For competing beauty sites that have no such source of revenue,
but that still want to cater to the high-end beauty market, there
are two possible routes. In fact, both approaches are embodied by
the beauty-related sites that have recently attracted the highest
number of visitors, according to Media Metrix, an online traffic
measurement firm.
</P>
<P>
   Eve.com, which led the Media Metrix rankings of beauty sites in
November, offers a long list of prestige beauty products from
companies that have chosen to sell online, including Awake,
Bvlgari, Nina Ricci and Philosophy. Meanwhile, it bolsters the more
well-known prestige selections with lesser-known brands like Yohji
Yamamoto or Weleda.
</P>
<P>
   IBeauty.com, on the other hand, sells brands like Estee Lauder
and Lancome on an unauthorized basis, meaning they procure the
products from nonmanufacturer sources.
</P>
<P>
   Elana Posner, executive vice president of IBeauty.com, said,
``This is a sound business practice, because IBeauty's No. 1
priority is meeting customer demand and sustaining high customer
satisfaction with our services.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Inevitably the floodgates will open'' Ms. Posner said, ``as
they did in the retail industry, because as traditional
manufacturers transition to an Internet-friendly business model,
their product supply and distribution practices must shift
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, but analysts said that in the short term,
those beauty sites that cannot serve customers with a full range of
products _ and that choose not to sell unauthorized manufacturer
goods _ will suffer. ``I definitely see more consolidation,'' said
Ms. Allen of Forrester Research. ``I just don't see how a lot of
the cosmetics sites with brands that many mainstream women have
never heard of, never mind bought or used, can ever survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
