<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER BRIEFS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROM VICTIM TO ENTREPRENEUR
</P>
<P>
   If it's true you should invest in things you know, then Mark
Agnew is in the right field: eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   That's been his preoccupation since Thanksgiving Day 1987, when
Agnew was mugged in downtown Portland, Maine. Agnew, an investment
banker at the time, lost the use of one eye and has had to wear
glasses ever since to protect his sight in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Agnew, 38, has been frustrated by the eyeglass industry, in
which he asserts the opticians are not helpful and the range of
suitable frames too limited.
</P>
<P>
   But where there's a Web there's a way. Last month, Agnew
introduced an online eyeglass store that lets people shop for
glasses in privacy, with several dozen designer brands to choose
among (www.eyeglasses.com). The company, started with private
financing, is based in Norwalk, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can see how different frames look on their own faces
by using photos, which they scan at home (or at a computer services
store like Kinko's) and then submit to Eyeglasses.com via e-mail.
Various possibilities can be viewed side by side on the Web page.
There is also a feature that lets the customer invite friends into
the virtual dressing room to offer opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Frames from Eyeglasses.com cost roughly the same, or slightly
less than buying them in a store, Agnew said, but the site offers
discounts on lenses, which require the customer's sending a
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Agnew maintained that trying on glasses virtually, rather than
in person, is helpful for people with poor vision because, he says,
they try on new pairs while still wearing their old pair. --LAURIE
J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD'S `CONTENT' IS GRIST FOR A START-UP
</P>
<P>
   Here's further proof that Hollywood is no longer merely courting
the Internet industry but ready to marry. On the schedule for
Monday is the announcement of a new Internet incubator founded by
former entertainment industry executives.
</P>
<P>
   Called Fusient Media Ventures, the new company is the work of
Brian Bedol, a former Time Warner executive who also cofounded the
Classic Sports Network, now known as ESPN Classic. Bedol, who also
had a hand in creating MTV, Court TV and Nick at Nite, will serve
as Fusient's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The last few years have seen the rise of venture incubators
focused on various facets of the Internet, but Fusient appears to
be one of the most pedigreed yet to focus on so-called content
rather than technology. The idea, Bedol said, is to identify and
develop material for the coming era of broadband, which is supposed
to enable all companies to broadcast virtually any kind of
programming over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next few years, content will become as important to
the Internet as programming is to television,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of America Online's intention to acquire Time
Warner, the announcement provides even more evidence that the line
between new media and the traditional entertainment business is
blurring.
</P>
<P>
   The founding team of Fusient also includes Stephen D. Greenberg,
former deputy commissioner of Major League Baseball and also
cofounder of the Classic Sports Network, and Tom Lassally, a former
executive vice president of Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg is chairman of the new company, which is based in New
York, and Lassally is president of its West Coast operation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Marcus, previously senior vice president at Miramax in
charge of international distribution, has joined Fusient as head of
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Fusient's investors, who have contributed a total of
$30 million, includes Allen &AMP; Co., Berkshire Partners, Redpoint
Ventures and Waterview Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Fusient plans to invest in 15 to 20 start-up companies a year,
and already has committed to two, Bedol said. Among those under
consideration is a teen-age-oriented humor site, though he declined
to give any more information on Fusient's investments.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned. Or logged on. Whatever. --LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
