<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMMAKING-FINANCE-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANCE TO PITCH FOR WOULD-BE MOVIEMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jon C. Scheide ambled up to the microphone, 400
pairs of eyes glued to him, utterly sympathetic, while a panel of
movie-industry types stared down dispassionately from their seats
on the dais, like guardians at the gates of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Scheide began his pitch: a futuristic, gender-bending,
techno-thriller called ``Out of Body, Out of Mind.'' You see, in
the not-so-distant future, you can upload and download
consciousness, meaning that sexual partners can trade bodies and
see what it is like on the other side, until one day a gold-digging
trophy wife refuses to give her tycoon husband his body back and
he/she has to figure out some way to restore matters before she/he
loots his/her bank account and dumps him/her for a younger model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid I lost you a little bit in the details,'' said
Jacquie Lawrence, an executive with Channel 4 in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps you've buried the best elements in your pitch,'' said
Joe Pichirallo, an executive at Fox Searchlight. ``And I think you
need to decide which way you want to go with this. It could be a
serious thriller, which is how I think you're describing it. Or it
could be a comedy. It could be a big-budget movie with big stars,
or it could be a smaller art film. You need to make some tough
choices. And also I should tell you that we have a story something
like that already in development at 20th Century Fox with Jim
Carrey.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheide leaned forward and beat his forehead against the
microphone, the thundering thump, thump, thump echoing through the
high-tech interior of the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts here.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``Open Day'' at the Seventh Annual International Film
Financing Conference, a somewhat more intimate, boutique-size
alternative to annual gatherings like the American Film Market in
Los Angeles in February and the Independent Film Financing Market
in New York in September. It is a place for aspiring producers and
filmmakers to get together with executives and bankers, people who
buy films or give money to make them, and also to meet one another,
compare battle scars and learn some tricks of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   This particular panel, ``Pitch Perfect: How to Sell Your Idea,''
is always one of the highlights of the festival, as it is in the
growing number of film gatherings, like this, that allow people to
walk in off the street and pitch a movie idea to real, live movie
executives. At this year's Sundance Film Festival, the annual high
point on the independent film calendar, which opens in Utah later
this week, a Los Angeles company will even allow people to pitch
their ideas online.
</P>
<P>
   For the audience it is a kind of entertainment, a catharsis;
they can live out their own best-pitch fantasies and worst-pitch
nightmares without actually being on the line themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For the aspiring filmmakers, it is a golden chance to try out
the silver-tongued pitches they've been practicing before the
bedroom mirror in front of a panel of kindly but somewhat
gimlet-eyed professionals. And there is always the hope, largely
delusional, that one of the panelists will jump up and say,
``That's it, just what we've been looking for!''
</P>
<P>
   After the pitch session, the fourth he has attended in four
years, Pichirallo said: ``I don't expect to find anybody here. That
would be a miracle. But it's so hard to get somewhere in this
business that what I try to do is explain to people the dos and the
don'ts. Just being a good filmmaker does not mean you know how to
sell your idea. But to succeed, that's exactly what you're going to
have to do, over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the conference is open; that is, anyone can buy
a ticket and take part in the panels. The rest of the weekend is
limited to the 58 producers and filmmakers whose applications were
accepted from the 300 or so submitted, a winnowing process that
makes the conference more attractive to a lot of production
executives and bankers because it gives them confidence that they
will be faced only with projects of some proven pedigree and not
every deluded aspirant who could afford a bus ticket, plus the
entire graduating class of the local film school.
</P>
<P>
   The success can be seen in the growing number of production
executives who attend the event, up from 6 in its first year to
more than 70 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm committed to smallness,'' said Wendy Braitman, executive
director of the conference. ``It's about relationships. It's about
building relationships. We allow people to get to know each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't result in an immediate film deal, and it almost
never does, perhaps it can be the beginning of a creative
relationship that will end with a project a few years down the
road, Ms. Braitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't spend a lot of time talking about content,'' she
said. ``This is about financing, making contacts, learning how to
get your film made. It's such a heartbreak-hotel business. Hearing
some of the success stories and commiserating with one another,
like the people are doing here, takes some of the pain away.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   This is a time of enormous change and anxiety in the
independent-film business. Although there have been recent
successes like ``The Blair Witch Project,'' which came out of last
year's Sundance festival, the governing reality for young producers
and filmmakers at this level is that the economic model that
sustained the American independent boom over the last decade has
altered. It is no longer as easy or perhaps even possible to make
the midrange movie, costing $1 million to $3 million, and have any
concrete hopes of it rising above the glut and making it into
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules have changed,'' said Jack Lechner, a veteran film
executive and writer who gave the conference's keynote address. It
used to be that a young filmmaker with talent and a decent idea
could make the rounds, get bare-bones financing to shoot a film,
put it out on the festival circuit and have reasonable hopes of
getting a theatrical booking, at least in New York and Los Angeles.
``It rarely works that way anymore,'' Lechner said. ``The films
will more likely sit there, collecting debt and dust while the
filmmakers try and figure out what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   What has happened during the last decade or so is that a rising
tide of American independent films _ led by breakout hits like
Steven Soderbergh's ``Sex, Lies and Videotape'' and Kevin Smith's
``Clerks'' _ gradually pushed foreign films out of the small number
of art-film houses around the country. Then, inevitably, the
Hollywood studios smelled profit and absorbed many of the
independent distribution companies, like Miramax and New Line, and
began to make their own independent-style films. Now those films
have pushed most of the genuine independents out of those same art
houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is flooded,'' Lechner said. ``The day of the nice
little movie is over, kaput. The old independent boom has been
absorbed by the mainstream, which has been invigorated by it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the reason for the sense of anxiety and
uncertainty that permeated the conference, as aspiring filmmakers
explored issues like the emerging world of digital production,
alternative avenues of distribution like cable television, and
seeking financing from foreign television markets hungry for
something to fill up their air time.
</P>
<P>
   That the conference comes just before Sundance _ the mountaintop
Valhalla of the independent movement, where perhaps a new ``Blair
Witch'' will emerge, or at least some of the fog may lift and a
path forward reveal itself _ only ratchets up the anxiety level.
</P>
<P>
   It was certainly palpable in the room during the pitch panel. So
many aspiring, creative people trying to figure out how to get
their movies made, how to get in on the party, like people on the
rope line outside a fashionable club trying to figure out what the
doorman is looking for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The pitches poured out: an immigrant sucked into the life of a
street gang. Brothers born 20 years apart brought together by the
death of their estranged father. An escaped slave who lives with
American Indians in the Carolina wilderness. A kind of rural
Serpico in the Pacific Northwest solving a 50-year-old murder. Two
young women who want to be filmmakers with a story about two young
women who want to be filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid you've lost me completely,'' Jan Rofekamp, whose
Montreal-based Films Transits finances documentaries, told one
tongue-tied pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan King of Laurence Mark Productions prodded, ``Perhaps
you should practice this in front of other people first.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Hu of Strand Releasing told one woman: ``You have to keep
in mind what you want from the pitch. What you really want in a
pitch is to set up the next meeting. It's always about the next
step. And you've done that. You've hooked me. I want to know what
happens next.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheide stood against the wall in the back of the conference
hall after his pitch, running it over in his mind. He had come to
the conference hoping to find financing to finish another film and
only put his name in the mix for the pitches on a whim. He thought
he would try out a new idea he was considering for his next
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw my card in, and then I thought, `Uh-oh, I'd better
figure out what I'm going to pitch,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He listened to the pitches before his, tried to figure out what
the panelists wanted to hear, restructured his ideas on a piece of
scratch paper, then let fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pitched before,'' Scheide said. ``You know, in the real
world. So this was not my first pitch. What was great about this is
that you got the before and after. Usually you make your pitch and
then you leave. Here they give you instant feedback. That's what
you need. You know, the big thing about pitching is getting over
your fear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
