A7532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ZELTSER-EXPLANATION-N     01-16 0252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZELTSER-EXPLANATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CONFIDENTIALITY CEASES TO BE BINDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (SIDEBAR With ZELTSER-PROFILE) 
(js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Relationships between journalists and their sources are
predicated on the honest exchange of information. That principle is
even more important when a source requests anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel E. Zeltser, the subject of an article Monday in The New
York Times, has argued that a profile of him is unfair because The
Times agreed to use him as an anonymous source after he was quoted
in an Aug. 20, 1999, story about te money laundering investigation
involving the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Zeltser was repeatedly reminded that the agreement would be
honored only as long as he did not muddy the reporting process with
lies or false documentation.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Aug. 20 story appeared, Zeltser offered to
arrange a meeting with a person he described as a Russian
intelligence official. When a reporter requested evidence of this
person's credentials, Zeltser canceled the meeting. The Times then
distanced itself from Zeltser.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Zeltser provided The Times with dubious documents
about the World Bank and a Bank of New York executive, Natasha
Gurfinkel Kagalovsky. He also misrepresented the nature of his
relationship with two of his longtime associates, including a woman
who works at the World Bank. At that point, the newspaper decided
to proceed with a profile of Zeltser that drew on some of his
remarks as a background source.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1734EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      01-16 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE ENTRIES IN THE FLOOD OF DEVICES INTENDED TO HELP SNORERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How loudly does Joseph Goldstein snore?
</P>
<P>
   Well, his wife likes to tell a story about their romantic
vacation at a pricey hotel in the Caribbean, where the guests stay
in little cabins, right on the beach, to fall asleep under the
starry sky as waves lap lullingly against the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, the ocean wasn't loud enough to obscure Goldstein's
snoring. Guests in the neighboring cabins phoned the front desk to
complain. The Goldsteins checked out the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Many treatments already exist for snoring, from Breathe Right
strips to uvulopalatopharnygoplasty, the most widely performed
surgery to treat snoring. And in the past year dozens of new
patents were issued covering the latest artillery in the snore
wars.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent of these went to Goldstein, who was awarded a
patent last week for what he contends will provide relief to
serious snorers like himself. He suffers from sleep apnea, a
snoring-related disorder that afflicts as many as 30 million
Americans and that has been linked to heart disease, strokes, high
blood pressure, daytime fatigue and irritability.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein is an inventor with about 25 patents to his credit.
But most of those are in the packaging-machinery field. He shifted
his inventing sights after he sought medical relief from his
snoring and discovered that he had sleep apnea, which is resistant
to conventional snoring treatments.
</P>
<P>
   So alarmed was Goldstein about the dangers of sleep apnea that
he was moved to write ``Snoring Can Kill!!'' _ a book recently
published by the Caren Publishing Group.
</P>
<P>
   Harmless snoring, according to Goldstein, is a steady rhythm.
Dangerous snoring is syncopated, with gasps for breath. ( Goldstein
sponsors a toll-free number, (888) 35-SNORE, which features the two
different types of snoring.)
</P>
<P>
   ``With sleep apnea, the brain sends out an emergency signal
because it's not getting enough oxygen,'' Goldstein said. ``The
person wakes up suddenly, gasps for breath and then falls back to
sleep often without realizing he has done so. But these arousals
cause a great deal of fatigue and irritability during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Goldstein briefly surveys apnea treatments,
including the ``continuous positive air pressure machine,'' or
CPAP, which was invented 20 years ago by an Australian sleep
researcher, Colin E. Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's invention is actually an attachment to this machine,
which is already widely prescribed for sleep apnea sufferers and
which acts as a miniature air compressor, blowing air into the
breathing passages to keep them open.
</P>
<P>
   ``CPAP is the most effective and noninvasive treatment for sleep
apnea,'' Goldstein said. But, he said, most users find it
exceedingly uncomfortable to use the CPAP mask, which fits over the
face with a tight seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to stop using it,'' Goldstein said. In many people it
results in a persistent sore on the bridge of the nose. Half of
those who are prescribed the machine stop using it, according to
Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Goldstein's attachment, which recently was approved
by the Food and Drug Administration, clamps on to the upper teeth
with a mouth plate that resembles those used by dentists to treat
bruxism _ a condition that is essentially the gnashing of teeth
during sleep.
</P>
<P>
   In place of a mask covering the nose, Goldstein's device has two
parallel tubes that insert into the user's nostrils. The other end
of the tubes attach to the machine.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement, Goldstein contends, is more comfortable
because it allows the wearer to turn his head from side to side
without bumping his mask on the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein has begun manufacturing the device through his
company, Stevenson Industries Inc., in Palisades, Calif. It is
distributed through Space Maintainers of Chatsworth, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein received patent 6,012,455. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER SOLUTION FOR SNORING PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   The marketplace abounds with special anti-snoring pillows. But
Robert Hershgordon, of Bensalem, Pa., has patented an anti-snoring
wedge that, instead of replacing the snorer's favorite pillow, can
be used in conjunction with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People generally become very attached to their own sleeping
pillow,'' his patent notes, and snorers are loath to give up a
pillow that is quite possibly ``the most important part of their
sleep regimen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershgordon's patent covers not just the foam insert but also an
extra-large pillow case that is big enough to accommodate both the
wedge and an ordinary pillow. The wedge props up the sleeper's
head, according to Hershgordon's patent, and thus alleviates the
snoring.
</P>
<P>
   He received patent 5,920,932. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
