<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SREBRENICA-REVIEW-     01-16 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SREBRENICA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SREBRENICA': DARK HOURS OF SERBIAN HATRED FILMED BY THOSE WHO
KNEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Program notes follow end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Consult local listings.) 
(js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The viewfinders of camcorders and the memories of survivors
combine powerfully in ``Srebrenica: A Cry From the Grave,'' Monday
night's unsparing account of the July 1995 slaughter of thousands
of Bosnian Muslims by Serbian troops. The number killed remains
uncertain, but the pictures bring home the human suffering and the
political failure of what Bill Moyers, narrating, calls ``the worst
massacre in Europe since World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute BBC documentary begins with Saliha Osmanovic's
return to the Srebrenica graveyard where one son is buried and with
pictures of her husband, captured by the Serbs, calling out
desperately to their other son; both disappeared among more than
7,000 Muslim men who are presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are now under the protection of the U.N. forces,'' the
U.N. commander, Gen. Philippe Morillon, is seen telling Muslims in
1993. But two years later, as a few hundred Dutch soldiers assigned
to keep Srebrenica as what the Security Council designated ``a safe
area'' did nothing to interfere, Bosnian men and boys were
separated from the women and killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch troops themselves, starved for food, fuel and
ammunition, became hostages. With Dutch soldiers at risk, NATO
threats to bomb the Serbs proved empty, and the thousands of
refugees fleeing the vengeance of the Serbs were trapped. One woman
says: ``We left without locking the house. I had beautiful big
roses.'' A Dutch officer tells of receiving two orders: one to
defend the refugees, the other, more to the point, ``We don't allow
you to bring body bags home.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most chilling scenes are of Gen. Ratko Mladic, who
led the Serbian assault, assuring his captives that no one need die
if they surrendered their arms, that they would all be safely
carried to Muslim territory, ``women and children first.'' But to
his own troops he declares, ``The time has come to take vengeance
on the Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   In pictures evidently taken with Western television in mind,
Serbian soldiers hand out candy to Muslim children, but Zumra
Shekhomerovic recalls a different scene amid the chaos of terrified
families: an armed Serb orders her husband, ``You come this way''
and tells her, ``You go on.'' She weeps, ``I never saw him again
and don't know what happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   A war crimes investigator tells how, beginning on July 14, the
male prisoners were assembled in scattered locations and executions
went on for two days. He estimates that 4,000 or more were
``assassinated in cold blood.'' The search for bodies continues in
preparation for war crimes trials, but the indicted Mladic is
reported to be in comfortable liberty in Serbia. How comfortable
that is was called into doubt by the murder of Zeljko Raznatovic on
Saturday in Belgrade; he was a notorious Serbian paramilitary
leader who had been indicted in 1997 by the International War
Crimes Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   With the Serbian victory complete, Dutch troops are seen
celebrating their freedom; and there is Mladic offering a toast
(``To a long life!'') and presenting gifts to a Dutch colonel. A
U.N. report, issued last year, admits that errors, misjudgment and
``an inability to recognize the scope of the evil confronting us''
resulted in the failure to protect Bosnian Muslims from the Serb
campaign of mass murder. It concludes, ``The tragedy of Srebrenica
will haunt our history forever.''
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SREBRENICA: A CRY FROM THE GRAVE'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Krishan Arora (Antelope Films) and Stephen Segaller (WNET/New
York), executive producers; directed and produced by Leslie
Woodhead. An Antelope Films production for BBC2's Storyville in
association with WNET/New York. Bill Moyers, narrator.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
