<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7538 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BYE-BYE-BARNS-ART-775     01-16 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BYE-BYE-BARNS-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNS ARE VANISHING FROM THE COUNTRYSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Iowa _ A place for horses and hay since before the
Civil War, the old red barn stands at the edge of a cornfield, with
its hand-pegged boards and ladder rungs still covered with bark.
</P>
<P>
   But the horses are long gone. And the old barn is too small to
house the huge combines and tractors now used in farming. Sometime
next month, a bulldozer will knock it over, and the old boards will
be burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame to see the beautiful old barns go, but they're
useless,'' said John Berdo, whose family has been farming here for
seven generations. ``The old barns are as obsolete as the manual
typewriter in the computer age.''
</P>
<P>
   Long the epitome of agrarian life, old wood barns are vanishing
from the American countryside. They are being replaced by metal
storage buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on charm.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on farm life say that more than half of the nation's
wood barns have already been lost. In Iowa alone, some 1,000 old
barns disappear each year, according to Jacqueline Shmeal, a leader
of the Iowa Barn Foundation, which raises money for the
preservation of the old structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole countryside is soon going to look like an industrial
park with all of these metal buildings,'' Ms. Shmeal said. ``These
barns are America's best example of folk art. It's terrible to lose
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In large part, the loss of the old barns reflects the declining
number of farmers. In 1900, 50 percent of all Americans lived or
worked on a farm. A century later, that number has shrunk to less
than 1 percent. And farmers today rely on high-powered machines
that can be 16 feet tall and 20 feet wide, much too large to be
stored in the old wood barns, while livestock is often confined to
low-slung metal sheds, which look nothing like the old barns.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of repairing the barns can be prohibitive. Just
installing a new roof can cost $20,000 or more. For farmers
struggling to survive a terrible drop in corn and soybean prices,
such an investment seems foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   And for preservationist groups trying to keep wood barns around,
cost is a big factor, too. There are no official figures on the
total number of wood barns preserved, but it is relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   While the old barns tug at their emotions, farmers know the
metal barns make more economic sense. And keeping an empty barn, a
tempting place for adventurous children, can pose liability
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The old barns have a hallowed place in the history and mythology
of rural life. They were, as Henry Ward Beecher wrote in 1869,
``the real headquarters of the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   More than just storage places, the old barns were places where
children played hide-and-seek in hay lofts, where hard-working men
sat down at day's end and mapped a plan for the sunrise and where
neighbors gathered for a dance.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Soike, the historian for the State Historical Society of
Iowa in Des Moines, recalls his father, Arthur, recounting how, as
a teen-ager, he would play the fiddle at barn dances in rural
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barn is the biggest thing on the farm,'' Soike said. ``A
lot of farmers, if they had some money, the barn was the first
place they spent it, not on the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers have not been building wood barns in significant numbers
since the 1940s, according to William Kimball, a retired professor
at Michigan State University and an adviser to the National Barn
Alliance, which promotes saving wood barns.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nation's old wood barns were built from the 1860s
through the 1940s, Kimball said. In some cases, a neighborhood of
farmers would gather and pitch in to help build a barn.
</P>
<P>
   Barns were often painted red because the pigment oxide was cheap
and durable, although some farmers, including the Amish, considered
red a garish, worldly color and avoided it, Kimball said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1870s there was a movement toward round or octagonal
barns, largely because some farmers ``believed there was something
sacred in that shape,'' Kimball said. Some of the Shaker barns in
that shape still stand in New England, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball, who often speaks to farmer groups, contends that the
old barns have more than just aesthetic and symbolic importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a resource here, and it's a lot more valuable than
people think,'' he said. ``These barns are easily converted to
other uses.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that barns have been turned into houses, offices,
theaters and churches. The old wood used on the barns is considered
valuable by many antiques dealers and craft workers, Kimball said,
though the preservation process is so time-consuming that it is
often not worth the effort to farmers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ed and Arlene Peiffer, retired farmers who have an old cattle
barn, received a call from some Amish men who offered to dismantle
the structure and haul away the wood for other uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have it,'' Peiffer, 78, told them.
</P>
<P>
   The old barn on the Berdo place has withstood too many floods
and storms to count. A terrible windstorm in 1998 flattened at
least 10 barns in Washington County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to my son that morning, `Maybe the wind has pushed the
old thing down and we'll be done with it,''' Berdo recalled. ``But
then we rounded the corner and there it stood, picture-perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Berdo said the barn was built by his great-great-grandfather
John Winter in the 1850s. Berdo's father, Charles, who died 11
years ago, had a deep sentimental attachment to the barn, because
his own grandfather had worked in the building and his mother,
Carrie, had been born in a house nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In the last years of his life, Charles Berdo had tried
unsuccessfully to interest the county historical society in
refurbishing the barn and keeping it as a museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad and I disagreed on the old barn,'' said Berdo, whose
family keeps a framed painting of the barn in its farmhouse. ``I
know it's a beautiful landmark, but for what?''
</P>
<P>
   Berdo, 49, chuckled a bit at the recollection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, my dad was pretty tight,'' Berdo said. ``So when
it came right down to it, I don't think he would have put up the
thousands of dollars to save it, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
