<P>
   CHILE-ELECTION (Santiago, Chile) _ Chileans go to the polls to
choose their next president. The race between conservative Joaquin
Lavin and socialist Ricardo Lagos is expected to be close. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-BATTLE (Washington) _ The annual fight over the federal
budget is about to get under way. Once again, the numbers-crunchers
will predict larger than expected surpluses, and Congress and the
White House will grapple with how to use it: to cut taxes, to
increase spending or to pay back the national debt. The arguments
are familiar, but with an election looming, the outcome could be
different. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   GLAXO-SMITHKLINE (Undated) _ Monitoring developments as the
SmithKline and Glaxo boards meet to consider an $80.7-billion
merger that would create the world's largest drug maker. By Andrew
Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-GORE-LABOR (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Al Gore can be thankful
that this state is more than an unending field of corn. Punctuating
the prairies are dozens of industrial plants that serve the
agricultural economy, and the heavily unionized workforce in these
farm-equipment factories and meat-packing plants is a major factor
behind the Gore camp's confidence that the vice president will win
Iowa's Jan. 24 caucuses, the first big test in this year's
presidential campaign. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   BYE-BYE-BARNS (Washington, Iowa) _ Long the epitome of agrarian
life, old wood barns are vanishing from the American countryside.
They are being replaced by metal storage buildings, which are
cheaper and bigger, if short on charm. Experts on farm life say
more than half of the nation's wood barns have already been lost.
In Iowa alone, some 1,000 old barns disappear each year. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANTS (New York) _ The police roundups are never
accompanied by a reading of the suspects' Miranda rights. Instead,
the lieutenant in charge usually asks: ``Do you want to work at
McDonald's for the rest of your life?'' The suspects are junior
high and high school students, and they are playing hooky in in the
kind of place that has lured truants for more than a generation: a
shiny new mall. The only difference is that this place is called
Times Square. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
