<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BROADBAND-INTERNET-AR     01-16 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND-INTERNET-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACE QUICKENS TOWARD REALITY OF HIGH-SPEED, INTERACTIVE
`BROADBAND' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was eight years ago that John C. Malone, the cable television
baron, brashly proclaimed that the average American home would soon
be able to receive 500 channels of information and entertainment.
But since then, the arrival of two-way, high-capacity, high-speed
services has been next year's story.
</P>
<P>
   Like some mythical wild beast that is described but never seen,
broadband _ as such high-speed links are known _ has always been
out there somewhere, just over the horizon. Next year, the analysts
and executives promised, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Five-hundred-channel cable systems have not materialized,
because Malone's original vision is still too far ahead of the
technology _ and more importantly, because the rise of the Internet
overtook plans for other types of interactive TV.
</P>
<P>
   But now, broadband information and entertainment pipelines are
finally reaching at least some American homes. And by agreeing last
week to acquire Time Warner, America Online, the leading Internet
access provider, is betting $165 billion that, at long last, next
year is actually this year.
</P>
<P>
   In that view, and on that big bet, America Online is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   The converging Internet, cable TV and telephone industries are
spending billions of dollars to make broadband a reality _ at an
estimated construction cost of $500 to $600 a household, whether
the broadband connection is through a cable system or telephone
line. The effort represents the most extensive, most expensive
engineering project in residential communications since the cable
TV industry started wiring neighborhoods in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation, residential streets are being torn up for new
fiber-optic cables. Technicians are testing telephone lines to
ensure compatibility with advanced new technology. Already, some
1.4 million American homes now enjoy broadband on-ramps to what was
once quaintly referred to as the information highway. And by the
end of this year, a large plurality of the roughly 100 million
households in the United States will probably have access to some
sort of high-speed data connection.
</P>
<P>
   So it was the sound of jackhammers and the whine of drills that
gave urgency to America Online's need to do the Time Warner deal.
For by agreeing to acquire Time Warner's media empire and its
far-flung cable television systems, America Online has made a major
concession: that the future of cyberspace for everyday consumers is
not in the phone-line modems and dial-up connections on which
America Online has built its base of 20 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Starting soon, AOL knows, the Internet companies that will
succeed will be those able to provide the sort of lightning-quick
data connections that until now have been common only in well-wired
business offices.
</P>
<P>
   For all the industry momentum, though, it will take years,
perhaps decades, for broadband data connections to become as common
in American homes as the telephone line. Millions of people,
particularly in rural areas, will probably miss out, at least
during the first rounds of introduction. Initially, broadband
connections will generally be priced at $360 or more a year,
putting them beyond the reach of some households. And in many parts
of the country, systems remain to be built and tested.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the challenges, the broadband beast finally seems poised
for domestication.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to people in major metropolitan areas is that
broadband is here as of the first quarter for millions of people,''
said Amy B. McIntosh, chief executive of Bell Atlantic's network
data operation. In the next two years, she said, ``We won't
probably get to 100 percent of the homes, but we will get to a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That the broadband project, despite fits and false starts, is
now moving so quickly is a tribute to the power of competition _ in
this case between the cable television industry and the local
telephone business. Satellite providers and perhaps electric power
companies may well weigh in with their own residential broadband
alternatives during the next few years, but so far have made little
headway.
</P>
<P>
   The cable TV industry, despite having fewer employees and less
money than the local phone companies, has taken the early lead. The
Yankee Group, a technology consulting firm in Boston, estimates
that by the end of 1999, 1.1 million U.S. households received
broadband data connections through cable lines while only about
300,000 had broadband service through phone wires.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity is partly a result of the cable industry's more
aggressive management. Many of even the biggest cable companies
have been run by the entrepreneurs who founded them, or by their
families, while the biggest local phone companies have had
board-room bureaucracies making decisions with more deliberation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``My observation from being in that world for almost a decade is
that there's a lot of big-monopoly bias,'' said Elizabeth Fetter, a
former executive at US West Inc., a regional Bell. Ms. Fetter is
now president of NorthPoint Communications, a small company that
delivers broadband connections through phone wires, using a
technique known as DSL, for digital subscriber lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the Bells had some sort of skunkworks,'' she said,
``but they were small and the very top management didn't put out
the mandate and say, `We're doing it.'''
</P>
<P>
   At least as important in cable's early lead are some fundamental
technical differences between cable and telephone networks. As
Sender Cohen, a data communications analyst at Lehman Brothers, has
said, ``Think of the copper telephone wire as a very thin but very
intelligent pipe, and the cable wire as very fat but very dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways it is easier to impart intelligence than girth.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television systems were designed, obviously, to carry
television signals, which require far more digital bits than even
the quickest data connections generally available to consumers.
Moreover, cable systems have been designed to convey those signals
over many miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transmission losses are minimal or negligible from
fiber-optic nodes down to homes in any reasonable neighborhood,''
said Trey Smith, chief technology officer of Roadrunner, Time
Warner's cable modem venture.
</P>
<P>
   Local phone wires can also run for many miles, but were
originally meant to carry only voice conversations _ a digital
trickle, compared with the torrent of bits required for a
high-speed cyberspace link. And as more digital bits are pumped
through a telephone wire, the sustainable distance for the flow
rate is reduced. For consumers, that means homes more than roughly
three miles from a telephone switching station have little hope of
getting a high-speed connection through phone wires.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, in a traditional phone network each home
essentially has its own wire running to a switching station. Cable
networks are designed around a ``tree and branch'' architecture in
which traffic is combined from individual homes and routed into
neighborhood-sized communications pipes.
</P>
<P>
   This cable design means that, strictly from the perspective of
raw communications capacity, even a high-speed data connection
hardly taxes a cable system. And just as important is that, from a
network standpoint, one home looks the same as the next. In a
telephone network, by contrast, the link to each home has its own
individual characteristics, starting with the length of the
required copper wire.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that traditional cable systems are meant to carry
signals in only one direction _ toward the home _ which is one
reason why they are sometimes called ``dumb.'' In the last few
years the cable industry has spent billions of dollars to make its
networks communicate in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   Once those two-way upgrades have been made, though, it can be
much easier for a cable operator to introduce a high-speed Internet
system. A cable operator can offer service ubiquitously throughout
a given neighborhood while telephone technicians must generally
make certain, often by hand, that the wire going to each house is
capable of supporting broadband service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that make us almost have to go out
and physically check a wire-pair to see if we can offer service,''
said John H. Atterbury, president for broadband services for SBC
Communications Inc., the largest local phone company. ``It makes it
impossible to advertise to customers to offer ubiquitous service.''
</P>
<P>
   The cable industry likes to trumpet this difference. ``Cable
gets you to every home in your footprint, and that's a huge
advantage,'' said Daniel Somers, chief executive of cable
operations for AT&AMP;T Corp., which is in the process of becoming the
nation's biggest owner of cable TV systems.
</P>
<P>
   But the phone carriers are moving quickly to catch up to cable.
SBC, for instance, has said it will spend $6 billion in the next
three years to upgrade its networks for high-speed Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, phone networks have some important advantages over
cable systems. Once a user is connected to a phone-line broadband
network, the data connection's speed is essentially guaranteed.
Cable's tree-and-branch network layout can reduce the speed of a
user's connection as more people in the same neighborhood sign on.
</P>
<P>
   That difference in basic network architecture, some engineers
say, also makes cable networks more vulnerable to malicious hackers
than phone networks are.
</P>
<P>
   So despite cable's lead, the local phone giants insist that they
will ultimately be able to offer a more attractive high-speed
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gap in time,'' said Ms. McIntosh of Bell Atlantic, ``will
turn out to be a mere nanosecond when the final verdict is in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
