<P>
   ALBRIGHT-MEXICO _ MEXICO _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
comments on her meeting with Mexico's foreign minister. (Ferriss,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   US-MIDEAST-$ADV17 _ WASHINGTON _ Momentum builds this week on
President Clinton's crusade to broker a comprehensive Mideast peace
accord before leaving office in a year. Clinton will host Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa
for a second round of negotiations beginning Wednesday; the next
day Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat comes to town,
amid talk of a Barak-Arafat peace summit under White House auspices
in the weeks ahead. (Deans, Cox News Service) MOVED SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ ATLANTA _ If, for a fleeting moment, they feel
more like hostages than refugees, they need only remember what
landed them in this poor southeast Atlanta neighborhood between a
prison and a junkyard. Hate. Oppression. War. Now, husbands are off
to work, children at school, older sons and daughters out getting
drivers' licenses, or at jobs or looking for jobs, and the Kosovar
women stay behind. Pounding bread dough on the kitchen table,
washing socks in the bathtub, listening to TV shows they can't
really follow. Most hesitate to leave their modest apartments and
venture into their neighborhood, because of their limited English
and fear for their safety. Still, life is ordinary. Life is good.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 80. WITH: Photo essay by
Rich Addicks; map. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ BERLIN, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore, who speaks Monday
at Martin Luther King Jr. ceremonies in Atlanta, sits for a
one-on-one interview with Cox Newspapers. (Shepard, Cox News
Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GAYS _ As the GOP presidential front-runner preaching
compassionate conservatism, Texas Gov. George W. Bush is reaching
out to various traditionally Democratic constituencies, including
African-Americans and Hispanics. But gays are not on the list.
Despite his soft rhetoric on gay issues compared to other
Republicans (he says he's a ``don't ask, don't tell man'' and
refuses to say he'd use sexual orientation as a litmus test for his
appointees), Bush's record in Texas is anti-gay. He opposed a hate
crimes bill that would include gays, he opposes same-sex marriage
and supported a bill banning adoptions by gays. (Greenberger,
Austin American-Statesman). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 1 p.m. EST Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RECORD _ Bush's record at a glance. (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman)
