<SLUG> BC-COX-MEXICO-ALBRIGHT-0117 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUCKING SKEPTICISM, ALBRIGHT PRAISES MEXICO FOR WAR ON DRUGS
 &HT;    By Susan Ferriss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAXACA, Mexico While Mexico faces criticism from some U.S.
lawmakers over its efforts to stop narcotics smuggling, Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright praised this country's commitment to
the war on drugs in a visit here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very evident that cooperation on
narco-traffickers is at a very good level,'' Albright told
reporters after a meeting with Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario
Green in this quaint colonial city in southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Mexico's attempts to stop drug smuggling will be in
the spotlight when the Clinton Administration makes its annual
recommendations for which countries should be ``certified'' by
Congress as reliable partners in the war on drugs. Countries that
fail to get a congressional stamp of approval face trade sanctions
or a cut-off in U.S. financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Albright arrived late Saturday night in Oaxaca, about 280 miles
south of Mexico City, following a two-day visit to Colombia and
Panama. The war on drugs dominated the tour, during which Albright
also met with Colombian President Andres Pastrana to discuss a
proposed $1.6 billion aid package to help Colombian police and
military fight traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Albright started the day Sunday in Mexico by touring the Monte
Alban pre-Colombian ruins outside Oaxaca. She and Green then met to
also discuss Mexico's concerns about the deaths of migrants
attempting to illegally cross the U.S. border and a dispute over
the United States' continuing refusal to allow Mexican commercial
trucks into U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned obviously with safety standards, as is
Mexico,'' said Albright. But she and her Mexican counterpart
believe a panel set up by the North American Free Trade Agreement
should resolve the dispute over trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two leaders touched on various topics, drugs were
clearly a central theme.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of cocaine produced in South America and smuggled
into the United States is transported through Mexico. Numerous
powerful cartels operate here, smuggling cocaine, marijuana,
heroine and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico - the United States' second-largest trading partner - has
always been certified by Congress. But approval has come only after
heated debate and denunciations by some members of Congress who
believe Mexico has largely failed in its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has failed to arrest any of the country's top drug lords,
some critics say, despite solid information as to their
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   The cartels are known to use their vast profits to bribe Mexican
law enforcement officials at all levels. In 1997 Mexico's anti-drug
czar - Gen. Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo - was arrested for consorting
with one top trafficker.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she and Green did not discuss certification during
their meeting, although they talked about bilateral cooperation on
money-laundering investigations and other drug-related topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inappropriate to make predictions,'' Albright
said when asked whether the administration planned to recommend
that Mexico be certified.
</P>
<P>
   But she and U.S. Ambassador to Mexico Jeffrey Davidow, who was
also present at the meeting, put a positive spin on Mexico's
commitment over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's leaders ``view the problems of drugs as seriously as we
do,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow told reporters that ``within the last year, there has
been an increase in cooperation'' between Mexico and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Mexican Navy seized 20 tons of cocaine off ships
traveling Mexico's coast using technology and information supplied
by American law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plain fact there are 20 tons of cocaine that are not on
our streets this year is because of that level of cooperation,''
Davidow said.
</P>
<P>
   Green said Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo has called
narcotics trafficking Mexico's ``main threat to national
security.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferris can be reached at susanF(at)coxnews.com
</P>
