<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINUX-INVESTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINUX VENDOR SET TO GET $57-MILLION INFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ TurboLinux Inc., a Linux operating system vendor
with roots in the Asian computer market, will receive a $57 million
investment on Monday from Dell Computer, Compaq Computer, Intel and
a variety of other United States computer, software and investment
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Linux, which is a version of the Unix operating system, is seen
as a growing threat to Microsoft and other proprietary operating
system vendors, particularly in Internet-related markets. It was
developed on a volunteer basis by a worldwide group of dedicated
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   The round of private funding, which is the largest to date for a
Linux company, will include investments from Applix, BEA Systems,
Citrix Systems, CSK Venture Capital, CTC, Fujitsu Support and
Service, Inprise, Legend Computer, NEC, Novell, NTT-ME Information
Xing, SCO, Seagate Technology, Toshiba and Toyo Information
Systems. August Capital and Broadview International, which were the
initial investors in the company, also participated in this
investment round.
</P>
<P>
   The investment is the latest in a wave of private and public
investments in Linux software companies like RedHat, Caldera,
LinuxCare and others. Last week, for example, Caldera announced a
private investment of $30 million, the filing of its initial public
offering and the settlement of a civil antitrust suit it had filed
against Microsoft for an amount in excess of $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   TurboLinux said it had particular strength in China and Japan.
The company adds proprietary software to Linux operating systems to
permit Internet sites to cluster together a number of computers
into so-called Web farms, creating more powerful systems.
</P>
<P>
   Linux's particular strength has been that it is more reliable
for business applications than Microsoft's Windows NT 4 operating
system. Next month Microsoft will begin shipping its Windows 2000
program, which is intended to attack the business markets that
Linux has done best in during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives claim they have solved the stability
problems in Windows with their new program. However, Linux still
will enjoy both a cost advantage as well as the advantage of easy
customization because programmers can examine and alter the Linux
source code.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1992, TurboLinux is based in San Francisco, with
offices in Beijing, Tokyo and Sydney, Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
