u f BC-DOMAIN-DISPUTES-NYT &LR;      01-16 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMAIN-DISPUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLING GROUP WINS BACK USE OF ITS NAME ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Call it ``Domain Name Smackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation has won back rights to the use of
its name in cyberspace, in the first case testing the new
international forum for resolving disputes over Internet domain
names.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of the World Intellectual Property Organization, an arm
of the United Nations, handed down the ruling Friday against a
California man accused of registering
www.worldwrestlingfederation.com with the sole intent of trying to
resell it to the organization at a ``substantial profit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first case filed and the first one resolved under a
policy begun late last year by the Internet Corp. for Assigned
Names and Numbers, or Icann, to help settle cases of reported
cybersquatting quickly and cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   And with a decision that was handed down in less than 40 days _
at a cost of a $1,000 filing fee plus lawyers' fees for the
wrestling federation _ all the parties involved said the case
offered proof that the controversial policy could work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case shows that the policy worked as it was intended,''
Louis Touton, vice president and general counsel of Icann, said.
``Victims of clear cases of cybersquatting should have a quick and
cheap way of protecting themselves from continued abuses.
Traditional court remedies are usually much more expensive and
lengthy, and remedies like this are needed to keep global
electronic commerce running on Internet time.''
</P>
<P>
   The new system, called the Uniform Dispute Resolution Process,
was the first substantive policy put in place by Icann after it was
selected by the Clinton administration to operate the Internet's
domain name system.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling group, which has owned the trademark on the World
Wrestling Federation for years, took its claim to the World
Intellectual Property Organization arbitration panel Dec. 2, just
days after the new policy was initiated and shortly after the
domain name www.worldwrestlingfederation.com was registered by a
California man through an Australian company.
</P>
<P>
   Six other cases have been filed and many more are expected in
the coming months. Network Solutions, the company that the
government had previously granted a monopoly in the lucrative
business of registering Internet names, had placed more than 1,000
disputed domain names on hold. Those disputes would now fall under
Icann's rules.
</P>
<P>
   The address of the World Wrestling Federation's Web site
currently is www.wwf.com. But Icann recently changed the rules for
domain registrations, allowing names of up to 63 characters, as
opposed to the traditional 22, to be registered. That enabled
Michael Bosman, a California stockbroker, to list the federation's
trademark as an Internet domain.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federation, Bosman contacted it three days
after registering the name, offering to sell it to them ``for a
significant profit.'' Bosman said he had originally registered the
name with the intent of hosting a wrestling fans Web site, but
decided to offer it to the federation after realizing he had
neither the capital nor technical expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman said he had been unaware of the new Icann rules
prohibiting the abusive registration of trademarks until he was hit
with a threat of costly lawsuits, and then a notice of the World
Intellectual Property Organization proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bosman said he was unhappy about having to give up the
name he paid $60 for, he said he was glad he was not forced to hire
a lawyer to fight a lawsuit from the federation, which he said had
threatened to sue him for up to $100,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he felt the WIPO process was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good organization,'' he said. ``They were fair
and unbiased and it didn't cost me a dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he conceded, ``I'm the first loser of the domain dispute
process. That's not a real good title to have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
