<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WWII-REFUGEES-NYT &LR;      01-16 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN OF CAMP SURVIVORS PLEDGE TO KEEP THEIR STORIES ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This weekend's conference on the experience of
Jewish displaced persons after World War II teemed with tales,
sometimes zany ones, about the resourcefulness of people who were
left with nothing and, often, no one.
</P>
<P>
   One Holocaust survivor's daughter, Toby Blum Dobkin, read an
account by her father, Boris Blum, of how after Dachau he found
himself in front of a mirror with other inmates still in their
striped uniforms and was so shriveled he could not pick himself
out. ``The person I saw in the mirror was one that I had never seen
before in my life,'' her father wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the next day, he and two friends had enough spirit to
celebrate their freedom by converting a large red cloth they had
scavenged into a red carpet and a feathered hat into a crown and
puckishly pretending they were royalty on parade on the streets of
their tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   The almost 1,000 people here were also struck by the
resourcefulness of the children of those refugees, daughters and
sons like Romana Strochlitz Primus and Menachem Z. Rosensaft who
put together this conference and chose as its theme a period that
they directly experienced, since many of them were born in the 90
camps in Germany, Austria and Italy set up by the Allies for the
DPs, as refugees were known.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the children _ most of them accomplished professionals
whose university educations gave the conference its seminar-like
structure _ who have effectively declared with this conference that
they will pick up the reins of leadership from their aging parents
and keep up the memory and culture of the slaughtered 6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the survivors are now in their late 70s or early 80s
_ the nation's second-largest survivors' community after New York
is now South Florida. Survivor leaders like Miles Lerman and
Benjamin Meed pressed for Holocaust remembrance to become a
50-state phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   A concession to the realities of time was made this weekend when
Lerman, longtime chairman of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council,
the federal organization which governs the museum here and
sponsored the conference, told the audience he was yielding his
chairmanship as soon as President Clinton appoints a successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come,'' he said, ``to begin the process of
passing the torch to a new generation,'' Lerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors' children _ who call themselves Second Generation
or, frivolously, 2G _ have noted how difficult it is to animate an
event 55 years after it occurred, that except in the history books,
few epic tragedies seem to endure beyond the lives of their victims
and perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   But Elie Wiesel, who delivered a keynote speech in which he
expressed worries that the Holocaust had become ``a fashionable
endeavor,'' thinks the survivors' children are in a privileged
position.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe a person who listens to a witness becomes a
witness,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable number of the survivors' children have dedicated
important parts of their lives to keeping alive their parents'
story. Ms. Dobkin, a folklorist born in the Landsberg DP camp,
collects richly textured tales. Sam Norich, born in the Feldafing
DP camp, keeps a Yiddish newspaper alive as general manager of the
Forward Association. Aviva Kempner has made a film about the
partisans of Vilna. Thane Rosenbaum writes post-Holocaust novels
like ``Second Hand Smoke.'' Eva Fogelman, born in the Kassel DP
camp, is a psychologist who runs therapy groups about growing up in
survivor families.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech, Norich recalled that after the death of his mother,
he realized that ``it was now up to me to give her life, that the
genetic and biological relationship between us _ that she had given
me life _ was now reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   The children come at the task from often clashing perspectives.
Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., who was born in Eschwege DP camp,
urged the audience to be alert not just to repression of Jews, but
to repression of others like the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts at universalism were not for Melvin Jules Bukiet, a
novelist and professor of literature at Sarah Lawrence College. He
read an introduction to an upcoming anthology of Second Generation
writers, in which he talked of children angrier than their
necessarily adaptive parents, less concerned with the ``insipid
fetish for healing,'' more concerned with the Holocaust's
singularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we rub the world's nose in our misery,'' he said. ``Go to
our museums, go see our movies, go read our books, look at what you
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bukiet uses the blue number tattooed on his father's arm _
108016 _ as the code to enter his computer and once presented a
novel he wrote to a baffled Helmut Kohl, the former chancellor of
Germany, signed with that number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
