<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT     01-16 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS WILL BE A PARCELLS TEAM WHETHER OR NOT HE RETURNS TO COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago Monday, the New York Jets took a halftime lead at
Mile High Stadium over the team favored to win the Super Bowl _ the
Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   It was the American Football Conference championship game, and
although the Jets wound up 30 minutes short of the Super Bowl, Jets
players, coaches and fans could see a brighter future 365 days
away.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they wound up short of the playoffs and short of a
coach after starting the season short of an owner and losing a
quarterback in their opening game.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of days, though, the biggest questions facing the
team should be resolved. The National Football League owners are
expected Tuesday to approve Robert Wood Johnson IV as the Jets' new
owner. Johnson wants to maintain stability and will probably move
quickly in naming a coach, either by persuading Bill Parcells to
return in that role or by appointing Al Groh to the job.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which way that decision goes, Parcells' fingerprints
will probably be seen on the organization and on the field. Groh
has limited administrative experience, so decisions about personnel
and other matters would be overseen by Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson is approved as owner, Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
will rule on the status of Bill Belichick, who resigned as Jets
head coach after one day on the job two weeks ago and is trying to
win the right to work elsewhere _ presumably as the coach and
general manager of the New England Patriots. Tagliabue may well
decide that Belichick remains bound to his Jets contract, which
would mean the Patriots would probably give the Jets draft picks in
exchange for Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' status remains the biggest mystery. He met with
Johnson for two hours last Friday, the second time they had met in
three days. But at least some of Parcells' assistants were in the
dark on Parcells' plans this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, the Jets players are awaiting the decision,
although they profess not to be overly concerned about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if people are running around screaming,''
linebacker Chad Cascadden said.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that might be because change is an accepted part of
life in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year you lose some of your teammates,'' said the Jets'
backup safety and special-teams star, Chris Hayes, who was a member
of the Super Bowl champion Green Bay Packers three years ago.
``What I learned in this business, playing on a Super Bowl team, is
that it's hard to keep a team together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes professes not to be overly concerned about the possibility
of a coaching change, even on a club that was supposed to be a
Super Bowl contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take it that whoever's in there, Bill Parcells will get the
right guy,'' Hayes said. ``I kind of wished Belichick was in there.
He knows the players. He also coached the DBs. So I'm losing a lot
by Bill not being there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said he spoke to Keyshawn Johnson by phone the other day,
and Johnson told him, ``So Belichick's out?'' but that the
conversation then shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're out of football we try not to talk football,''
Hayes said. ``When I talked to Keyshawn we didn't try to read
anything into it. I respect this business for what it is _ and
that's strictly business. I don't read into it between the lines
because I know it's not personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jumbo Elliott believes Parcells might yet come back, calling it
``the popular opinion right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows who's going to be there and who's going to be part
of important schemes?'' Hayes said. ``Belichick's gone, and he's a
big part of the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude is if you want to go to the Super Bowl, you go
with Parcells _ and if he doesn't want to go, he'll find someone
who does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1848EST &QL; 
