<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-HAMPTON-2TAK     01-16 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HAMPTON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' HAMPTON DEVELOPED THE WILL TO WIN FROM HIS DEMANDING FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wicked line drive shocked the 7-year-old pitcher, who
quickly raised his glove yet still missed the ball. It struck his
nose and blood oozed out of each nostril. He looked to the dugout,
where his father instructed him to go to the water fountain, wipe
away the blood and return to the mound. That is what Mike Hampton
did.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Hampton, who might have been recuperating
with an ice pack and a teddy bear if he were any other 7-year-old,
was pitching again for the Phillies in the Homosassa, Fla., Little
League. That is the way Mike Sr. raised him and the way Mike Jr.
wanted to be raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a chance to pick the perfect son, I probably would
have come up with Michael,'' said the father. ``He is everything
that I wanted to be. It might be a bad thing to say, but I was
going to make him be a ballplayer one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The son listened intently to his father's daily lectures about
second place being the first loser, about working harder and longer
than everyone and about remaining respectful while surpassing
others to pursue his sports dreams. Never rebellious, the devoted
son always acquiesced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew the harder he pushed me, the more I'd want to do it
and the more I'd push myself,'' said Hampton. ``It was a lot harder
than most people would push their kids or anyone else. I owe my
competitiveness and drive to him. He pushed me to do everything as
hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   The pushing, the nudging, the guiding, the cajoling, the
encouraging has never stopped between Big Mike and Little Mike, the
nicknames that still cling to the two men like Velcro. Big Mike is
still the voice of God to his son, the voice that Little Mike has
heard throughout his 27 years. The voice that he will continue to
hear now that he is the ace starter for the Mets, after being
snared from the Houston Astros in a trade last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Big Mike what the Mets will receive from Little Mike and he
offers a scouting report that does not mention Hampton's cut
fastball or his 22-4 record last season. He talks about the
intangibles of a pitcher who is unlike any in the major leagues, a
tremendous athlete who happens to be a terrific pitcher. Brad
Ausmus, Detroit's All-Star catcher and one of Hampton's former
teammates, told Big Mike that Little Mike is the first left-handed
starter he would pick if he was starting a new franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't pitch for a victory, he pitches to win,'' Ausmus
said. ``Some players never learn that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton slides forcefully into second to break up double plays,
he hustles out grounders like a rookie, he will be one of the
faster players on the team and he has the talent to be one of the
Mets' best defensive outfielders. Seriously. Hampton sometimes gets
to the ballpark at 7:30 a.m. to work out before day games and he
always wears spikes in the dugout, in case the team needs a
pinch-runner or a pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out there, I'm doing whatever it takes to help my
team win,'' said Hampton. ``If that means taking one off the face
or jumping in front of a ball or hitting or getting hit with a
pitch, I'll do it. That goes back to the way I was raised to win at
all costs.''
</P>
<P>
   When Michael William Hampton was born in Brooksville, Fla., on
Sept. 9, 1972, his father was 19 and his mother, Joan, was 16. Big
Mike, who laments how he did not pursue a sports career, pursued it
through his son and said the two ``grew up together.'' The younger
Hampton was walking at 8 months old and was separated from other
5-year-olds in school and placed with 8-year-olds because he threw
too hard. As an eighth grader, Hampton predicted that he would
become a professional athlete. Hampton's friends giggled. His
father smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he believed,'' Mike Sr. said, ``I had to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Hampton watched Big Mike control Little Mike and often
cringed. She was the one who hugged her crying son when his father
pulled him off the field or made him sit by himself in the car for
not hustling. She was the one whose car Little Mike fled to after a
rare shabby performance. She was the one who unsuccessfully asked
her husband to relax his strict methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to see, but he was preparing him for what his
life is like today,'' she said. ``Michael wouldn't have made it if
he just had my heart and my easygoing way. I'd cry if somebody
booed me. He needed to have that toughness and that stubbornness.
He would not be where he is without his dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Mike is an assistant coach under Joe Buccheri at Crystal
River High School, the job he accepted when his son was a freshman.
Buccheri, a native of Flushing, N.Y., and a former batting practice
pitcher for the St. Louis Cardinals, called Hampton ``the most
gifted athlete'' he has even seen.
</P>
<P>
   Little Mike could dunk a basketball, he could bench-press 300
pounds, he could do back and front flips like a gymnast and he was
such a good defensive back that Notre Dame, Miami and Florida State
recruited him.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the perception that he might be showing his son
favoritism, Big Mike kept challenging an athlete who was twice
named all-state in football and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike was real hard on Michael, but they were still like
brothers,'' said Buccheri.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hampton loved tackling players and ``looking in
their eyes and realizing you got them,'' he picked baseball over
football. At 5 feet 10 inches and 170 pounds, Hampton knew he would
have to add bulk to play college football and that would destroy
his flexibility as a pitcher. While Hampton was cocky, he was
realistic. His father taught him about realism, too.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Big Mike owns Cedar Key Fish and Oyster Co. and he made his son
work for him when Little Mike turned 15. The younger Hampton hated
it. His father would rap on his bedroom door at 6:30 a.m. on a
Saturday to wake him for work. Tired from a Friday night game,
Little Mike waited to see if his father would leave him behind, but
he never did. So Hampton gutted, filleted, packed and froze fish
for $4.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me that I didn't want to do that,'' said Hampton.
``Not only was it hard, I couldn't stand smelling like that. You
didn't get that smell off in one night.''
</P>
<P>
   Between laughs over Little Mike's memories of handling fish, Big
Mike said his strategy succeeded and a lesson was learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to work to achieve his goals so he wouldn't have
to do this kind of work,'' Big Mike said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who was drafted out of high school in the sixth round
by Seattle in 1990, made it to the majors with the Mariners when he
was 20. After failing to please Manager Lou Piniella, he was traded
to Houston after the 1993 season, broke into the Astro rotation in
1995 and went 48-21 over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   He might be one of the top five starters in baseball, but
Hampton still peers over his shoulder and hopes. The new Met would
love it if Manager Bobby Valentine took the baseball from him one
day and asked him to retreat 300 feet and chase fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could give up pitching right now to go play in the
outfield, I'd do it in a heartbeat,'' Hampton said. ``But I pitch
better than I can hit or play the outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton credited his .311 batting average of last season to
being fed fastballs. Hampton said he would hit in the .200s with
intense practice, but he added, ``but I'd hustle and do other
things and make you want me on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dierker, the Astros manager, said, ``I think if he had
tried for a career in baseball as an outfielder, he would have made
it to the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton made it as a pitcher, a plan his father devised when
Little Mike was still in diapers. When Big Mike was asked if he
felt that he had ever been too difficult on his son, he quickly
answered no. He was stern yet supportive, demanding yet loving. He
decided his son would be a major leaguer and then Big Mike and
Little Mike worked together to achieve that dream, a dual dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell what he did for me,'' said Hampton Sr., his voice
quivering. ``He sent me a bat when he made it to the majors and he
wrote on it, `To my Dad, all I ever want to be and more.' I told
him that having a son who feels that way about me means more to me
than anything in the world.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7560 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-IOWA-GORE-LABOR-960(2     01-16 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-GORE-LABOR-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR MOBILIZES TO SUPPORT GORE IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Al Gore can be thankful that this state is
more than an unending field of corn.
</P>
<P>
   Punctuating the prairies that most Americans see as the essence
of this state are dozens of industrial plants that serve the
agricultural economy, and the heavily unionized work force in these
farm-equipment factories and meat-packing plants is a major factor
behind the Gore camp's confidence that the vice president will win
Iowa's Jan. 24 caucuses, the first big test in this year's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa's caucuses, success traditionally turns on who has the
best organization, and the state's 150,000-member labor movement,
because it is so big and well organized, gives Gore an extra weapon
to use against his Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of labor in this thing is huge,'' said David Yepsen,
the chief political reporter for The Des Moines Register. ``They've
always been a big player in the caucuses. They're a key
constituency in the Democratic Party here.''
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding labor's dismay at the Clinton administration's
trade policies, Iowa's union movement has gone into overdrive in
the past two weeks in an attempt to give Gore a convincing caucus
victory. With the AFL-CIO having endorsed Gore in October, over the
opposition of the Teamsters and Autoworkers, the Iowa caucuses are
shaping up as a major test not just for Gore but for John Sweeney,
the labor federation's president.
</P>
<P>
   To pump up turnout, Sweeney's foot soldiers have telephoned more
than 30,000 union members who are registered Democrats. The
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees has
sent four separate pro-Gore mailings to its 12,000 members in the
state _ and the AFL-CIO has done three additional mailings to union
members. The organization has even mailed 30,000 five-minute videos
in which Sweeney urges union members to participate in the
caucuses, while telling them, ``Al Gore is America's foremost
champion of today's unions.''
</P>
<P>
   But labor's push has stumbled into two formidable problems. Two
of the state's biggest unions _ the Autoworkers and the Teamsters _
are not campaigning for Gore and have asked the AFL-CIO not to urge
their members to back the vice president. Second, many union
members cannot get excited about Gore and seem to care more about
Monday night football than about the Monday night caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaning toward Gore, but I'm getting tired of the whole
process,'' said Gary Mobley, a member of the United Steelworkers of
America who said he would not attend a caucus. ``This is all taking
place far too long before the election.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at the state AFL-CIO's aging, brick headquarters, a
half-dozen union members _ working at a phone bank beneath the
original, century-old charter that Samuel Gompers signed to set up
Iowa's labor federation _ were using one of the oldest tricks in
labor's electoral playbook. (They were also following one of
Gompers' maxims: ``Stand faithfully by our friends and elect
them.'')
</P>
<P>
   First, the callers asked the hundreds of union members they
contacted whether they supported Gore or Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   If the union members said they backed Bradley, the callers said
``Thank you'' and hung up. But if the union members favored Gore,
they were encouraged to attend the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   And if Gore supporters said they would miss the caucuses because
they had to attend a child's basketball game or swim meet, the
callers turned on the hard sell, warning that missing the caucuses
was tantamount to voting against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much harder to get people to go out to the caucuses than
to vote in a primary,'' said Mark Smith, the chain-smoking former
economics professor who is president of the state's AFL-CIO.
``You're asking people to make a two-hour commitment at a school or
somewhere when the wind chill might be 46 below.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest generation of union members is hardly familiar with
the process, because labor has not shepherded its flocks to the
caucuses since 1984, the last time the AFL-CIO endorsed a candidate
in the Democratic presidential primaries. That year, labor backed
Vice President Walter Mondale over Sen. Gary Hart.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's 2,142 precinct caucuses, to be held in schools,
town halls and homes, Iowans will be asked to move to one part of a
room to show support for their candidate. To familiarize union
members with this awkward process, the AFL-CIO is organizing mock
caucuses in Cedar Rapids, Davenport, Waterloo and 10 other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that 100,000 of Iowa's union members are registered
to vote, 20,000 as Republicans, 30,000 as independents and 50,000
as Democrats, accounting for one-tenth of Iowa's Democrats. But by
mobilizing their masses, labor officials hope union members will
represent far more than one-tenth of the participants in the
Democratic caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that when Democratic union members were polled about
candidates, 50 percent said they were undecided or gave no answer,
30 percent backed Gore, 15 percent supported Bradley and 5 percent
favored others, ranging from Jesse Jackson to Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's program, Smith explained, is straightforward, to remind
union members that Gore has backed labor on many issues, opposing
Medicare cuts, backing a higher minimum wage, refusing to cross a
picket line during a strike at ABC. The next step is to mobilize
Gore supporters to attend the caucuses, an effort that has involved
shop stewards talking to workers and knocking on union members'
doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magic bullet,'' Smith said. ``It's like Woody
Hayes, the Ohio State football coach, used to say, `Three yards and
a cloud of dust.' You don't have to dream up anything fancy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Labor's pro-Gore push has revved up many members. Mark Rocha, a
service delivery coordinator with US West, said he would definitely
support Gore. ``The vice president has always been an ally of the
Communications Workers, on family issues, on the right to
organize,'' he said. ``True, he doesn't knock my socks off, but I'm
not looking for that. He's upbeat. He's strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's union leaders voice confidence that labor will make
an impressive caucus showing _ and the Bradley campaign has
acknowledged as much, perhaps to lower expectations for Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor has the potential to make a big difference,'' said Eric
Hauser, spokesman for the Bradley campaign. ``Their organized clout
is real. Senator Bradley tried to get their attention and support,
but they went the other way. We respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has periodically visited Iowa union halls in the hope of
reaching out directly to members. But his efforts have been
undercut by several union mailings that have hammered him, accusing
him of supporting school vouchers and raising the age for Social
Security _ accusations that the Bradley campaign says are
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding their attacks on Bradley, union leaders say
their members are generally fond of the New Jerseyan and would have
little problem backing him if he wins the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gore doesn't survive the process, we'll endorse someone
else and rally the troops for that person,'' said Dan Albritton,
the steelworkers' political director for Iowa. ``If it's Bradley
vs. George W. Bush, it's easy, because there are such clear-cut
differences. Bush is totally anti-labor as far as I'm concerned. We
wouldn't have problems getting our people fired up if the dog
catcher ran against George W. Bush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
