<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 17, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, winds exceeded 100 miles an hour at Cannon Beach along
the Oregon coast as a tightly wound low pressure system moved into
western Canada. Monday, a weaker low center and its attendant cold
front will approach the Northwest coast, bringing windswept rain to
coastal Washington and Oregon. Farther inland, the moist Pacific
air will cool as it ascends the Cascades, setting the stage for
heavy snow above 3,000 feet. Snow showers will also pepper many of
the west-facing mountain slopes of the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a plume of moisture originating from the central
Pacific Ocean will send a thick shield of clouds Monday into the
Southwest. Spotty light showers will fall from southern California
to western Colorado. Farther east, mild conditions will stretch
from southern New Mexico to the western Gulf Coast as the jet
stream retreats to the north. Indeed, amid ample sunshine many
places will surpass 70 degrees Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will end Monday across eastern Maine as a strengthening
storm grinds toward the Canadian Maritimes. A formidable pressure
difference between the low and polar high pressure over Ontario
will promote gusty winds across the Northeast. Wind speeds will be
highest over eastern New England where gusts will exceed 65 miles
an hour. It will also be bitterly cold across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, warm, humid air ascending a dome of chilly air along
the ground will cause patchy freezing rain and sleet near the
southern Ohio and middle Mississippi Valleys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE POWER OF WIND
</P>
<P>
   Strong winds from the northwest will blow over New England
Monday, causing a hazard for drivers of high-profile vehicles,
especially those traveling north or south. When the wind blows, it
exerts a force on a given area of an object. As the wind increases,
its force increases as the square of the wind speed. That is, the
force per unit area of a wind of 20 mph is four times greater than
the force of a wind of 10 mph Thus, the total force exerted on a
vehicle which has a high profile and thus a large area can become
mighty when crosswinds are strong, causing the driver to possibly
lose control of the vehicle. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
