<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-IOWA-TOWN-BUSH-NYT &LR;      01-16 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-TOWN-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PUTS SMALL IOWA TOWN ON THE MAP _ FOR A DAY, AT LEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Neb.)  (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RED OAK, Iowa _ Word of the big visit leaked days ago. ``I heard
rumblings on the street last week,'' said Jan Castle Renander,
editor of the weekly Red Oak Express.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday she had it nailed down, and on Tuesday ran the news at
the top of the front page: ``George W. Bush Coming to Red Oak.'' On
Wednesday, John Gambs, a government teacher at Red Oak High School,
decided that he would push back final exams so that his students
could meet the candidate. And all day Thursday, Jerry Dietz, owner
of and on-air talent for the FM radio station KCSI, was busy
beating the drums, telling listeners he would be at the event, and
they might want to be, too.
</P>
<P>
   So by the time Bush and his entourage rolled off Route 48 on
Friday and into this welcoming little town dotted with Victorian
houses and ringed by cornfields and cattle farms, Red Oak was
primed. The Gold Auditorium on the county fairgrounds was festooned
with Bush posters, and every seat in the hall was taken. Mayor
Karen Blue was there, wearing a Bush sticker. Ms. Renander's
husband, Clayton, was there too, having put off feeding the calves
to attend, and so was Dietz's camera-toting assistant, Barb Allen,
who chased after her teenage son Brayton, trying to get him in a
picture with the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   To the members of the Bush team and the journalists following
them, the visit might have been all but indistinguishable from 100
other campaign stops: a not particularly noteworthy media event.
But for the people of Red Oak, a town of 6,200 in the hilly farm
belt of southwest Iowa, the visit had a deeper impact. It was a
moment that made them feel part of a larger process and one they
hoped somehow would reflect well on their community in the eyes of
a nation that ordinarily does not pay them much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a town like ours, this is a very big deal,'' said Ms.
Renander, whose yellowing front-page story about a 1987 visit to
Red Oak by Bush's father, then the vice president, hangs on the
wall of Gambs' classroom. ``It's seeing him in the flesh, saving
the clip from the paper _ something to tell the kids about later
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Oak doesn't make much news. Tucked into a rural corridor,
and closer to Omaha, Neb., than to Des Moines, Iowa, the town is
something of a media afterthought in the coverage of events like
the Iowa caucuses. The state paper, The Des Moines Register,
stopped home delivery here a few years ago; it is the Nebraska
television stations that Red Oak antennas pick up. ``The joke
around here is no one sees a reporter from The Register unless
there's bad news,'' Ms. Renander said.
</P>
<P>
   No one sees a candidate very often, either. ``Sometimes, we'll
get a wife,'' Gambs said. It's understandable, then, that while Des
Moines or even Davenport might greet the arrival of a national
office-seeker these days with a bit of a yawn, Red Oak is more
prone to gasp.
</P>
<P>
   And especially when the candidate is from a well-known
Republican family. Red Oak is, after all, a robustly Republican
town, the seat of largely Republican Montgomery County, which went
for Bob Dole in 1996, when Iowa as a whole went for Bill Clinton.
It is a profoundly patriotic place, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is George W. Bush country,'' George Maher, a banker and
lifelong resident, observed as he took a visitor around, showing
off the Red Oak sights. He drove past the old country club and the
new YMCA going up; the old factory where Thomas Murphy Co. made the
nation's first illustrated calendars in the 1890s, and the newer
plants manufacturing automotive parts and prefabricated windows and
turning corn into tortilla flour for a Mexican business.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Bush is a kind of unofficial favorite son here _ ``The
people I know who are backing him are some of the leaders of the
community,'' Mayor Blue said _ Red Oak is having a slightly more
difficult time working up much enthusiasm for the contest. The town
has its share of worries. The prices for corn and hogs are severely
depressed, and a steady drain of young people has left the area
with one of the state's grayest populations. But the county's
unemployment rate is 2 percent, the offices and plants are
virtually full, and a $10 million bond issue was recently passed
for a new elementary school wing and high school technology lab.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Red Oak is feeling pretty good about itself, not
exactly the atmosphere for political introspection or discontent.
``I don't sense that anyone is what I would call excited,'' Gambs
said. Ms. Blue added that since ``everything is going pretty well,
except agricultural prices,'' the race is ``still peripheral. And
the process starts so far in advance, it's hard to stir up interest
and keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Bell, assistant manager of the Tru Value hardware store on
Route 48, said he saw pluses and minuses in each of the Republican
contenders, and seemed to be looking for something more. He said he
found Bush likable, favored Steve Forbes' flat tax proposal and
respected John McCain's war record. ``If only we could pull the
good things out of each of them and put them together in one man,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   But for one day, anyway, the presidency as far as Red Oak was
concerned was a one-man race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard many, many comments about how lucky we are that
he's coming to Red Oak,'' said Jeanette Peterson, a member of a
local Republican women's group. The crowd for the candidate's 8:30
a.m. arrival began gathering in the auditorium an hour before. And
by the time Bush, in a crisp blue suit and red tie, walked briskly
up to the podium and, framed by a mural depicting an Iowa farm,
began to speak, 500 faces were staring back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here in Red Oak askin' for the vote,'' Bush said, with a
bit more country in his voice than can be detected in his
television commercials. ``I'm askin' for you to do your duty.''
</P>
<P>
   He drew applause after he said that being a mother was the
toughest job in America, and again when he said, ``I trust the
people of Iowa to make the right decisions for the children of
Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambs thought he had done pretty well. ``He's much better on the
stump than he is in the debates, isn't he?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd swarmed Bush afterward. He stayed in the hall for
another hour or so, posing for pictures and autographing posters.
Andrea Jensen, a senior in Gambs' government class, was surprised
by her own reaction. ``I didn't think he'd be that funny,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Ms. Renander headed back to The Express, with
her notes and her camera, and Dietz, who broadcast live from the
Gold Auditorium, pulled up the duct tape that had secured his cable
to the floor. Bush and his retinue, meanwhile, motored on to
Glenwood, another Iowa town that does not find its name much in the
out-of-town papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
