<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK DELAYS THIRD WEST BANK TRANSFER, ANGERING PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel decided to
postpone a withdrawal from the West Bank due to take place later
this week, senior Palestinian officials reacted Sunday by
condemning the Israelis, saying they were souring the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who is scheduled to leave Tuesday for Washington to
resume peace talks with Syria, told his cabinet Sunday that he
would attend to the land transfer on his return. Officials said the
prime minister had not had sufficient time to review the maps and
present them to his cabinet for approval before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with that explanation, Barak's postponement heightened
Palestinians' concerns that the Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations
would adversely affect them. Some Palestinians fear that Israeli
officials and American mediators will be distracted and that their
peace track will be relegated to second-class status.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a senior Israeli official, in discussing the delay
Sunday night, said, ``You have to take into consideration the
Syrian track. It takes our energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The land transfer was supposed to take place on Thursday under
the interim peace agreement signed last September in Sharm el
Sheik, Egypt. It was to have been the third and final Israeli
withdrawal under the interim agreement, giving the Palestinians
full or partial control over about 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is totally rejected, and it is a blow to all our
attempts to create a partnership,'' said Saeb Erekat, a Palestinian
negotiator. He added that the Israelis did not consult with the
Palestinians, despite regular talks between the two sides, but made
a ``unilateral decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians have been speculating that the Israeli
government might include some Arab neighborhoods just outside
Jerusalem in the next withdrawal. If true, this would make the land
transfer a sensitive political issue for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of many Israelis, giving back land near Jerusalem
under the interim agreement would be premature since the final
status of Jerusalem is under negotiation in the permanent peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   With Jerusalem as one of the most complex issues before them,
Israelis and Palestinians are heading into an intensive period of
negotiations to hammer out a framework agreement for final peace by
Feb. 13. It is another deadline that may well end up being
postponed.
</P>
<P>
   At different moments, both Israelis and Palestinians have
accused each other of stalling the framework negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In postponing this withdrawal, Barak seems to be inching closer
to the position he put forth last summer _ that the third
withdrawal should take place in mid-February. Before the Sharm el
Sheik agreement was signed, Barak unsuccessfully tried to persuade
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, to link the third withdrawal
with the successful completion of a framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat did not agree, and a Jan. 20 deadline was set for the
third withdrawal. The prime minister's office said Sunday that when
the Sharm el Sheik agreement was signed, the Palestinians also
verbally agreed that a three-week extension would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to make sure it happened before the framework
agreement, and this will be the case,'' said Gadi Baltiansky,
Barak's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak doesn't intend to violate the Sharm agreement,'' he
added. ``But Barak wants to see the overall picture first.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is flying to the United States this week, too, to meet
with President Clinton and to present him with the Palestinian
outline for the final status. It is possible that there will also
be a three-way meeting with the Israelis, to discuss where final
negotiations stand.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said Barak did not want to risk a miniature
crisis with the Palestinians before that meeting, in the event
there was a dispute about the territory Israel selected for the
land transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The second withdrawal was significantly delayed because of a
bitter disagreement over the maps, but took place earlier this
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
