<HEADER>
A7573 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-BUDGET-BATTLE-2TAKES-     01-16 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-BATTLE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR U.S. BUDGET, THE BIGGER THE SURPLUS, THE BIGGER THE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.M., Ohio, Miss., S.C.)   (jw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress and the Clinton administration are heading
into another battle over taxes and spending, with a bigger pot of
money on the table, no consensus on how to use it and election year
politics complicating the prospects for any compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of the fight are sure to be similar to the
standoffs of the last few years, with Republicans pressing for tax
cuts, Democrats proposing spending programs and both sides happy to
end up on the middle ground of using the federal budget surplus to
reduce the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle this year is likely to be magnified by two
factors: official projections to be released in the next few weeks
that members of both parties said would show the surplus growing
significantly larger relative to last year's estimates, and the
attention focused on fiscal politics by the presidential campaign,
where the leading candidates are setting out starkly different
views of how the nation should use its prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awfully big piggy bank for people to play with this
year,'' said Richard May, a former Republican staff director for
the House Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The first budget tussle of the legislative year is likely to be
over how big a surplus the nation should count on over the next
decade. Some Republicans want to use one set of numbers that show a
particularly sharp increase over previous surplus projections,
reflecting the flood of revenues into the Treasury as the economy
continues roaring along.
</P>
<P>
   By some preliminary estimates circulating on Capitol Hill, the
portion of the surplus generated by non-Social Security tax
receipts could amount to almost $2 trillion over the next decade
using the arithmetic favored by those Republicans, nearly twice the
10-year projection made last year. Such projections assume that
annually appropriated spending would be cut by tens of billions of
dollars this year and then frozen for the next decade, an
assumption that Democrats consider politically preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Queasy about the prospect of calling for big spending cuts in an
election year, other Republicans, including Sen. Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, are
considering adopting another set of assumptions under which
spending would be frozen more or less at current levels. Such a
step would result in a somewhat lower surplus estimate than the
projection that starts with the assumption of a spending cut.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and many Democrats in Congress would prefer to
calculate the surplus after accounting for anticipated and
already-agreed-to spending increases, yielding a surplus estimate
likely to be hundreds of billions of dollars less than either
Republican version over the next decade, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the surplus projections will be increasing
rather than decreasing, and by a fairly significant amount,'' said
Rep. John Spratt Jr., D-S.C., the senior Democrat on the House
Budget Committee. ``But we have to make everyone understand the
underlying assumptions, which are not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is likely to be a related fight over whether Congress
and the administration should formally drop the spending limits
that were adopted a decade ago to help deal with huge budget
deficits. Congress evaded the spending caps the last two years
through use of accounting gimmicks amid a tacit understanding on
both sides that the limits at their current levels were not
politically sustainable in an era of swelling surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who have been briefed on the White House's plans said
President Clinton was willing to propose scrapping the existing
caps, scheduled to expire in 2002. But Clinton would insist that
the old caps be replaced with new, higher limits that would be
extended through the rest of the decade, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials declined to comment on their plan. But
they made little secret of their position that the current caps had
little value given the way Congress had maneuvered around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans clearly shredded the budget caps last year
with gimmicks and sleight of hand,'' said Gene Sperling, the White
House economic policy adviser. Clinton's budget, he said, will have
``a straightforward, fiscally disciplined path that will ensure we
pay off the national debt within 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican leaders, including Domenici and Rep. John Kasich
of Ohio, the chairman of the House Budget Committee, have signaled
that they are open to a deal on resetting the caps, especially if
Clinton takes the first step.
</P>
<P>
   But they face potential resistance from their party's more
conservative members, who are sure to object to anything that
smacks of a retreat from fiscal discipline, especially in an
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress made little headway last year in shifting from a system
set up to reduce budget deficits to creating a new system to deal
with the prospect of long-running surpluses. The main mechanism for
fiscal discipline was a pledge by both parties not to touch any of
the portion of the surplus generated by Social Security. The Social
Security surplus was projected last year to be $2 trillion over 10
years, and is likely to be even higher under new projections to be
issued by the Congressional Budget Office on Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Republican-led Congress passed a budget for the
current fiscal year that appeared to spend all of the non-Social
Security surplus and to dip $17 billion into the Social Security
trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong economy now appears to be generating enough
unanticipated tax revenue to get the Republicans off the hook. In a
letter last week to Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader,
Domenici said new calculations by the budget committee showed that
the government would not have to use any Social Security money in
the current year, and indeed would run a non-Social Security
surplus of up to $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With the surplus continuing to pile up, Republicans remain as
committed as ever to tax cuts. In the House, Kasich is developing a
plan under which he would reserve most of the non-Social Security
surplus for tax cuts or debt reduction to thwart an end-of-session
spending binge.
</P>
<P>
   The result could well be another stalemate, in which some money
goes to additional spending and the rest goes to reducing the
national debt but neither side gets any major legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a post-impeachment environment in which Republicans
don't work with Democrats,'' said Stanley Collender, managing
director of the Federal Budget Consulting Group at Fleishman
Hillard, a public relations firm. ``And you're in an election year
where Democrats think they have a shot at taking over at least the
House and are not going to want to give the Republicans anything
they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some members of both parties take seriously the prospect of
a bipartisan deal. They are talking about tradeoffs under which
Republicans would get limited tax cuts, such as a reduction in the
so-called marriage penalty paid by many two-income couples, while
Democrats would win the addition of a prescription drug benefit to
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans leaders in the House have already abandoned their
call for a single big tax-cutting package and replaced it with a
push for a series of smaller tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton appears to be backing away from his
insistence that any tax cuts or other big new initiatives await
agreement on a plan to assure Social Security's long-term solvency,
something that neither party expects to attempt this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1924EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
