<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7577 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANT-A     01-16 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TIMES SQUARE, A NEW GENERATION OF TRUANTS, HOOKED ON MTV 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police roundups are never accompanied by a
reading of the suspects' Miranda rights. Instead, the lieutenant in
charge usually asks two questions: ``Do you want to work at
McDonald's for the rest of your life? Do you want to super-size my
fries?''
</P>
<P>
   The suspects are junior high and high school students, and they
are playing hooky in the kind of place that has lured truants for
more than a generation: a shiny new mall. The only difference is
that this place is called Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   And if any doubt remains that it has become a mall, just ask the
nearest teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Like Juan Morales, a clean-cut eighth-grader from Queens, who
skipped class with three friends last Tuesday and took the No. 7
train to Times Square ``because of, like, the new stuff _ MTV and
the Virgin Megastore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he quickly added, ``to check out girls, man.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his friends managed to check out only one girl before
they were rounded up by the Police Department's truancy patrol. ``I
guess we learned our lesson today,'' Juan said sarcastically upon
his release. Then he grinned, his braces glinting, and the four
headed back to Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there has probably never been a time _ from the era
of nickelodeons and burlesque right up through kung fu movies and
peep shows _ when the area was not a haunt for teen-agers gone
AWOL.
</P>
<P>
   But police officials say that now, the troubled truants looking
for pornography or fake ID cards or drugs have been replaced by
even more students of all kinds from around the metropolitan
region, who are cutting classes to seek out the relatively
wholesome alternatives offered by corporate America in the new
Times Square. They come for high-priced compact discs, high-priced
movies and the rare chance to stand on a crowded sidewalk for hours
for a fleeting glimpse of a rock band appearing at the MTV studios.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Helen Rossi, who has been patrolling Midtown for truants
since 1983, said that during most of her years on the job, the 42nd
Street area attracted primarily ``runaways, and kids who had
warrants, and juvenile delinquents.'' Searches of the truants often
turned up guns and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' she said, ``kids are coming to see 'N Sync.''
</P>
<P>
   Searches, when they are conducted, usually turn up cell phones
with Mom's number on the speed dial.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell exactly how many truants are showing up in
Times Square on an average school day, police officials say. Most
are coming from schools in the five boroughs, although officers
also commonly find students from Long Island, New Jersey and
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the borough of Manhattan, the police find far fewer
truants every year _ between 5,000 and 6,000 _ than they did a
decade ago, when the number sometimes reached 10,000. The truancy
patrols do not appear to be any less aggressive or frequent than
they were during Times Square's more troubled past.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 100 or so teen-agers that the police now pick up every
week in Manhattan, about 60 are now found in the Times Square area,
and most of the rest in the Manhattan Mall on 34th Street, said
Chief Allan H. Hoehl, the police commander of Manhattan South.
</P>
<P>
   But on the busiest days in Times Square _ almost always when a
popular band shows up for an afternoon interview at MTV's
glass-walled studio on Broadway _ the official count does not help
a lot. Ms. Rossi's five officers try not to pluck students from
behind the barricades where they start to gather by the hundreds in
the early afternoon to stake out a prime spot to see their favorite
band.
</P>
<P>
   Officers also try not to pull students off long lines inside the
Virgin music store at Broadway and 45th Street when they throng
there to wait for a recording artist's autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to cause a riot,'' explains Ms. Rossi, who has
two daughters of her own, ages 11 and 15, and knows about these
things. Besides, she said, ``If you wanted to, you'd have to bring
buses to take everybody away.''
</P>
<P>
   And the officers can easily fill up their roving vans just by
concentrating on students who wander off from the crowds alone or
in small groups to the area's new high-tech arcades or to
McDonald's or to the Virgin store.
</P>
<P>
   This was the tactical mistake made by Rebecca Miller, 15, and
three of her friends from West Morris Mendham High School in New
Jersey, who skipped school late last fall to see Korn, a rap-metal
band that attracts almost fanatic crowds when it shows up for MTV's
interview program called ``Total Request Live.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the students had cut school, and they did
so with the blessing of their parents, though not, of course, their
school. (``They can just deal,'' Rebecca said later about her
teachers.) An older sister of one student worked in Times Square,
so they caught a ride with her.
</P>
<P>
   Like many teen-agers interviewed in the area starting last fall,
she and her friends seemed curiously lacking in the seditious
spirit normally associated with truancy. Instead, they had asked
permission, planned in advance and gone with concrete goals: see
the band, buy compact discs, maybe get on television so that their
classmates will believe they were there.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 a.m., the students had already scouted out the best spot
near MTV. They walked around, staring up at all the jumbo
television screens and at the only parental presence anywhere
around: the huge, smiling faces of Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer
on a ``Good Morning America'' billboard.
</P>
<P>
   But while thumbing through a CD rack at the Virgin store, they
were picked up by Ms. Rossi's uniformed police officers and held
(it is called ``noncriminal detention'') for two hours at the High
School of Graphic Arts on West 49th Street near 10th Avenue, a kind
of Central Booking for truants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' Rebecca said. ``We're coming here to see
our band, and, like, they pick us up and take us somewhere.'' But
she grinned as she said this and then showed off the word ``Korn''
written with a permanent marker on her stomach. Katie Largent, 14,
added that she wasn't sure where they had been taken, but it was in
``the middle of, like, nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Under normal procedure, noncriminal truants, are held one or two
hours while their parents and their schools are contacted. Then
they are generally released without charges and are told to go back
to school or home, or are held until parents arrive to pick them
up. They also get a police form that is universally referred to by
truants as a street pass, since it lets officers know that their
truancy has already been reported and they should not be detained
again.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Largent, Katie's mother, who arrived later in the afternoon
to pick up the four teen-agers, explained that she found it almost
comforting that they had been picked up, because it meant that the
police were actively watching out for young people in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Largent, 49, a medical assistant for a pediatrician, said
she remembered playing hooky and going to Times Square herself when
she was in high school to see ``The Endless Summer,'' the surfing
documentary, ``of all things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this place was like it was back then,'' she said, ``I
wouldn't have let them come anywhere near it.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind her on Broadway, her daughter began to scream and held up
a poster board sign toward the second-floor MTV studio windows,
hoping a producer might see. It said: ``We got arrested to see
Korn. Let us up. We earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few youth-oriented merchants in Times Square say the truant
crowd _ including many students not even in their teens _ has grown
so visible on some days that the merchants have begun to try to
keep them out during school hours.
</P>
<P>
   Guards who watch the doors of the Virgin Megastore, for example,
try to spot young-looking customers and turn them away before they
get inside. Russ Hamilton, the entertainment director for XS New
York, one of a handful of new video arcades in the area, says he
also tries to keep out truants, especially the chronic ones he sees
again and again.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that if students were determined to cut classes,
there were worse places for them to spend their time than the new
arcades, much safer and cleaner than their counterparts in the
1970s and 1980s, some of which were known for fake IDs or as places
where men met teen-age boys for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton added that ultimately, it was not his arcade's
responsibility to control truancy. He did not add, of course, that
truancy probably lifted the arcade's bottom line. ``We can shake
our finger at them and try to discourage them,'' Hamilton
explained, ``but if they want to cut, there's not much you can do.
Kids are slick.''
</P>
<P>
   But in what could be an early measure of the effectiveness of
police and of the stores, there are already some chronic truants
reporting that Times Square is no longer a cool place to hang out
because they are too likely to get ``bagged'' or picked up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go there anymore,'' said Erica Figueroa, 14, a
freshman from the High School for the Humanities on West 18th
Street, who was picked up by the police last week with a large
group of friends while riding the No. 1 train.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like MTV and all, but there are too many kids there, you
know? It makes me way too nervous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
