<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-MISSTEPS-MED     01-16 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MISSTEPS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPIRATION, EXCITEMENT AND JOB VOLATILITY OF AN INTERNET START-UP
VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gasp. That's the first thing I did when I heard the AOL-Time
Warner news last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The second thing I did was flash back to February 1995, when I
surfed the World Wide Web for the first time. I was working as the
nebulously titled ``director of content development'' for Delphi
Internet, a tiny online company that Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.
had just bought. Within a few months, the News Corp. entered into a
joint venture with MCI _ a union that, like the proposed
acquisition by America Online of Time Warner, was described by the
parties as the perfect strategic fit.
</P>
<P>
   Am I giving the story away if I say the marriage didn't work
out?
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, was long before dot-com fever swept large
pieces of the planet. Netscape had yet to go public, and Bill Gates
hadn't introduced his answer to Netscape's Navigator software _
Microsoft's Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   In buying Delphi, the News Corp. had intended to make it a force
in the burgeoning online world. Who was better suited to such a
task than a media powerhouse like Murdoch, after all? The only
other major media company to have entered the fray at that point
was Time Warner, with its ill-fated Pathfinder, which was meant to
lasso all the company's brands into a set of linked Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   So the News Corp. had an early starter's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   And consider the competition at the time. There was Compuserve,
based out in the provinces _ Columbus, Ohio _ and owned by H&AMP;R
Block, a company whose main media presence was television
commercials at tax time.
</P>
<P>
   There was Prodigy, out of the media limelight in White Plains, a
suburb of New York City, and co-owned by Sears, Roebuck and by a
company we all knew was a computer dinosaur, IBM.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was a laughingly embarrassing company called
America Online, which acted as if the Internet was fast food and
could be packaged and peddled like a Big Mac and was based in
decidedly unchic Dulles, Va.
</P>
<P>
   None of those companies had our Sixth Avenue cachet. None could
match our easy access to world-class news and entertainment
resources _ our ``content.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first time most of us had ever referred to an
editorial or artistic project with that base word: content. But
having content seemed to us the linchpin of a successful online
service. America Online had to pay providers for content
(including, at the time, The New York Times). Not our Rupert. He
owned the content outright.
</P>
<P>
   But getting Murdoch's vast resources _ TV Guide magazine, Fox
Television, the 20th Century-Fox studio, to name a few _ to move
online for the benefit of our service proved no simple matter. The
executives from the various News Corp. divisions who would even
talk to us wondered why they should give us their goods when
America Online was willing to pay for them. (These days, AOL gets
paid by partners to feature their content, but the scales balanced
differently back then.) Technical and legal issues also impeded our
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, talk we all did, evangelizing the Net to anyone inside
and outside the Murdoch dynasty who would listen, who would
negotiate a deal. ``The Web isn't about computers,'' we would say.
``It's about connecting people, a new form of news and
entertainment.'' Did our voices betray our wishful thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Soon, my title became ``Web talent scout.'' Certainly, talented
people from all corners of the media world were recruited for the
venture, paid handsome amounts for taking the risks associated with
jumping into the unknown. They included a former executive producer
of ``The MacNeil/Lehrer News Hour,'' a former editor for a major
book publisher and a former promotions director of Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Few demanded stock options, if they even thought of them,
because no one expected an initial public offering. A smattering of
23-year-old computer programmers was thrown in for good measure,
but the programmers were yet to be the industry's dominant force.
</P>
<P>
   The staff quickly grew to more than 500 people _ so many that
human resources' orientation each Monday morning resembled a
parade. There were no degrees in Web design or e-commerce, a term
yet to be coined. Many people had barely used e-mail. What they
brought to the venture was an eagerness to build a new medium from
the bottom up.
</P>
<P>
   The eager, savvy administrator at our tiny branch office on the
Fox lot in Los Angeles, for instance, wrote up deals on napkins
with a producer or two to build some of the earliest Web sites for
movies, ``Die Hard 3'' and ``Power Rangers'' among them. With some
enlightened television personnel, we even concocted an online
auction of ``X-Files'' memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   As our permanent offices in the heart of the new district,
Silicon Alley, were constructed, money was spent in a less visible
but important way. A naming company was retained _ it was said for
$1 million _ to come up with a new identity and name for our grand
new service.
</P>
<P>
   Then, seemingly minutes after a new name, Genuine, was chosen in
spring 1995 came the blockbuster announcement: MCI, the mighty
information-network giant, had agreed to invest $1 billion in the
News Corp. Combining the News Corp.'s media content with MCI's
dial-up telephone network and Internet backbone created a sure-fire
formula for interactive-media success. Or so we hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, though, there were problems. The new name
was tossed out, and deciding on an interim name became the first
struggle: should News Corp. precede MCI, or vice versa, before the
words ``joint venture''? A number of key executives were fired,
too, to make way for a new team.
</P>
<P>
   Each partner contributed a co-leader. The News Corp. sent its TV
Guide editor, Anthea Disney, to become editor of the online
venture. MCI sent a former Prodigy executive, Scott Kurnit, to be
the venture's chief executive. The team struggled to decide what
the service should include, how it would work and when it would go
into operation.
</P>
<P>
   MCI apparently lost faith in the relationship, and soon struck
an Internet backbone deal with Microsoft. Layoffs at our joint
venture followed. I got my walking papers in October 1995. By
February 1996, 300 employees had been cut. The online service that
never was fizzled before its debut _ though it briefly morphed into
a TV Guide-style Web site called I-Guide before shutting down
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   So when I heard the AOL-Time Warner news last week, I recalled
those Delphi days and remarked to myself how different the industry
landscape looked now, such a short time _ though eons in Internet
time _ later.
</P>
<P>
   And then, hearing AOL and Time Warner's grand plans, I wondered
whether things really had changed as much as those two companies
seemed to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Napoli is the Internet correspondent for the cable news
channel MSNBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
