<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TWO BIG MEN, UCLA ABANDONS PRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ UCLA coach Steve Lavin often talks about
learning from defeat, and he learned one of the harshest lessons of
his 3{-year career last week in the 12-point loss to USC: The
Bruins are a mess when they press.
</P>
<P>
   After USC shredded their full- and half-court pressure defenses
for 91 points and a slew of easy baskets, Lavin ordered a retreat
against North Carolina _ a compact 3-2 zone that protected the
paint and forced the Tar Heels to score from the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned about this team is that we're not effective
when we extend our defense, because we open the flood gates and
start reaching and grabbing,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   If Baron Davis (NBA) and JaRon Rush (suspended) were available,
it might be different. Their energy and athleticism _ and the depth
they'd provide _ are essential for a smothering press.
</P>
<P>
   But Lavin wants big men Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric on the
floor together whenever possible. A press pushes one (and sometimes
both) away from the basket, while a zone uses their size and
wingspan and keeps them in the lane. It also protects against foul
trouble by limiting body-on-body situations. Moiso had two
Saturday, Gadzuric had one and UCLA committed just 17 _ its lowest
total in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, tempo and pressure are intertwined. A zone slows the
game and reduces fast-break opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press is always a dilemma, because we want to extend to
create tempo and stay out of those 52-50 grinders,'' Lavin said.
``Our offense is affected by our defense. But with two 7-footers,
they're better off in the paint. We'd rather get beat from the
3-point line than the interior. In all our big wins since I've been
here, that's been the formula.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Break out: Saturday marked the first time in 1{ seasons
together that Moiso and Gadzuric recorded double-doubles in the
same game. Gadzuric had 10 points and 10 rebounds. Moiso had 19
points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric's performance was in line with recent play: He had 13
rebounds at Washington and 16 points at Washington State. But for
the struggling Moiso, Saturday was a breakthrough. It couldn't have
come at a better time with 22 NBA scouts and general managers in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will be a turning point,'' said Moiso, who is
expected to leave for the NBA this spring. ``Obviously, I've been
struggling a bit lately. I've been trying to be aggressive and I
haven't been able to find my game.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's leading scorer until Christmas, Moiso was ineffective
against Purdue, the Washington schools and USC, with 35 points in
the four games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Big shots: Junior guard Ryan Bailey wasn't the last player
UCLA wanted at the foul line with the game at stake, but he was
close.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a 62.5 percent foul shooter, had attempted just eight
free throws this season when he stepped to the line with a 69-68
lead and 14.9 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying, `Just let him make these free throws,' '' said
forward Rico Hines, a Greenville, N.C., native with 20 friends and
family members in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Bailey banked in the first and clanked in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to laugh at the bank,'' Bailey said. ``I winked at the
bench to let them know everything was OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-     01-16 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON RESIGNS FROM DOLPHINS AND WANNSTEDT SUCCEEDS HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLES NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Just a day after the Miami Dolphins endured a
humiliating 62-7 defeat in the National Football League playoffs,
Jimmy Johnson stepped down as the Miami head coach Sunday after
four seasons. His longtime assistant and friend, Dave Wannstedt,
was named his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a 56-year-old Texan who is best known for winning two
Super Bowls with the Dallas Cowboys, had indicated to team
officials in recent weeks that he had lost his passion for the game
and probably would call it a career once the season was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time it's final and forever,'' said Johnson, who had quit
for a day after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had a 171-102-2 overall record in nine NFL seasons. He
was 38-31 in his four seasons with Miami. Wannstedt, 47, was the
Dolphins assistant head coach this season after posting a 41-57
record in six seasons as the Chicago Bears head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson coached and oversaw the Dolphins football operations.
Like him, Wannstedt will also be the team's general manager, with
power over the draft and trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dave is a great football coach, and I think people are
going to find out how great a coach he is,'' Johnson said. ``When
you get right down to it, I think he is a better football coach
than what I am. He's got the passion for the game. He loves dealing
with the players. I really believe he's going to give them the
spark to make this organization better.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones, the Dolphins president, said Johnson first
indicated a desire to retire two weeks ago, when he told Jones and
team owner Wayne Huizenga, ``I don't think I can do this any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Huizenga told Jones to assemble a list of
candidates to succeed Johnson. The list reached about 20 names,
Jones said, but Wannstedt was the only candidate to be interviewed,
and that did not take place until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga, mindful that he was able to talk Johnson out of
retirement last year, met with his coach early Sunday, but it was a
brief conversation. ``It's final, Wayne,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m., Johnson had an emotional meeting with his players,
telling them how close they were to being a genuine Super Bowl
contender and emphasizing the importance of securing a first-round
playoff bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have heard a pin drop,'' cornerback Jerry Wilson
said. ``He was really talking from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Huizenga and Wannstedt met, with Jones, the team president,
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave was so impressive with Wayne,'' Jones said. ``He didn't
say, `Well, maybe we might be able to do this or that.' He said,
`We can do this, this and this,' right now the line. Wayne's a very
decisive guy himself. At some point he stuck out his hand and said,
`We've got a deal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both Huizenga and Jones cited the continuity that Wannstedt's
hiring provides. ``We're not stepping back and retooling,'' Jones
said. ``We're moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will no longer be a Dolphin employee, but he said he is
available to help in a variety of roles, including talent
evaluation. ``We'll be calling him,'' Wannstedt said with a laugh.
``We're not going to let him lay around down there in the Keys and
gain 20 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   At several points during his midday news conference, Johnson's
voice quivered, particularly when he described his coaching career
as ``35 great years.'' But he left with his wife, Rhonda, without
giving reporters a chance to ask about his strained relationship
with quarterback Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried in vain to remold Marino into part of a less
turnover-prone offense, particularly this season. But he discovered
the perils of coaching a legend. Even after Marino suffered 17
interceptions this season and contributed to the Dolphins'
remarkable drubbing by the Jaguars, many fans continued to side
with Marino. Johnson faced an expletive-dotted barrage of insults
as he boarded the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the handcuffs off Marino, you overrated bum,'' one man
yelled.
</P>
<P>
   As the team dispersed at the Fort Lauderdale Airport, Stuart
Weinstein, the team's security investigator, helped Johnson carry
luggage to his car. ``I've lost my passion to coach,'' Johnson
suddenly said. ``Tomorrow is my last day.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami clearly plans significant changes on offense. Three
offensive assistant coaches were released Sunday: Kippy Brown, the
offensive coordinator, Rich McGeorge, the line coach, and Larry
Seiple, the quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt said he would probably meet with Marino soon to
determine if he wants to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure where his thoughts are,'' Wannstedt said. ``Dan
and I will talk about the whole scope of the offense, the team,
where we're going. And Dan will make that decision. We're not going
to pressure him into doing anything. He's meant too much to
Dolphins fans over the years all over the country to not respect
him with his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino is scheduled to count almost $6 million against Miami's
salary cap next season. If he were to retire or be released, the
team's cap maneuverability would zoom to nearly $12 million, a
tantalizing prospect for the next free-agent auction.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga said he would support Wannstedt in whatever he decides
to do regarding Marino. But then Huizenga hedged, saying Marino is
a special case and that he would like to be consulted on any
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt, after immersing himself in all phases of the Dolphins
for a year, believes he has the organization around him that he
lacked in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't have the support there,'' Jones said. ``He was
trying to do it all. Here, he doesn't have to. And in him, we think
we have a terrific person who knows a lot about coaching and a lot
about people, someone who can keep us moving down the right road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
