<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORREST'S PROBLEM: HE'S TOO NICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You had a terrific amateur career, compiling a record of 225-16
and reaching the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   You're 30-0 with 25 knockouts in your seven-year professional
career.
</P>
<P>
   You're an in-your-prime 28.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to myriad world championships _ maybe a few by
this time _ right?
</P>
<P>
   Not if you're welterweight Vernon Forrest, who has yet to fight
for a major title.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Olympian has the credentials and the ability. He's
known inside the boxing world as a complete fighter _ good boxing
skills, good speed, good power. What he hasn't had is good
opponents. He will not have faced a big-name foe in his career
until he steps into the ring to face former junior welterweight
champion Vince Phillips on Saturday in Las Vegas in his first HBO
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   In good part, it comes down to this: He's !ital!too good _ not
to mention tall, 6 feet _ and relatively unknown, an unmarketable
combination. Too much risk for minimal financial gain.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Forrest is trying to lure Shane Mosley into the
ring for what would be a compelling matchup, but why should Mosley
comply? The Pomona fighter has a bead on Oscar De La Hoya and a
sizable payday. There's no reason to bother with Forrest.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Forrest's promotional firm, Main Events, has
been unable to push him to the top of the rankings _ which would
make him an unavoidable mandatory challenger for a title _ or get
him on HBO until now. Forrest's advisor, Charles Watson, blames the
corrupt sanctioning bodies more than Main Events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there's a sense of urgency,'' Forrest said from his
training camp in Houston. ``I thought by now I'd be a three-time
world champ. I'm definitely behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll catch up, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Forrest's troubles started even before he turned pro. He was the
defending amateur world champion in his weight class and a favorite
to win the gold medal when he went to Barcelona for the 1992
Olympic Games. However, he lost in the first round after suffering
food poisoning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest, so devastated ``I walked around Barcelona like a
zombie,'' lost his springboard to fame.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's his personality. Forrest is the last thing you want
to be in the boxing business: a nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   He's not a big talker. He only reluctantly has begun the
obligatory baiting of other fighters in order to get them into the
ring and sell himself to the public.
</P>
<P>
   And, although he grew up in a tough neighborhood in Augusta,
Ga., he's avoided trouble. His trainer, Ronnie Shields, said with
great emphasis that ``Vernon has never been in any trouble of any
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   And _ say it ain't so _ he works with !ital!kids, at-risk kids
in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, he's too good for his own good. He'd probably be
further along in his boxing career had be become a bank robber
instead of a decent role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Catch-22,'' he said. ``People want you to be a
good guy. Then, when you're a good guy, they say you need more
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching the 50 Greatest Athletes on ESPN and I saw
(tennis player) Pete Sampras. They were saying how great he was but
that he didn't have a personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it shouldn't be about personality. It should be about
competing, doing the best you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one (Muhammad) Ali,'' he went on. ``We need to
leave that alone. That was 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Forrest might be wrong. It seems fighters need
something that sets them apart _ an Olympic gold medal, an electric
personality, a !ital!huge knockout punch, something.
</P>
<P>
   If he's as good as he appears to be, Forrest will simply have to
keep winning and bide his time. He's bound to get his chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big,'' Watson said of the Phillips fight. ``After he
beats Phillips, people will see how good he is and great things
will come.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Mosley-Wise: Mosley will face 32-year-old veteran Willy Wise
in the main event Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vargas watch: Oxnard resident Fernando Vargas could face a
maximum sentence of nine years in state prison if convicted of
assault, a charge to which he pleaded innocent last week.
</P>
<P>
   However, largely because he has no record, experts say he
probably would be sentenced to three or four months in county jail
if convicted. That means his boxing career most likely will not be
jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   The IBF junior middleweight champion is accused of beating Santa
Barbara residents Anthony Arria and Doug Rossi _ the former by
himself, the latter with four companions _ in a suburban Santa
Barbara home in July.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' handlers have said that witnesses cannot place him in
the room at the time of the alleged beatings. However, Hilary
Dozer, senior deputy district attorney of Santa Barbara County,
said initial interviews suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statements made immediately after the event, including a 911
tape at the time Rossi was being beaten and the first interviews of
people who actually saw the event, indicate that five people
entered the room and beat Doug Rossi with golf clubs and sticks _
four guys and Vargas.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozer added that there is no evidence that Arria or Rossi are
responsible for bad bruises on Vargas' back, which the fighter had
photographed immediately after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to take place in May, which means Vargas'
April 15 fight against Ike Quartey will not be jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   __ Jones fight: It was the same old story for Roy Jones Jr.,
only with more glitz.
</P>
<P>
   Jones easily outpointed a pathetically overmatched David Telesco
to retain his light heavyweight titles at Radio City Music Hall in
New York on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' biggest challenge was staying in sync with the Rockettes
in their dance routine before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, this is boxing: A nice venue, a flashy pre-event show and
a lousy fight.
</P>
<P>
   Jones needs to find a worthy opponent.
</P>
<P>
   __ Movies: Boxing fans who like a good fight film, rejoice: Two
are showing at theaters at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane,'' starring Denzel Washington, depicts the life
of fighter Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, who served 19 years in
prison on a murder conviction that was later overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has received tremendous reviews for his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play it to the Bone,'' starring Antonio Banderas and Woody
Harrelson, is based on a fight in 1965 in which L.A.-based Mexicans
Polo Corona and Pulga Serrano received a call to fight in Las Vegas
that night, drove there together and engaged in an unforgettable
brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The entertaining film, directed by Ron Shelton (``Bull Durham,''
``White Men Can't Jump'') is raunchy but funny, and the main fight
scene is among the most realistic ever put on film.
</P>
<P>
   Corona, portrayed loosely by Banderas, attended the premiere of
the film last week. Serrano died 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   __ More Hurricane: Former middleweight champion Joey Giardello
is suing the film's makers because they made it seem as if his
unanimous-decision victory over Carter in 1964 was the result of
racial prejudice rather than what actually took place in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the movie belittled me,'' Giardello told the
Philadelphia Daily News. ``I fought so many fights (133) for so
many years (19), with all my heart, and this movie makes a mockery
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many critics have suggested the film strays from reality at
times.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hall of Fame: The International Boxing Hall of Fame is
inducting 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   They are: Ken Buchanan, lightweight; Jimmy Carter, lightweight;
Jeff Chandler, bantamweight; Carl ``Bobo'' Olson, middleweight;
Jimmy Barry, bantamweight; Battling Levinsky, light heavyweight;
Billy Petrolle, lightweight; Ad Wolgast, lightweight; Arthur
Chambers, lightweight; Jeff Dickson, promoter; Tito Lectoure,
promoter; Dan Morgan, manager.
</P>
<P>
   The best fighter of the bunch? Maybe Petrolle, who never won a
title. He beat greats Tony Canzoneri, Jimmy McLarnin and Jack
``Kid'' Berg.
</P>
<P>
   Barry, who fought before the turn of the century, never lost. He
was 59-0-9. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
