<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. STRAINING TO APPOINT TOP INSPECTOR OF IRAQI ARMS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the deadline approached for appointing a new chief arms
inspector for Iraq, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan was still
unable Sunday to find a consensus on the Security Council for any
of his potential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the American representative at the United
Nations and this month's council president, was left waiting until
the final hours for word from Annan before notifying other council
members. Diplomats said that the council was not likely to meet
until an agreement had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Several diplomats expressed concern last week that a deadlock
extending beyond Sunday would create procedural and possibly legal
problems, while sending Iraq the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   Annan had until midnight Sunday to appoint an executive chairman
for the newly created U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection
Commission. He had hoped to name his choice by Friday, but the
decision had to be made in consultation with a divided Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The new commission would be a successor to the U.N. Special
Commission, which was forced to end its inspections after Iraq
refused to cooperate. The new entity was created by the council on
Dec. 17 after months of wrangling over how to establish a system
for judging when Iraq had met enough disarmament requirements to
warrant the lifting of the U.N. sanctions imposed in August 1990
after Saddam Hussein's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, China, France and Malaysia abstained during the Dec. 17
vote, signaling their displeasure with the new plan. Since then,
Russia and China, both with veto powers, have resisted the
nomination of a chief inspector who might be hard on Iraq _ in
effect, allowing the Iraqis to influence and stall the process.
</P>
<P>
   In the cease-fire resolution that ended the 1991 war in the
Persian Gulf, the sanctions were linked to the destruction of all
prohibited nuclear, biological, chemical and missile programs, and
Iraq is still at least technically required to comply with that
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that as the deadline approached Sunday, at least
two possible nominees had withdrawn from the running for the
position of chief inspector. They are Celso Amorim, a Brazilian
diplomat and former foreign minister who now works for the United
Nations in Geneva, and Abdul Minty, a South African nuclear expert
and Foreign Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   While diplomats differed Sunday about who was still actively in
the running, Pasi Patokallio, a Finnish disarmament expert, and
Rolf Ekeus, the first executive chairman of the earlier commission,
were still thought to be in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has consistently said that it does not matter whom the
secretary-general chooses, because Iraq has no intention of
cooperating. The threat was repeated by Iraq's state-controlled
press Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
