<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-MEETING-NYT &LR;      01-16 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PLANS YEAR OF RAISING MONEY AND REACHING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Republican Party leaders did not talk much in
public about fund-raising at their winter meeting here this week,
but when they did discuss the party's finances, they seemed
supremely confident.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Sembler, the party's finance chairman, revealed that the
party has a budget of $177 million this year and has $10 million in
the bank. Sembler said he was sure that amount could be raised with
the help of the party's eventual nominee and a major fund-raising
program called Victory 2000, a committee that will accept soft
money, the unlimited campaign contributions from corporations and
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Jim Nicholson, the party's chairman, said the
$177-million goal was a record for the Republican National
Committee, and he added that raising that much money this year was
``not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, several fund-raisers said they were sure the party
would far surpass that goal, especially if the nominee is Gov.
George W. Bush, who has refused to accept federal matching funds,
which come with spending limits, because his campaign has shattered
all previous presidential fund-raising records.
</P>
<P>
   Long discussions about money and budgets occurred in sessions
behind closed doors, several Republican leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee passed a resolution last
Friday that criticized the McCain-Feingold bill that calls for a
ban on soft money. The resolution deplored the Campaign Finance
Reform Act, saying it was ``a scheme that amounts to unilateral
disarmament by Republicans and their allies while leaving the
Democrats, unions and liberal special interests untouched.'' The
resolution said that the bill, which died last fall, ``might more
accurately be termed the Democrat Incumbent Protection Act of
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican leaders, who concluded their four-day meeting
here Sunday, devoted most of their time showing how the money would
be spent: on several new strategies, such as efforts to woo
Hispanic voters and promote the use of the Internet to spread the
party's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have recognized over the last 120 days that it's a new
world, where you are digital or die,'' said Nicholson, who has
worked hard in the past few months on the party's Internet
initiatives. Several times this week, Nicholson said Republicans
must use the Internet to send the party's message directly to
supporters and would-be supporters without going ``through the
filter of the news media.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the Republican Party became an Internet service
provider, offering the public access to the Internet through the
party's hookup. Besides the usual fare _ e-mail and chat rooms _
its service includes Web pages that provide frequent updates on the
latest Republican developments. The service also offers what party
officials call an ``antismut filter'' and ``unbiased reporting.''
An advertisement pitches the service to ``people who want freedom
FROM the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on their Web site, www.rnc.org, Republicans unveiled
GOPlanit, a calendar that allows users to follow the activities of
Republican candidates and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Silicon Valley terms,'' Nicholson said, ``GOPlanit is a
killer application for the GOP at every level.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, America Online probably has nothing to fear. Nicholson
said in an interview that he hoped to enlist ``100,000 e-mail
activists'' by the start of the party's national convention in
Philadelphia in August. Nicholson said an e-mail activist is a
Republican who will forward the party's messages to at least 10
friends. ``With the press of one button, we would be able to reach
one million people,'' he said. ``It's phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have built a new infrastructure to communicate
with voters, the Republicans heard warnings from some Internet
executives that the party must send messages that are positive,
rather than negative.
</P>
<P>
   At a panel discussion attended by about 100 Republicans, Jim
Barksdale, the former chief executive of Netscape, told Republican
leaders that to sway libertarian voters like themselves, the party
must ``lighten up'' on negative issues, such as opposition to
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party is also using the Internet to spread its
message. The Democratic National Committee recently created a
``Bush Stump Speech Search Engine'' on its Web site,
www.democrats.org. By entering any statement uttered by Bush, users
are told how many times the Texas governor has used the statement
during earlier appearances. The intention is to portray him as
scripted and repetitious.
</P>
<P>
   In a new push to court Hispanic voters, Republicans introduced a
60-second television commercial this week that touched many
Republicans who watched its portrayal of a Hispanic family reunion
on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   But the bid stumbled out of the starting gate. Some party
officials winced at a report in The San Francisco Chronicle this
week. According to the report, a lecturer in a closed-door session
told Republicans that many Hispanics do not believe that the party
is in touch with their culture. So the lecturer urged them to find
ways that show their sensitivity to Hispanics, like a mention of
Ricky Martin and his hit song ``Livin' la Vida Loca,'' the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their reluctance to publicly embrace any candidate, most
Republican leaders interviewed here this week said they were
supporting Bush. They said he has the best chance to win. And they
said if he is the nominee, the party will have a much better chance
to maintain its slight edge over the Democrats in the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Until the voters in Iowa, New Hampshire and other states select
a nominee, of course, the Republican National Committee must remain
neutral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
