<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush speaks out on gays and lesbians
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``I've got a record of tolerance as the governor
of the state of Texas. People know that I judge each person by
their heart and soul, but I don't ask people that work for me what
their sexual orientation is.'' _ On whether he would appoint a gay
to a cabinet position. (Interview on CNN's ``Larry King Live,''
Dec. 16, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me whether or not I'd meet them and I said,
probably not, because I didn't want to create a ruckus.'' _ On his
decision not to meet with Log Cabin Republicans. (Dec. 16, Larry
King interview)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a don't ask, don't tell man.'' _ On whether gays should be
allowed to serve in the military. (Republican presidential debate
in New Hampshire, Jan. 6, 2000)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most children should be raised with heterosexual
couples.'' _ On a Texas bill that would have barred homosexuals
from adopting children in state custody. (Bush to reporters, Jan.
26, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all sinners. Far be it from me to cast a stone. But I
don't believe people ought to be married who are gay.'' _
Responding to persistent questioning from a man in the audience at
a Chamber of Commerce dinner in Littleton, N.H. (Nov. 5, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
