<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN HATE SEES AN OPENING 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Iowa, Ohio, Calif., Ore., Ala.)  (jw) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can get a chill just turning the pages of ``Youth at the
Edge,'' a report from the Southern Poverty Law Center on the
inroads that organized hate groups are making among angry white
youths in communities that are struggling despite the economic boom
of the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the development of a two-tiered economy, we're seeing the
rise of a new underclass of white youth that is particularly
susceptible to the lure of hate groups,'' said Mark Potok, a
spokesman for the law center, which monitors hate groups around the
country and is headquartered in Montgomery, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Racist gangs, hard-core neo-Nazi groups and major white
supremacist outfits like the Hammerskin Nation are having a field
day recruiting youngsters, often from suburbia, whose families are
beleaguered financially and losing faith in their dream of a stable
middle-class existence.
</P>
<P>
   These kids hear the seductive tones of organized haters telling
them they're special, they're white, and yet they're getting the
short end of everything. It's the fault of the blacks, they're
told, and the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids resist. The winds of racism in the United States blow
with a lot less force than they did four or five decades ago. But a
frightening number respond. And some are very young. In a
commentary that accompanied the center's report, Potok wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cedar Rapids, Iowa, a 12-year-old boy distributes
propaganda for neo-Nazi leader Matt Hale, a man whose one-time
deputy murdered two people and wounded seven others last July. In
Cleveland, a group of white 14- and 15-year-olds allegedly plans an
October massacre of black students on homecoming day. And in
Pasadena, Calif., four 13- and 14-year-olds, one of them fond of
swastikas and similar symbols, are accused of drawing up plans in
September to murder Armenians _ an ethnic group that the children's
leader had apparently decided was not truly white after reviewing
stacks of hate literature.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the cases mentioned in the report was that of Milton
Walker, a homeless black man who was murdered a little over four
years ago by a group of young whites in Lancaster, Calif., a suburb
of Los Angeles. The report described the crime as ``a particularly
grotesque killing that allegedly was followed by a 16-year-old
girl's boast of having `played' with the man's eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the men accused of attacking Walker, a 23-year-old named
Randall Rojas, said he had come from a troubled family and found a
home with an offshoot of the Nazi Low Riders, an increasingly
influential gang devoted to drug dealing and white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   The law center is not suggesting that tough times automatically
lead to ethnic hatred. ``You don't become a klansman just because
you lost your job,'' said Potok.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little doubt that large numbers of alienated young
people, struggling against economic and other forces that often are
difficult to see and even harder to fight, are primed for the
offering of scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   In communities that appear to be benefiting little from the
miracles of technology and globalization, it's not as difficult as
one might imagine to advance the idea that golden opportunities for
whites have been destroyed by blacks riding the wave of affirmative
action and Jews who are secretly running things through their
control of the federal apparatus, otherwise known as the Zionist
Occupational Government.
</P>
<P>
   This sickness is more widespread than we wish to believe and
frequently results in insane violence. If you want a quick way to
grasp the potential for mayhem, think Skinheads.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Blazak, a sociologist at Portland State University in
Oregon who has spent years studying white supremacist Skinheads,
was interviewed as part of the law center's study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most hard-core kids had experienced some first- or
second-hand downward mobility,'' he said. ``But the propaganda
around the changing face of the American Dream was just as
powerful. The perception was that all white people are moving down,
and all minority people are moving up: `The working-class white man
is losing out on America, the country that he built.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7600 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SCFLAG-MLK17-COX     01-16 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG-MLK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boycott of Georgia tourism possible as S.C. flag fight spreads
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The fight over the Confederate flag engulfing
South Carolina is spilling into Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   As an estimated 20,000 flag opponents gather in Columbia today
for a Martin Luther King Jr. Day rally, the Rev. Jesse Jackson is
urging a tourism boycott of Georgia until the state legislature
removes the Confederate emblem from the state flag. The NAACP
started a similar boycott against South Carolina on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will use whatever technique is necessary to focus attention
on the flag in Georgia,'' said Joe Beasley, the Southern regional
director for Jackson's civil rights organization, the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said civil rights groups, hoping to capitalize on
national publicity for the Super Bowl, plan to call for the Georgia
boycott Jan. 30 during the 34th annual Super Bowl in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Georgia Dome hosted the Super Bowl, in 1994,
civil rights groups staged a protest against the Confederate
emblem, incorporated in Georgia's flag in 1956 by legislators
honoring the state's Civil War dead. But the upcoming Super Bowl
demonstration will be the first time flag opponents, who view the
emblem as a racist symbol, will seek economic sanctions against
Georgia, Beasley said.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said the boycott in South Carolina, the last state to
fly the Confederate flag atop its Statehouse, inspired Georgia
civil rights officials, who have failed in recent years to persuade
the Legislature to change the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would say to people who love justice and equity that
Georgia and Atlanta are living in the past,'' Beasley said. ''They
should not attend any conventions in Atlanta or Georgia until that
flag is removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is Georgia's second-largest industry behind
manufacturing, providing $18 billion in business to hotels and
resorts, restaurants and other businesses, according to the state
Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism. Atlanta claims an
estimated 60 percent of that revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any time you have people in the state who feel there is an
issue degrading to them, embarrassing to them, we are concerned
about it,'' said Bill Howard, spokesman for the Atlanta Convention
and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But Howard questioned whether economic sanctions would gain much
support, especially in Atlanta where black residents are prominent
in business, politics and civic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Atlanta is a city in which blacks have a huge stake. Why
boycott a black mecca?'' Howard said. ''It seems
counter-productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Georgia's Sons of Confederate Veterans predicted a
boycott would fail because the emblem has widespread support,
especially outside of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city of Atlanta does not run the state of Georgia,'' said
Elijah Coleman, a Sons of Confederate Veterans member from
Mableton. ''Legislators from outside of Atlanta are with us on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said he plans to seek support for the boycott from the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference, longtime allies of the
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition. Officials of those organizations in Atlanta
couldn't be reached Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said the boycott will appeal directly to black National
Football League players, urging them to protest the return of the
Super Bowl to Atlanta until the flag is changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope that they would speak out,'' Beasley said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, civil rights groups have grown more vocal in
condemning the Confederate flag as a remnant of slavery intended to
defy civil rights progress over the past half century. Critics say
it is inappropriate as part of any state flag.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of the flag have begun to rally, sparking a march
of 6,000 people in Columbia nine days ago. Today's King Day rally
by flag opponents also will converge on the Statehouse, where South
Carolina Gov. Jim Hodges is prodding legislators to resolve the
flag fight, so far with little success.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators plan further meetings this week on a flag
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the state's Legislative Black Caucus joined the NAACP
in saying relocating the Confederate flag from atop the state
Capitol to the nearby Confederate soldiers' monument would not be
sufficient. But some of the most vocal pro-flag legislators say
they will not consider moving the flag until economic sanctions
against South Carolina end _ a step the NAACP says it is unwilling
to take.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's fight is also spilling over into the
presidential debate. On Saturday, Vice President Al Gore accused
Republican front-runner George W. Bush of ducking the issue
recently when he told South Carolinians the flag's fate was their
decision.
</P>
<P>
   In a TV interview with Jackson, Gore said the flag represents
''for many Americans a hurtful message that recalls the pain of
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did agree with Republican opponent Alan Keyes that S.C.
Sen. Arthur Ravenel's reference to the NAACP as the ''National
Association for Retarded People'' was inappropriate and should be
repudiated.
</P>
<P>
   Ravenel, a Republican from Mount Pleasant, has scheduled a news
conference in Columbia on Tuesday, he said, to ''conclude, as far
as I am concerned, this little controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
