<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-ST.JOHNS-UCONN-NY     01-16 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHNS-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNRANKED ST. JOHN'S UPSETS UCONN, 82-77
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ In a game this good, in an upset this
significant, there are many pivotal plays and at least a half-dozen
key players. Lavor Postell scored 23 points and added seven
rebounds for St. John's, and they were important in an 82-77
victory over Connecticut Sunday. And who would overlook 15 strong
points from the post play of the Red Storm's Anthony Glover?
</P>
<P>
   But no man, moment or matchup meant more than the one with 2
minutes 22 seconds remaining, right after Connecticut rallied to
cut the St. John's lead from 14 points to 2.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley, the ascendant point guard in the Big East,
brought the ball upcourt for the Red Storm (12-2, 4-0), an unranked
team that might be a rising conference power. Covering him was
Khalid El-Amin, the star guard of the defending national champions,
voted the Big East preseason player of the year for a team that
came into the game ranked fifth in the nation. The 10,000 fans who
jammed Gampel Pavilion rose to their feet as one, roaring for a
stop or a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two premier point guards in the Big East,'' Barkley said.
``I'm sure everybody came to see what would happen between us.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened in this instance was unusual. El-Amin, a stocky
junior with a small bandage on his left ear, stayed step for step
with Barkley, a slender sophomore with a larger bandage on his left
cheek. Suddenly, near the top of the key, El-Amin's feet flew out
from under him and he fell to the floor. This didn't change the
plans of Barkley, who said, ``I was thinking about shooting'' from
the beginning of the possession. But Barkley had time to look down
at his feet, plant himself in 3-point range and loft the shot that
clinched the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took what he gave me,'' Barkley said with a chuckle
after finishing with 16 points, 4 assists, 5 rebounds and 5 steals.
``I knew I was going to make my shot because of all the time I had.
That shot really made it comfortable for us to take a deep breath
and just look up and say: `Wow! We're up 5 against UConn.'''
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin said, ``I don't know what happened there,'' but his
recollection of detail was pretty precise. ``I wasn't letting him
go anywhere,'' said El-Amin, who led his team with 22 points, 7
assists and 3 steals. ``He wasn't going to get by me. I slipped.
When I tried to get up, I slipped again, because I was wet and so
that made the floor wet. You can't give anybody five seconds to
shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (12-3, 1-2) got within 3 points twice after that,
but no closer. The teams meet later this season at Madison Square
Garden, and maybe again in the conference tournament or the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had that team beat in the first half, and we stopped
attacking,'' El-Amin said, referring to Connecticut leads of 10-4
and 18-12. ``We could have blew those kids out. We've still got to
play in Madison Square Garden. So, hopefully, we can get them back.
The season is not over by any stretch of the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskies Coach Jim Calhoun said his players did not play as a
unit and should have exploited their height advantage by passing
the ball more to Jake Voskuhl, the 6-11 senior center, who had 13
points in the first half _ only 5 in the second _ and 16 rebounds.
``If they passed him the ball, he could have got 30,'' Calhoun
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Voskuhl received his third foul, he left the game
briefly with a twisted right ankle. When he returned with less than
nine minutes remaining, Glover took advantage, taking the ball
directly to him near the hoop and was successful three consecutive
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that he was hurt,'' Glover said. ``What's a better time
to get your opponent? I tried to attack his leg, which I did. I got
the up-and-under. You back him down, you try to drop-step and go
under with your right hand or your left hand.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis said Glover's early fouls and
limited minutes in the first half were a blessing in disguise
because he was fresh at the end. His team is not too tall, but
Jarvis said the Red Storm used its lack of size as an advantage.
Calhoun noticed it, saying, ``No question in my mind they
out-toughed us.'' Connecticut had only a 38-36 advantage in
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's outscored Connecticut in the paint, 50-32, and in
points off turnovers, 23-6. Calhoun said some of his players looked
as if they didn't want to be in the game. Kevin Freeman, a starting
forward, had 9 points and 3 rebounds, and Albert Mouring scored 15
points on five 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the magnitude of the victory and its effect on St.
John's national stature, Jarvis said he expected to be ranked but
added, ``I probably won't know how big this is until I go home and
listen to my wife tell me.'' Then he quickly added, ``It's huge, it
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, asked about rankings, said: ``Definitely, I think so,''
and added: ``We're just going to go from this game right here to
dictate our season. It feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm has a six-game winning streak. The Huskies, who
had won their previous two, have lost to Iowa outside the
conference and to Notre Dame in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's gunning for them,'' Barkley said. ``Notre Dame
really made it clear that they can be beat at their home gym. Great
teams lose, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But the St. John's fans who made the trip did not seem to think
Connecticut was a great team. ``Overrated!'' they chanted, from the
high seats in the corner, as the UConn fans began to leave early.
``Overrated!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
