<HEADLINE>
SHUMPERT LEADS SYRACUSE (14-0) OVER NOTRE DAME, 80-57 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ The Notre Dame players and coaches had seen the
tapes of Syracuse's athletic inside players floating near the
basket for alley-oop dunks.
</P>
<P>
   So the Irish, with few players who could match the Orangemen
physically, tucked their defense into a zone and dared Syracuse to
beat them from the outside, a strategy that had worked earlier this
season in upsets of Ohio State and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   But when Syracuse struck from the outside Sunday, it came so
fast and furiously that a 1-point lead had deteriorated into a
17-point deficit before coach Matt Doherty could even consider
another strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Shumpert was the prime shooter, making four 3-pointers
in a span of three minutes in the second half as the No. 7-ranked
Orangemen remained the only unbeaten team in the country with an
80-57 victory over Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   After Shumpert, a reserve sophomore forward, hit a 3-pointer 5
minutes 15 seconds into the second half, there was little response
from the crowd of 22,500 at the Carrier Dome. But the fans were
roaring when he hit three more and added a field goal in the next
three and a half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting spree accounted for 14 of Shumpert's career-high 26
points and helped Syracuse improve to 14-0 over all and 4-0 in the
Big East. Shumpert made seven of nine 3-point attempts and matched
the school record for 3-pointers in a game, set by Dave Johnson
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just moments before Shumpert began his outburst, Notre Dame
(11-6, 2-1) had taken its first lead since the opening minute of
the game, 39-38. But Etan Thomas hit a pair of free throws and then
Syracuse drilled five consecutive 3-pointers, four by Shumpert and
one by Tony Bland. When Shumpert made a layup with just over 11
minutes remaining to cap the 19-1 run, Syracuse led by 57-40. The
Orangemen finished with 14 3-pointers _ one short of the school
record _ in 27 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I could say was `unbelievable,''' Syracuse
point guard Jason Hart said of Shumpert's production. ``He busted
the game wide open when we were struggling to find buckets. I think
their coach just didn't want to put anybody on him. He kind of left
him open, if you ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shumpert, who leads the Big East in 3-point accuracy at 56.3
percent, was not certain when the Irish would start chasing him.
But as long as the shots were there, he was going to keep taking
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised, but they were working well in the
zone in the first half,'' he said. ``They had us on our heels a
little. But once I started getting hot, I don't know what their
strategy was, but I saw that as a time for me to let loose and
that's what I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I hit, when the crowd erupted, I wanted to shoot
more and make more. Every time they were jumping out of their
seats, I wanted to shoot more, make 10 or 20. Every shot, I just
shot with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Shumpert became the sixth player to lead the Orangemen in
scoring this season, and the balanced squad may play a part in
confounding observers who are uncertain just how good this team is.
Syracuse began the season ranked 17th in the Associated Press news
media ranking before reaching its current lofty spot.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have pointed to the Orangemen's schedule, which began
with 10 straight home games before sending them out on the road
when the Big East season began. The Orangemen could point right
back to their recent three-game road trip, which took them to Miami
and West Virginia before ending with a 77-74 overtime victory last
Thursday at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they not only overcame foul trouble to Thomas, their
most dangerous inside player, with their outside shooting, but the
Orangemen were also able to blanket Troy Murphy, who entered the
game ranked second in the nation in scoring at 25.1 points a game.
While Murphy finished with 22 points and 10 rebounds, he had to
work for everything. Murphy, a sophomore forward, missed nine of
his first 12 shots and 11 of 17 for the game. It was enough to
convince him of just how good Syracuse is.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're one of the top two teams we've played,'' said Murphy,
who has shot a combined 11 for 41 (26.8 percent) from the field in
three career games against Syracuse. ``We played hard today and
they really got us. Syracuse and Arizona are the two best we've
played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
