<HEADER>
A7607 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHILE-ELECTION-1090(2     01-16 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-ELECTION-1090(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILEAN SOCIALIST NARROWLY ELECTED PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Ricardo Lagos brought Chile's left a sweet
triumph Sunday night, winning a narrow victory to become the
country's first Socialist president since President Salvador
Allende Gossens was overthrown in a bloody coup in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos, a 61-year-old who in the 1980s helped lead the fight
against the dictatorship of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, defeated Joaquin
Lavin, a former aide to Pinochet, after a campaign in which both
left and right appeared to overcome Chile's polarized past. Lagos'
supporters celebrated with a festive caravan of honking cars
through Santiago on this hot summer night.
</P>
<P>
   But the election also marked a comeback for the right, which had
failed to mount credible campaigns in the last two presidential
elections, because of its long association with the fallen
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   With 99.75 percent of the vote in, Lagos led Lavin, 51.32
percent to 48.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new spirit is spreading across our territory,'' Lagos said
to 20,000 supporters who waved the Socialist and Christian
Democratic party flags of the governing coalition in Constitution
Plaza. After recognizing Allende's widow in the audience, he said:
``I want to resolve the pains of our past. There is space here for
everyone. I haven't forgotten the past, but my eyes are open to the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a final vote count was in, Lavin left television
commentators breathless when he went to Lagos' hotel headquarters
and embraced the Socialist candidate on a flag-draped balcony,
while their wives did the same.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture of conciliation between right and left would have
been impossible just a few years ago, but on Sunday night the two
politicians appeared to seize the moment to say that the country
could be unified after three decades of revolution,
counterrevolution and an uneasy transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always be with Ricardo Lagos and with Chile,'' Lavin
said as he conceded defeat. ``I am at his disposal to help unify
Chile.''
</P>
<P>
   A former minister of both education and public works, Lagos
appeared to put together enough votes to win by attracting voters
for minor left-wing candidates in the first round. He also
conducted a more credible and imaginative campaign in recent weeks
to gain support among Christian Democrats and women.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, some analysts suggested, that reports last
Tuesday from London that Pinochet would probably soon be released
because of ill health rather than face extradition and trial in
Spain on human rights charges came in just in time to help Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's apparent imminent return may well have reminded
voters of the human rights violations of the dictatorship just as
Lavin was attempting to eclipse the dictatorship and his role in it
as a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's strong showing was a result in large part of to a
creative, marketing-driven campaign that used the slogan ``Long
live change.'' Candidates are not required here to reveal how much
they spend or who their contributors are, but most analysts say
Lavin may well have outspent Lagos by 3-to-1 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the very closeness of the race between Lagos, and Lavin,
46, marked a break from the past. In the two previous presidential
elections held since Pinochet agreed to step down in 1989, the
governing Christian Democratic-Socialist coalition won in
landslides as the right failed to brush off its identification with
the fallen dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time we have an election in which anything can
happen,'' said Marta Lagos, an independent pollster who is not
related to the presidential candidate. ``We're sick and tired of
the extreme colors. Now we want a gray, modern country.''
</P>
<P>
   How much Chile has changed could be seen at the polling places
at National Stadium, where after the coup against Allende in 1973,
Chilean troops and policemen gathered thousands of Allende
supporters for executions and torture.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday thousands of voters peacefully formed neat lines to
vote, while troops wearing red berets watched from a distance.
Government officials said there were no reports of irregularities
or violence anywhere in the country throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is about choosing a president with new ideas,''
said Juan Morales, a 25-year-old business student who came to vote
in a surfing T-shirt and refused to say whom he voted for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lagos is a renovated Socialist, not an Allende Socialist who
thinks the state should manage everything, while Lavin is a
practical man who knows how to administer resources,'' he said.
``They both have something to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagos repeatedly distanced himself from traditional positions of
his Socialist Party, in large part to shore up his support with
Christian Democrats and with women, who tend to be more traditional
and conservative than men in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   He supported the government's efforts to fight Pinochet's
extradition from Britain to stand trial on human rights charges in
Spain, a position that riled his more left-wing supporters. He also
trumpeted his good relations with Wall Street investors.
</P>
<P>
   After his surprise virtual tie with Lavin in last month's
first-round vote, he emphasized crime prevention as a major issue
in the second-round campaign, promising to hire more police
officers. In one of his final television advertisements, he
appeared before a vandalized taxicab, with his arms crossed and
looking like a tough prosecutor, urging criminals not to vote for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin, meanwhile, broke new ground for the right by meeting with
relatives of those who disappeared during the dictatorship era and
by suggesting he would cut military spending.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Pinochet was arrested on a Spanish warrant in
London in October 1998, Lavin spoke at a rally in support of the
former dictator and even visited him in London as a gesture of
solidarity. But as the campaign progressed, Lavin distanced himself
from Pinochet, and repeatedly promised that he would not step in
the way of a future trial of the general in Chile once he returns.
</P>
<P>
   Though he served for seven years as mayor of the upscale Las
Condes neighborhood of Santiago, Lavin repeatedly posed as an
outsider who would represent a change from a generation of
old-fashioned politicians. He promised to sell the presidential jet
and to appoint people of all parties to top posts in his
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president, I am not going to lose a minute on political
fighting,'' Lavin said at a last-minute campaign appearance on
Saturday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates voiced populist positions in their campaigns.
Lagos promised to create hundreds of thousands of jobs, while Lavin
pledged to bring superior educational opportunities to the children
of the poorest of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Striking one of the more traditional Socialist notes in the
campaign, in the final week Lagos promised to deliver better health
care to all Chileans, declaring, ``Health is a right, not a
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything else, the two candidates tried to appeal
to voters with nuts-and-bolts approaches to issues, like promises
to deliver better government services by using modern computers and
to offer special national telephone call-in lines for citizens with
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny margin between two candidates who expressed few policy
differences on the stump and who studiously avoided the
controversies of the past also appeared to reflect an emerging
political consensus in favor of free-market policies initiated by
General Pinochet and then softened by government social welfare
policies initiated over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Chile has enjoyed one of the most successful economic
performances in Latin America in recent years. Its average annual
economic growth rate of better than 5 percent since the mid 1980s
has surpassed all but a handful of nations.
</P>
<P>
   And while the income gap between rich and poor is wide, as it is
all over Latin America, the sharp decreases in infant mortality and
illiteracy suggest that the lives of the poor have improved in the
last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp recession last year gave impetus for Lavin's call for
change, but in recent weeks government reports indicate that
unemployment is declining. The Chilean peso has been gaining
strength, and the local stock market has been climbing in recent
weeks _ signs that businessmen and international investors feel
comfortable with both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But even as both candidates avoided speaking of the painful past
and declined to criticize each other sharply, both have
professional histories that span the old polarized, conflictive
past to the more peaceful present.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Lagos was a strong supporter of Allende, the
Socialist president ousted by Pinochet. Lagos was slated to be
Allende's ambassador to Moscow at the time of the 1973 military
coup.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos spent much of his exile in the United States, where he
served as a visiting professor at the University of North Carolina.
In the 1980s, he helped lead the opposition to Pinochet and take
the Socialist Party from its traditional Marxist orientation to a
more democratic direction.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin began his career as an acolyte to Pinochet. After studying
economics at the University of Chicago, Lavin served as a minor
functionary in the Planning Ministry. Later he worked as a business
editor at the conservative Santiago newspaper El Mercurio and wrote
several books praising the general's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   After unsuccessfully running for Congress as a hard-right-winger
who went by the nickname ``the fighting cock'' in the late 1980s,
he ran for mayor of Las Condes as a moderate in 1992. As mayor, he
tried to use free-market tools to improve health and housing
services for his more disadvantaged constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The similar campaign positions of the two candidates estranged
many on the left, who in past years would have been expected to
endorse a Socialist over a former aide to Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no alternative,'' said Gladys Marin, who won 3
percent of the vote as the Communist candidate in the first round,
as she announced Sunday that she had nullified her ballot. ``The
two candidates represent the same thing _ neoliberalism, low wages,
and no pensions for women who work in the home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
