<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-KILLING-NYT &LR;      01-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MOTIVE SUSPECTED IN KILLING OF SERBIAN GUERRILLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The Serbian authorities on Sunday
provided few details of the assassination on Saturday of Zeljko
Raznatovic, a notorious Serbian paramilitary leader known as Arkan,
who was wanted on war crimes charges in the Bosnian and Croatian
wars.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of political parties here said Raznatovic, worried
about his security, had made overtures to the Serbian political
opposition in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   They said he had traveled to Montenegro, Serbia's sister
republic, which is led by President Milo Djukanovic. Raznatovic
supported Djukanovic's election in 1997 against the wishes of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. But Djukanovic, who is
supported by the West, made clear to Raznatovic that as an indicted
war criminal he could not remain in Montenegro, these officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was killed in the lobby of the Intercontinental Hotel
here, shot three times in the face by gunmen about 5:15 p.m. as he
emerged with friends from the hotel restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to Belgrade's main emergency hospital, where he was
pronounced dead.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate assumption here was that the Milosevic government
had ordered and carried out the killing, because Raznatovic knew
too much about the activities of Milosevic and his associates
during the Bosnian and Croatian wars that raged from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main question was not whether Arkan would be killed, but
when,'' said Slavoljub Kacarevic, editor-in-chief of the
independent daily Glas Javnosti.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Saturday night, Raznatovic's followers, some of whom are
members of paramilitary groups who live in a sort of plush barracks
in Belgrade, went to his huge, modern house in the rich suburb of
Dedinje, where Milosevic also lives, and fired their guns in the
air in mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say at least 500 families in Belgrade owe their
livelihoods directly to Raznatovic, who had businesses both open
and shady, ranging from bakeries to currency exchanges, oil
smuggling and a casino.
</P>
<P>
   His Serbian National Guard, known as the Tigers, was active in
the Bosnian and Croatian wars and were responsible for murder,
looting and so-called ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic was secretly indicted by the war crimes tribunal in
The Hague in 1997, apparently for events in Bosnia and in Vukovar,
Croatia, where 250 Croats were taken from a hospital and murdered.
The tribunal disclosed that he was under indictment only during
NATO's bombing campaign against Serbia last spring, but the
document detailing the charges has not been unsealed.
</P>
<P>
   A tribunal spokesman, Paul Risley, said in a telephone interview
on Sunday that lawyers asserting that they represented Raznatovic
had contacted the tribunal, exploring the idea of Raznatovic
turning himself in and agreeing to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Risley suggested that Raznatovic's fate might encourage other
wanted men, including the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and
former Gen. Ratko Mladic, to consider turning themselves in to the
relative safety of a Dutch prison cell.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic had close ties to the Serbian and Yugoslav
intelligence services and secret police, carrying a membership card
in the Federal State Security police.
</P>
<P>
   In the shooting, two other men were also killed, a former
business associate named Milovan Mandic, known as Manda, and Dragan
Garic, a high-level police official who worked in the Interior
Ministry, political officials said, confirming a report in Glas
Javosti.
</P>
<P>
   Kacarevic, the editor, said on Sunday that his newspaper
believed that there had been two gunmen with automatic Heckler and
Koch machine pistols, and that one of them had been wounded but
crawled out of the hotel. Both managed to escape. A woman who was
passing by was also hurt, apparently trying to flee the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   There were at least 38 shell casings on the floor of the hotel
lobby, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic, 47, was said to have been accompanied by his wife,
the popular singer Svetlana Raznatovic, known as Ceca, and their
two children, as well as his sister-in-law, Lidija Velickovic.
Raznatovic's wife and sister-in-law are said to own a boutique for
luxury goods in the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Some news reports said Ms. Velickovic had been injured, but
Kacarevic said she had not been, and had in fact organized the
transport of Raznatovic to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The attack had all the characteristics of previous gangland
style killings here of public figures _ a police chief, other
senior police officials, a top journalist and shady business
figures with ties to the Milosevic family or the government.
</P>
<P>
   The former chief of Serbia's uniformed police and the editor of
an independent daily who was once close to Milosevic's wife,
Mirjana Markovic, but then turned away from her are among those who
have been gunned down in public in recent years, with no arrests
ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Another indicted war crime suspect who was said to have led
paramilitary forces in Bosnia, Slobodan Miljkovic, died in a hail
of bullets in 1998 in the Serbian town of Kragujevac.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a memorial service for Raznatovic on Tuesday and a
funeral on Wednesday. In the meantime, his body will be at the
headquarters of his party, the Party of Serbian Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian opposition parties called Raznatovic's killing
emblematic of Serbia's condition under Milosevic's rule. The
Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk Draskovic, who says the secret
police tried to murder him in a car crash last October, said the
killing was ``confirmation that we live in a country of state
terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on the Belgrade television channel it controls,
Studio B, Draskovic's party said, ``Such brutal executions aim to
spread fear and general insecurity among citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Sunday, Studio B said one of its main transmitters had
been sabotaged, cutting off up to 2 million viewers _ half of its
possible audience _ in central Serbia. Studio B's signal is often
jammed in Belgrade and elsewhere, with the government blaming NATO.
The station said the sabotage had occurred after it had managed to
bypass the jamming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
