UCLA's SUFFERING ENDS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The talk around Westwood this week, as far as what
Maylana Martin heard, bordered on desperation.
</P>
<P>
   USC had ended UCLA's win streak in football in November and in
men's basketball Wednesday. Martin heard the pleas: ``You guys are
our last hope. Redeem our school.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned Bruins fans can relax, at least until Feb. 12, when
the teams play in the Sports Arena. By beating USC 82-62 on Sunday,
No. 14 UCLA won its fifth in a row over the Trojans, turning a
close game into a rout with a 19-4 run to start the second half
before a crowd of 7,787 mostly underaged fans. It was the
fourth-largest Pauley Pavilion crowd ever to watch a women's
basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Martin scored eight of her 20 points in the second half's first
7:16, and Janae Hubbard scored seven of her 19 points in that span.
Nothing new there: UCLA (9-4, 3-0) often holds a post advantage
over USC (7-6, 2-1). Martin's career bests in points and rebounds
came last year at USC. Hubbard, meanwhile, looked sharper at game's
end than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week, I tried to hustle more in practice,'' Hubbard said.
``I felt stronger. I put in the effort this week and it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA also received 18 points from freshman Nicole Kaczmarski,
often coming from inside penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, USC was as responsible for the run as anything UCLA did.
And it wasn't just an inability to stop the Bruins' penetration.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans trailed just 40-35 at the half because of some
success on defense. Although USC didn't think it played well in the
first half, its man-to-man defense posed trouble for UCLA's guards,
leading to 14 turnovers. But USC couldn't sustain, beginning the
second half fouling early and often. With 12:14 to play, USC had 10
team fouls and UCLA had made nine of 11 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   When USC finally got into the bonus, it couldn't make enough
free throws, missing several front ends of one-and-ones and
finishing 14 of 24. The Trojans also made just 10 of 34 second-half
shots (29.4 percent) and finished at 36 percent (23 of 64).
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed tons of free throws,'' USC coach Chris Gobrecht
said. ``Had we hit our free throws, we could've stayed in the game,
maybe close enough to make another run. . . . We didn't come out
strong opening the second half. Our inability to handle the dribble
penetration (was one factor). We played timidly defensively. If you
back off, you'll get eaten alive.''
</P>
<P>
   USC received 20 points from Danielle Golay and 14 points from
Denise Woods.
</P>
</TEXT>
