<HEADER>
A7614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-REPUBS-TAXCUT-NY     01-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBS-TAXCUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPUBLICAN TAX-CUT PLANS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Jan. 17:
</P>
<P>
   With the release of Sen. John McCain's tax-cut plan, the
profound differences between his priorities and those of the
front-runner for the Republican nomination, Gov. George W. Bush,
become clear. Nearly any proposal to cut federal income taxes
benefits high-income families since they pay most income taxes.
McCain's and Bush's plans are no exception. But McCain's version
largely bypasses low-income and very rich families, focusing
instead on families earning between $65,000 and $130,000 a year.
Bush showers benefits on very wealthy families but also cuts rates
on low-paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond who gets the tax cuts, there is an important issue of
scale. McCain, playing to moderates in both parties and traditional
conservatives in his own party, proposes modest-sized cuts by
Republican standards. Bush proposes a tax cut that is about three
times larger. Only the Bush plan is fiscally reckless.
</P>
<P>
   McCain boasted that his plan would provide important relief for
low-income families. It would not. To reduce federal taxes on
low-income families requires cutting Social Security and Medicare
payroll taxes, which neither candidate proposes. The central
feature of the McCain plan would extend the 15 percent tax bracket,
which now covers families with incomes up to about $40,000, to
families with incomes up to about $70,000. This provision does
nothing for families already in the 15 percent bracket _ more than
two-thirds of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tilts his tax-cut plan toward high-income families by
cutting their rates and making them eligible for tax breaks that
are now limited to lower-income families. Under the plan, the
wealthiest 1 percent of taxpayers would get almost 40 percent of
the tax cuts. But Bush would also cut the bottom tax rate to 10
percent from 15 percent. Robert McIntyre of Citizens for Tax
Justice, a liberal research center that uses standard economic
models, estimates that about 5 percent of the tax cuts under the
McCain plan would go to the bottom 60 percent of the population.
Under the Bush plan, the number would be about 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are other undesirable features of the Bush and McCain
plans. Both would slash taxes on multimillion-dollar estates.
McCain would permit taxpayers to invest 2.5 percent of their
salaries in private retirement accounts rather than paying the
money into the Social Security trust fund. Private accounts would
prove unattractive to low-paid workers because administrative costs
eat up a large percentage of small contributions. Worse, as
high-income families peel away from the trust fund, the Social
Security program would lose some of its ability to redistribute
income from high-paid to low-paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre estimates that McCain would cut taxes by about $500
billion over 10 years, less than a third of the $1.7 trillion tax
cut proposed by Bush. That means the McCain plan would preserve
more money for education and other federal programs and for paying
off federal debt _ two ways to help the economy grow before the
baby boomers retire and drive up the costs of Medicare and Social
Security. McCain promises to offset much of the cost of his tax cut
by eliminating corporate loopholes. That is a fine idea, except
that Congress habitually tosses such ideas aside once the lobbyists
swarm Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The two tax plans are more a roadmap to campaign strategies than
a blueprint for tax reform. Bush pitches his plan to those who want
to starve government programs. McCain's mission is different,
promising to pump money into the Social Security and Medicare trust
funds. Because the money would not be needed over the next decade
or so to support retirees, it would be used to buy back government
bonds from the public _ a feature that will appeal to traditional
fiscal conservatives in the party who like the idea of paying off
the national debt. Yet there is a thread that runs through the
McCain and Bush plans and every other Republican income-tax plan.
Each piles most of the benefits on the families who least need
help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
