A7615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-PRISONERS-HIV-NY     01-16 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRISONERS-HIV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHEN PRISONERS HAVE HIV 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Jan. 17:
</P>
<P>
   An Alabama prison policy that excludes HIV-positive inmates from
programs open to other prisoners was upheld by an appeals court on
dubious grounds and now needs Supreme Court review.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has urged the high court not to take
the case, because there is no clear legal conflict among federal
appeals courts on this issue. But the ruling by the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, if allowed to stand, leaves Alabama
inmates who have HIV subject to unfair discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is one of a few states that bar all HIV-positive inmates
from participating in programs where they might mix with the
general prison population. The inmates sued on grounds that the
policy violates the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, which prohibits a
federally financed state program from discriminating against
individuals on the basis of their disability.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates did not contest their segregated housing, but
challenged their exclusion from some 70 prison programs available
to other inmates, including work-release programs, college classes
and recreational activities. Some programs, such as chapel
services, were provided on a segregated basis to HIV-positive
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama argued in federal court that HIV infection posed a
``significant risk'' to other inmates that could not be eliminated
by ``reasonable accommodation.'' The federal appeals court affirmed
a trial court's decision that the exclusion policy was justified
because the potential for violence in prisons might result in
blood-to-blood contact, making transmission of the virus possible.
</P>
<P>
   The policy is not based on an assessment of individual inmates'
records for violence or particular situations that might result in
conflict. The appeals court seems simply to accept the trial
court's analysis that participation by HIV-positive inmates in all
programs _ including even data-processing classes _ poses a risk of
infection to others.
</P>
<P>
   Prison administrators are generally allowed great deference in
making security judgments. But this overly broad analysis of risk
punishes inmates solely because of their HIV status, and should be
overturned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2051EST &QL; 
