<HEADER>
A7620 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-VIKINGS-HNS &LR;      01-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-VIKINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ST. LOUIS _ Even though he was the NFL's Most Valuable Player this
season, there were plenty of people who had never seen St. Louis
Rams quarterback Kurt Warner play.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He made the highlight reels nearly every week, but after the
Rams' less-than-impressive seasons throughout the '90s, the
schedule-makers didn't see fit to give St. Louis any national
television games in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally got the national spotlight Sunday, Warner made
good use of it, throwing five touchdown passes to lead the Rams to
a 49-37 divisional playoff victory over the Minnesota Vikings. St.
Louis will host Tampa Bay in the NFC Championship Game on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we painted a glaring picture that we don't have any
obvious weaknesses,'' St. Louis coach Dick Vermeil said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner needed all of 11 seconds to put the Rams on the
scoreboard. On his first play from scrimmage, he threw up a pass to
Isaac Bruce, who made one defender miss and sailed into the end
zone for a 77-yard touchdown that put the Rams up 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Jacksonville Jaguars, the dominance of the Rams
(14-3) has been called into question because of a soft schedule.
But like the Jaguars, who stomped Miami 62-7 one day earlier, St.
Louis didn't leave room for doubters. The final score might have
looked respectable, but the Vikings (11-7) had to score three
touchdowns in the final five minutes to narrow what had become a
49-17 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw one sign as we left that said, `Ha, we still haven't
played anybody,''' Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who threw for 4,353 yards and 41 touchdowns in the
regular season and had a passer rating of 109.2, completed 27 of 33
attempts for 391 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's special,'' Vermeil said. ``That's a pretty good day's
work.''
</P>
<P>
   And the St. Louis defense, which ranked sixth in the NFL, was
successful in shutting down the league's third-ranked offense when
the game was still on the line. The Vikings, who had taken a 17-14
lead into halftime, netted minus-two yards in the third quarter as
the Rams surged to a 35-17 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings quarterback Jeff George finished 29-for-50 for 424
yards. But he threw four interceptions (to one for Warner), and
half of his yardage came after the game was out of hand. George
also was sacked four times for minus-35 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's Randy Moss had a 188-yard, two-touchdown receiving
performance but couldn't cross the goal line until less than four
minutes remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't hold Minnesota to minus-two yards in the third
quarter without playing well,'' Vermeil said.
</P>
<P>
   If it was the Falcons' offense that ended Minnesota's dream
season last year, it will be the Rams' attack giving them
nightmares this offseason. All afternoon, Minnesota defenders were
diving and catching only air as the Rams blew past the league's
30th-ranked pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rams had run just two offensive plays, Bruce had 103
yards receiving. After five plays, Warner had thrown for 155 yards
and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew yesterday that we were going to come out and run that
play (to Bruce as the opener), and I went over about every scenario
in my head,'' Warner said. ``It was nice to get out there and run
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Faulk scored the second touchdown off a screen pass. He
cut right to evade one tackler, then sprinted 41 yards untouched to
put St. Louis on top 14-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' strategy was to run the football and control the
clock, thus keeping the No. 1 offense in the league off the field
as much as possible. It didn't quite work as hoped. The Vikings had
the ball for 12:44 and St. Louis for only 2:16 in the first
quarter, but only because St. Louis' two touchdown drives took a
mere 2:06 to execute.
</P>
<P>
   There were big plays on special teams as well, none more
significant than Tony Horne's 95-yard kickoff return to start the
second half, giving the Rams a 21-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That sparked five unanswered scores for St. Louis, the other
four coming on a one-yard run by Faulk, a 13-yard pass to Jeff
Robinson, a one-yard pass to Ryan Tucker and a two-yard pass to
Roland Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great stamina,'' Vermeil said. ``There was a lot of
fuel in our tank when we came out at halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings had taken a brief lead before the intermission after
a pair of late touchdown drives, one capped by a 22-yard pass from
George to Cris Carter, the other coming on a four-yard spinning run
by fullback Leroy Hoard.
</P>
<P>
   Both came after St. Louis miscues. Minnesota cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock picked off a pass at the Minnesota four to begin Carter's
scoring drive. Safety Robert Griffith picked up a Warner fumble at
the Minnesota 47 to spark the second touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vermeil: ``(At halftime), I told them, `We're only down by
three. They've taken their best shots. Now, we'll deliver ours.'''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rams are certain they have plenty left to deliver next
weekend against the Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have called everything we had in our game plan if
we played three weeks in a row,'' Vermeil said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
