<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NACHAMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTRONGO NACHAMA, 81, CHIEF CANTOR OF BERLIN'S JEWS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Estrongo Nachama, the chief cantor of the Berlin Jewish
community and the man who did as much as anyone to revive Jewish
life in the city after Hitler destroyed it, died on Thursday. He
was 81.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was a heart attack, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous to the last, eyes always glimmering, his voice scarcely
affected by age, Nachama exuded the passion for life of a man who
had seen the worst horrors and come through. He was an Auschwitz
survivor, spared because his voice pleased the SS guards, who
particularly enjoyed his rendering of ``O Sole Mio.''
</P>
<P>
   His family, all sent to Auschwitz after the Nazis took control
of northern Greece, where Nachama was born, was less fortunate. His
parents, a sister and many relatives were all killed by the Nazis
at the camp.
</P>
<P>
   While forever marked by this loss, Nachama was an inveterate
optimist of seemingly boundless energy. On his 80th birthday, he
declared, ``I will sing for as long as God allows me'' _ and he
did, coaching bar mitzvah students until the day before his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the absolutely critical people in terms of the
rebuilding of the Jewish community in Berlin,'' said Tom
Freudenheim, the deputy director of the city's Jewish museum.
``Before the wall fell, he would cross to the East with a special
pass to conduct services there. In his day, his voice was famous
well beyond this city.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, when Nachama became cantor, the Jews of Berlin had
almost all departed or died. Today, with the Jewish population
swollen by an influx of Jews from Russia and other Central and
Eastern European countries, about 12,000 people are registered
members of the Jewish community and several thousand more are known
to live here.
</P>
<P>
   Estrongo Nachama was born in Salonika, Greece, the son of a
prosperous grain merchant. He was to have taken over the family
business, but the Nazis sent his entire family to Auschwitz in
1943.
</P>
<P>
   A splendid tenor, Nachama earned the nickname ``the singer of
Auschwitz.'' His voice saved his life. When the camp was closed in
1945, Nachama was pressed into a ``death march'' back to Germany.
Sick with typhoid, he was ultimately freed by Soviet troops near
Berlin in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   On his recovery, he planned to take a train back to Greece. But
he grew close to a Christian family that had taken him in and
quickly became active in what was left of the Jewish community. In
the end, he never left.
</P>
<P>
   His voice became well known in the city and was broadcast on
Friday nights by the radio service in the American sector of
Berlin. He worked tirelessly for an improved understanding between
Jews and Christians and became one of the first prominent German
Jews to attend church congresses.
</P>
<P>
   When, last September, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel became
the first foreign leader to visit Germany after the government
moved back to Berlin, Nachama was at his side during a service at
the Sachsenhausen concentration camp near the capital. His voice
rising over the bleak scene of horror was one of tremulous beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Nachama is survived by his wife, Lily, a son, Andreas, who is
the leader of the city's Jewish community, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-AFRICA-NYT &LR;      01-16 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: A GOOD TIME FOR CANDOR ABOUT AFRICA'S LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL BERKELEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and its new representative at the
United Nations, Richard Holbrooke, have embarked on a laudable
month-long effort to focus the world's attention on the multiple
overlapping crises in Africa. In using its presidency of the
Security Council to schedule debates on Angola, Congo and Burundi
in particular, the administration brings a long-overdue sense of
urgency to these ruinous conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   But an opportunity for productive American leadership will be
lost if the debates do not include a candid recognition that some
of Washington's allies in the region are compounding the very
problems it now seeks to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   It seems only yesterday that the United States was hailing the
advent of a ``new generation'' of African leaders bent on rooting
out the corrupt and brutal era of strongman politics that had
blighted the continent for a generation. President Clinton produced
the climactic moment during his tour of Africa in April 1998. At a
meeting in Uganda with six of these new-found allies, he embraced
the ``new generation'' as harbingers of an ``African renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   Within months of Clinton's visit, alas, nearly all of these
leaders were at war with one another. Laurent Kabila of Congo, who
had liberated that vast nation from America's longtime Cold War
client Mobutu Sese Seko, turned out to be a predatory thug.
</P>
<P>
   Then the dean of the ``new generation,'' Uganda's Yoweri
Museveni, and his protege, Rwanda's Paul Kagame, who had backed
Kabila's war against Mobutu, grew disillusioned with their progeny
and launched yet another armed insurrection to replace him _
yielding the present intractable conflict that has drawn in a
half-dozen surrounding nations and now counts civilian casualties
in the hundreds of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   In the Horn of Africa, meanwhile, Issaias Afwerki of Ethiopia
and Meles Zenawi of Eritrea, two charismatic former guerrilla
allies, set upon each other in a remote border conflict that has
claimed tens of thousands of lives in trench combat reminiscent of
World War I.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? For all their impressive talk, our African
allies had little in common apart from their success at beating
discredited predecessors at their own game. They all achieved power
through the use of force, and that is how they are inclined to hold
onto it. Ultimately they, no less than those whom they ousted, are
accountable to no one save their own armed constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was understandably eager to do business with a new
generation of articulate leaders who at least embraced
market-oriented economic reforms if not democratic systems of
accountability. Museveni, to his credit, had brought a welcome
measure of stability to his own war-battered country. Kagame drew
sympathy as a leader of Rwanda's decimated Tutsis after the
genocide of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration has been slow to come to terms
with the fact that all these men have shown a recklessness with the
lives of defenseless civilians that is the hallmark of men grown
accustomed to unaccountable power. The names and faces have
changed, but the nature of the game is the same.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best-intentioned among them are now trapped in
Macbethian logic, compelled to shed ever more blood merely to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has belatedly distanced itself from Kabila in
Congo, but it remains closely identified with Museveni and Kagame,
even as they have launched or provoked one blood bath after
another.
</P>
<P>
   It has rarely rebuked them for their recklessness, maintaining
strong diplomatic, military and economic ties that have left the
impression across the continent that they enjoy unwavering American
support. In turn, they have behaved as if they believed they had
carte blanche to pursue their dangerous adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright have
forthrightly acknowledged America's Cold War complicity with
tyrants and warlords across the continent whose crimes paved the
way for today's conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The list is lamentably long: Mobutu in Zaire, Samuel Doe in
Liberia, Gafaar al-Nimeiry in Sudan, Mohammed Siad Barre in Somalia
and the Angolan rebel Jonas Savimbi, who now perpetuates a
pointless war with the benefit of diamond smuggling revenue. But
the administration has been slower to recognize that a
well-intentioned effort to forge special relationships with less
malevolent but no more accountable leaders has failed to arrest
their destructive tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has called on Congo's warring parties to comply with a
peace agreement that has languished since last July. His appeal
will amount to little if Washington does not also clearly signal to
its closest allies that at long last it is ready to use its
considerable diplomatic and economic influence to hold them
accountable for their reckless adventures.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just a policy prescription from afar. It is what
Africans themselves across a broad spectrum are daily risking their
lives and livelihoods for: accountable government and the rule of
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
