<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-GLAXO-SMITHKLINE-ART-     01-16 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAXO-SMITHKLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAXO AND SMITHKLINE AGREE TO FORM LARGEST DRUGMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN WITH MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British drug maker, Glaxo Wellcome, agreed Sunday
night to merge with one of its chief rivals, SmithKline Beecham,
that would create the world's largest pharmaceutical company,
executives close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company, to be called Glaxo SmithKline, would be a
powerhouse in Europe and the United States, with a stock-market
value of $186 billion, annual sales exceeding $25 billion and a
research and development budget of more than $3.6 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The new company would combine Glaxo's roster of top-selling
drugs like Zantac, an ulcer drug, and treatments for AIDS and
asthma with SmithKline's consumer brands like Tums antacids and
Aquafresh toothpaste as well as its lineup of prescription drugs,
which include Paxil, a leading antidepressant, and Augmentin, an
antibiotic.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have large and growing operations in the United
States. The combined company would be the largest seller of
prescription drugs in the United States with more than $9 billion
in prescription sales here, based on last year's results.
</P>
<P>
   A merger might result in the elimination of overlapping jobs
among the combined companies' 106,000 employees worldwide. But
Glaxo SmithKline's ambition to expand its American presence is
expected to mean that few of its nearly 22,000 jobs in the United
States would be at risk. In fact, the merged company, would
probably set up an operational headquarters in the United States,
somewhere near New York City, executives said, although the
specific location has not been chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the merger, which the companies planned to announce here
on Monday morning before the opening of the London Stock Exchange,
comes amid rampant consolidation in the pharmaceutical industry.
Mergers are being driven by the increasing pressure for companies
to slash costs and bolster their drug pipelines as profit margins
continue to thin. Moreover, throughout the industry, patents for
many of the leading prescription drugs have expired or will soon,
intensifying the competition among big research laboratories to
find new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, Glaxo and SmithKline would control 7.3 percent of the
pharmaceutical industry and hope to save $1.63 billion annually by
the third year of the merger, the executives said. The two
companies would surpass the industry's current leader, Aventis,
which is based in Frankfurt and had sales of $10.8 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo and SmithKline's merger was driven, in part, by
Warner-Lambert's announcement last Thursday that it was in talks
with Pfizer over a possible merger that would have made it the
largest drug maker in the world. If they do combine, Pfizer and
Warner-Lambert would rank second in the world behind a combined
Glaxo SmithKline and would be the only American pharmaceutical
company in the industry's top five.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this era of merger mania, you don't want to be the last
company without a partner,'' said Sergio Traversa, a pharmaceutical
analyst at Mehta Partners, a New York investment firm. Traversa
said Glaxo and SmithKline were a good fit because both were
themselves formed by past mergers and because many of their
London-based executives already know one another. Of all the drug
companies, Traversa said, ``this is one of the combinations that
makes the most sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives said the Glaxo and SmithKline boards voted Sunday
night to approve what they planned to call ``a merger of equals.''
Although Glaxo shareholders would control 58.75 percent of the
company, each side would send the same number of directors to the
board.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time that Glaxo and SmithKline have tried to
merge. Nearly two years ago, the drug makers began merger
discussions, but those talks collapsed because of a bitter clash of
egos by the companies' top executives over who would control the
combined company. The deal can be consummated now, in part, because
one of the executives involved the earlier stalemate, Jan Leschly,
SmithKline's chief executive of SmithKline, is planning to retire
in April.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said Sir Richard Sykes, chairman
of Glaxo would become chairman of the combined company, and
Jean-Pierre Garnier, chief operating officer of SmithKline, would
become chief executive and run the company day to day _ probably
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Richard, 57, is expected to retire in 2002, when Garnier,
52, would be expected succeed him, the executives said. John
Coombe, Glaxo's finance director, is to become finance director of
the new company and Tadataka Yamada of SmithKline would be be
director of research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company is expected to keep its corporate
headquarters in London, but create a new operational headquarters
in the United States. An employee close to the negotiations said
that the exact location was still being worked out, but that the
American headquarters would be somewhere near New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo has its American headquarters in Research Triangle Park in
North Carolina, and SmithKline's American base is in Philadelphia.
Glaxo has 9,750 employees in America, most of them in North
Carolina. SmithKline has about 12,000 employees in the Untied
States, with 9,000 in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, SmithKline has managed much of its global
operations from Philadelphia, where both Jan Leschly, SmithKline's
chief executive officer, and Jean-Pierre Garnier, its operating
officer, live in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Because both companies have been trying to increase their
American presence, most of the job reductions are expected to be
outside the United States. The companies expect to continue most of
their operations in North Carolina, Philadelphia and Pittsburgh,
where SmithKline has its American consumer products business, which
makes Tums, Contac cold medicine and Aquafresh toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical analysts said Sunday that if United States jobs
were cut, they would most likely in overlapping administrative or
manufacturing operations, rather than positions in the companies'
research laboratories or sales forces.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, officials at Glaxo and SmithKline acknowledged they
were in talks, though neither company would disclose any specifics
except to say any deal would be a merger of equals. Spokesmen for
Glaxo and SmithKline declined to comment on the impending merger
Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of both companies rose last Friday in hopes the merger
would be consummated. SmithKline rose $3.9375, to $70, and Glaxo's
gained $2, to $60.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo is being advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., and SmithKline
is being advised by Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the merger had been expected since early 1998,
when the earlier talks between the companies collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hardly unexpected,'' said Dr. Joseph Zammit-Lucia,
president and chief executive of Cambridge Pharma Consultancy in
Cambridge, England. ``It's going to create a company of
considerable size. In terms of culture and direction of research
discovery, the two companies complement each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Zammit-Lucia warned that while the companies should be able
to create the cost savings promised, ``It's not such a trivial task
to manage such a big company with such a product spread.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
