<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-VIKINGS-RAMS-NYT &LR;      01-16 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-RAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST, FIERCE AND LOVELY, THE RAMS FLY HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Minnesota Vikings and the St. Louis Rams offered
Sunday the equivalent of two cyclists pedaling furiously downhill,
two rafts bouncing wildly downstream, two teams that glared into
each other's eyes, took 10 paces, whirled _ and threw a maddening
stream of footballs at each other.
</P>
<P>
   All day long.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was better equipped to throw them, catch them and run
with them. Though the Rams fell behind, 17-14, at halftime, they
rode a stunning 35-0 scoring spree in the second half that put them
ahead, 49-17, with 8 minutes 13 seconds left to play. It was a
blizzard of points, a barrage of big plays, and it left the Vikings
wobbly. The attack was so powerful and so decisive that though the
Vikings scored 20 points in the game's final eight minutes, who
cared?
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis won, 49-37, before 66,194 fans in the Trans World Dome
who enjoyed nearly all 34 Kurt Warner pass attempts, especially the
27 he Warner completed, and also saw 50 pass attempts by the
Vikings' Jeff George. The fans saw Warner throw for 391 yards to 10
different receivers and George hit five different receivers for 424
yards. Warner threw five touchdown passes, George four.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Warner who put together the game-deciding string _
scoring passes of 13, 1 and 2 yards late in the third quarter and
early in the fourth _ to push the Rams into the National Football
Conference championship game. The Rams (14-3) will play the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers (12-5) here next Sunday to decide which team will
represent the conference in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you go into the fourth quarter and a team hasn't
gotten more than 50 yards rushing and you've got the kind of points
they had means there were just too many times our guys were on the
ground slipping, falling, or too many plays that they made off
their athletic ability,'' Vikings Coach Dennis Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of speed and they play on a fast surface.
They use that speed well. The quarterback can throw a nice deep
ball and they've got a lot of guys that can chase it down. They've
got exceptional speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rams receiver Isaac Bruce caught four balls for 133 yards and a
touchdown. Torry Holt grabbed six more for 65 yards. Running back
Marshall Faulk caught five passes for 80 yards, including a 41-yard
score off a screen pass. Receiver Az-Zahir Hakim caught five for 49
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Open receivers, crisp Warner passes, big plays, points aplenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think their defense matched up with our offense and
we really believed we could make big plays and score points,'' Rams
Coach Dick Vermeil said. ``We've got so many kids that can score
and make plays. We can get chunks of yardage.''
</P>
<P>
   That was illustrated on the Rams' first offensive play of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota started the game on offense and orchestrated a
sparkling 11-play, 60-yard drive to the Rams' 13. It stalled there,
but took 5:37 off the clock and produced a 3-0 Minnesota lead.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, the Rams said. They took the ensuing kickoff and
returned it to their 23. One play later, on a deep post pattern,
Bruce scored on a 77-yard touchdown pass from Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it took the Vikings 11 plays and 5 minutes to score a field
goal and the Rams 1 play and 21 seconds to score a touchdown. On
the game's initial possessions, the order had been set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a double post, with me and Torry both lined left,''
Bruce said of his 77-yarder. ``Their secondary had to keep track of
both of us running the same route. I caught them a little
flat-footed.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Lyght, the Rams' Pro Bowl cornerback, said: ``A varied,
attacking scheme is the key for our offense, and the Vikings have
pretty predictable defensive sets and not a good mix on defenses.
You cannot give that to our players and our coaches. No offense
does the amount of movements and shifts across the board that we
do. It gave Minnesota some trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Vikings temporarily solved it. The long Bruce score was
followed by the long Faulk score and the Rams were ahead, 14-3,
entering the second quarter. Minnesota began stunting and blitzing
more, pressuring Warner, and forcing St. Louis turnovers. In the
second quarter Minnesota's Cris Carter caught a 22-yard touchdown
pass and Leroy Hoard scored on a 4-yard run. Minnesota left at
halftime with a 3-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a breathtaking play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take the third-quarter kickoff to the house,'' the
Rams' Tony Horne said. ``I had just missed doing that on a couple
of kickoffs in the first half. We had set them up, running right on
the kickoff return all of the time in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   To start the second half, therefore, Horne and the Rams started
the kickoff return running right but veered and returned the ball
to the left. A hop, a skip, a jump and blazing speed was exhibited
by Horne. It wound up a 95-yard kickoff return for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That started the Rams' 35-point getaway.
</P>
<P>
   It began a third quarter that the Rams controlled in first downs
(10 to 0), total yards (150 to minus 2), passing yards (133 to
minus 3) and possession time (12:25 to 2:35).
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge; it set the tempo,'' Warner said of Horne's
return. ``It got us the momentum back. The offense kind of took
over and stayed on a wave from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikings linebacker Dwayne Rudd said: ``We had things going our
way and Tony Horne changed it around. That was a championship play
that helped them to the championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis rout was in gear.
</P>
<P>
   By game's end, the Rams had broken 12 team records and Warner
had broken five team passing records.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is a classic matchup of offensive firepower (St. Louis)
against defensive mettle (Tampa Bay) in the NFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the Rams are playing well,'' Vikings linebacker
Chris Doleman said. ``I'm not saying they'll go all the way. But
I'd say their chances are very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner is confident the Rams will throw more passes, score more
points, continue to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Will this offense be stopped, he was asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Warner said. ``I haven't seen a defense
that has done it yet. People are going to have to prove it to me
for me to believe it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
