<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-RESIGN17     01-16 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-RESIGN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson resigns from coaching Dolphins
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ The official announcement, delayed almost two
hours, finally came at 12:52 p.m. For most of Jimmy Johnson's life,
this time _ 1 p.m. on a Sunday _ meant an opening kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   On this Sunday, though, it meant a closing statement.
</P>
<P>
   One day after standing on the sideline at Jacksonville's Alltel
Stadium, watching the Miami Dolphins suffer the worst loss in
franchise history _ a 62-7 defeat in the second round of the NFL
playoffs _ Johnson stepped onto the stage in the auditorium of the
Dolphins' training facility and announced that he was doing what he
almost did one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Ending his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' he said, ``it's final and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason the news conference was delayed had nothing to do
with Johnson, 56, wavering on a decision. Dolphins owner Wayne
Huizenga was busy working out the details of a three-year, $3.9
million contract for Johnson's successor _ Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt, a longtime friend of Johnson's who was hired a year
ago as an assistant head coach after being fired after six seasons
with the Chicago Bears, becomes the fourth head coach in franchise
history. Wannstedt promptly fired three assistant coaches,
including offensive coordinator Kippy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can stand here right now and tell you that the goals of our
football team are no different than what they were in July _ and
that's reaching the Super Bowl,'' Wannstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was the goal of Johnson when he returned to
South Florida in 1996. The coach who had guided the University of
Miami to a national title in 1987, before heading to Dallas and
winning two Super Bowls in five years, brashly talked of a
three-year plan to get the Dolphins back to the Super Bowl for the
first time since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   But in four years, he produced a 38-31 record and won two
playoff games _ each of which was followed by a record-setting
post-season loss.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, the Dolphins fell 38-3 at Denver. At the time,
that was the worst post-season loss in team history. It was topped
Saturday at Jacksonville when, in what also might have been
quarterback Dan Marino's final game, the Dolphins fell behind 24-0
in the first quarter en route to the NFL's worst loss in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later, shortly after meeting with Huizenga,
Johnson stood in his office and prepared for his news conference.
He seemed relaxed, as if a burden had been lifted. He smiled as he
talked about giving his fish tank to his secretary and his office
to his longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't this one game,'' he said. ``I've been thinking about
this for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   He approached Huizenga and team president Eddie Jones separately
several weeks ago and gave each the same message: His dream job
wasn't a dream anymore. He was tired of coaching. He wasn't having
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could put two and two together real quick after that,''
Huizenga said. ``We agreed that no decision would be made until
after the season. ... If we had won in Jacksonville, maybe Jimmy
would have re-thought where he was going.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson insisted that wasn't the case, that he had his mind made
up that no matter what happened _ first-round loss or Super Bowl
title _ he was ready to quit.
</P>
<P>
   This, he made it clear Sunday, was his final answer.
</P>
<P>
   He already is a millionaire. Now he needs other things. Like a
life beyond football.
</P>
<P>
   There already are at least two offers from networks to be an NFL
analyst. Johnson, however, said he likely would pass on them,
instead sticking to some consulting work for the Dolphins and lots
of time on his boat, named ``Three Rings'' for his national titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my time in the sun,'' he said. ``I've had my time in
the spotlight. Now I want to have my time with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he stick to that pledge this time?
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be interesting,'' Wannstedt said. ``We're going to
call him. We're not going to let him lay down there and gain 20
pounds down in the Keys. We're going to keep him active. He's going
to want to be involved. He loves these players and the relationship
he's got with Wayne and Eddie. He's going to be here in South
Florida. This is his home.''
</P>
<P>
   He married his longtime girlfriend, Rhonda, last summer during a
party at their house in the Keys. Several weeks ago, after Bill
Parcells resigned as coach of the New York Jets, Johnson joked
about how ``some people are strange,'' how they actually want to
spend time with their family; how they want to sleep until 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   He let only a few people know, but at the time he had decided he
was one of those strange people.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Rhonda stood, holding their dog, Buttercup, and watched
as Johnson gave his farewell speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team has done some good things,'' he said. ``We
were one of three teams in the NFL that went to the playoffs the
last three years. And we advanced the last couple years. I think
we've got some good, young players on this football team. I think
we're in great shape as far as the salary cap. And even though some
may scoff at me saying this, I really don't think we're that far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   He maintained his composure until the end, when he started
thanking people, ending with words for Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know,'' he said, his voice starting to crack, ``how
badly it makes me feel that we didn't bring a championship to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, he turned the stage _ and the team _ over to
Wannstedt, a friend since their days as assistant coaches at the
University of Pittsburgh in the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish him the best of luck,'' he said. ``I'll do whatever he
asks me to. Again, I had ... ``
</P>
<P>
   He swallowed hard as he mentioned his 35 years of coaching _
which began with a role as a defensive line coach at Louisiana Tech
in 1965 and ended on this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 35 great years,'' he said, giving a wave with his right
arm as he walked away from the microphone. ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt gave Johnson a hug, then stepped to the microphone. As
Johnson, Rhonda and Buttercup headed for an exit, Wannstedt made
one last comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Jimmy,'' he said. ``Be careful on those roadblocks going
95 south now.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson smiled, glancing at his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``High tide is at 2 o'clock,'' he said. ``I've got to get out of
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
