<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Israeli Leader Wins Fight Over Banking Nomination
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Cabinet, over the public objections of the finance
minister, narrowly approved Prime Minister Ehud Barak's choice of a
conservative central bank economist as the bank's next governor.
</P>
<P>
   David Klein, who now heads the Bank of Israel's monetary affairs
division, was endorsed in a 10-7 vote after a long afternoon of
contentious debate that exposed stark economic policy divisions
within Barak's center-left coalition.
</P>
<P>
   A Friendlier Anti-Snoring Machine
</P>
<P>
   A chronic snorer has been granted a patent for a device he
contends will provide relief to serious snorers like himself. His
invention, an attachment to the previously used ``continuous
positive air pressure machine,'' makes that device more comfortable
to wear during sleep. The inventor said half of those who are
prescribed the machine stop using it because of discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Linux Vendor to Get Investment
</P>
<P>
   TurboLinux, a Linux operating system vendor with roots in the
Asian computer market, will receive a $57 million investment Monday
from Dell Computer, Compaq Computer, Intel and a variety of other
U.S. computer and software makers and investment firms.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling Group Wins Name Match
</P>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation has won back rights to the use of
its name in cyberspace, in the first case testing the new
international forum for resolving disputes over Internet domain
names.
</P>
<P>
   ABC Says It Resisted Script Review
</P>
<P>
   An ABC spokeswoman said the network stopped trying to collect
government financial credits for inserting antidrug messages in its
programs after President Clinton's drug advisers asked to see
scripts before they were broadcast. Her comments indicated that the
White House's efforts to advance antidrug messages were perhaps
more aggressive than previously believed.
</P>
<P>
   The Other Story of `The Hurricane'
</P>
<P>
   Promotional appearances surrounding ``Hurricane,'' the new film
exploring the life of Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter, the boxer who was
jailed for nearly 20 years for a triple murder, belie the happy and
simple ending of the movie. Carter and two Canadian men who
befriended him and played a role in his appeals process haven't
spoken in more than two years. Those two men are currently
promoting their own book about the ex-boxer, whose conviction was
eventually overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai Opens Silicon Valley Office
</P>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies, which had one of last year's hottest
Internet stock offerings, has expanded beyond its base in
Cambridge, Mass., to open an office in Silicon Valley. The company
provides services that help busy Web sites perform more efficiently
by directing traffic to the least congested parts of a network.
Akamai is opening the new office partly because some of its biggest
accounts, like Apple Computer and Yahoo, are nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Control Issues in a Media Deal
</P>
<P>
   America Online's proposed purchase of Time Warner is probably
not, after all, a snapshot of the new economy versus the old. It's
more like two very wealthy old men doing comb-overs on their
balding pates, trying to look hip and zippy but not quite willing
to let go of the past.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Financial Markets Closed
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets will be closed Monday in observance of
Martin Luther King's birthday.
</P>
