<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-VIKINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS ROAR PAST VIKINGS TO REACH NFC TITLE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Hello world!
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the first time on national television all season,
the St. Louis Rams held their official coming-out party Sunday
before a crowd of 66,194 at the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   And in the 49-37 blasting of the Minnesota Vikings in the NFC
divisional playoffs, the Rams showed everybody what their fans
already knew.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who turned a 17-14 halftime deficit into a 49-17 lead
with five consecutive touchdowns to start the second half, are for
real.
</P>
<P>
   Check that.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, led by quarterback Kurt Warner's five touchdown passes
to five receivers and a defense that limited the Vikings to a
minus-2 yards in the game-turning third quarter, are talented.
</P>
<P>
   Now everybody knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that they play in a town that was playing host to its
first-ever playoff game. Or that the team, which moved to St. Louis
five years ago from Los Angeles, was in the playoffs for the first
time since 1989. Or that the Rams had not beaten an opponent with a
winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much for not having playoff experience,'' Rams coach Dick
Vermeil said. ``John Wooden once told me that talent is more
important than experience. We have a lot of talent on this team. We
expected to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rams receiver Isaac Bruce: ``We were the only game playing,
other than the AFC. I think we played somebody. They were a tough
team; they were a playoff team from last year. I think we finally
smashed that question of us not playing anybody. We set the tone
and continued to pound them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Vikings (11-7), who were considered to be the
ultimate litmus test for a team that finished at the bottom of the
NFC West last season at 4-12, have been dispatched, the Rams (14-3)
have been installed as the favorites to duplicate Atlanta's last
place-to-the-Super Bowl journey of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   They are one step away, playing host to the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
in the NFC Championship Game next Sunday at 3:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Warner displayed the form that earned him NFL MVP honors,
completing 27 of 33 passes for 391 yards, including a sizzling
18-of-21 for 197 yards and three touchdowns in the second half.
Only two quarterbacks have thrown more than five touchdowns in a
playoff game. And his 81.8 completion percentage was the third
highest in playoff history. He completed passes to 10 receivers,
led by Tory Holt's six catches for 65 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Brothers, as the Rams receiver corps is called, set
the tone on their first play.
</P>
<P>
   After Minnesota opened the scoring with 31-yard field goal from
Gary Anderson, Bruce ran a post pattern and Warner hit him
perfectly for a 77-yard touchdown pass play.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Marshall Faulk caught a 41-yard touchdown pass from
Warner in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff jitters seemingly got to the Rams in the second quarter
when Minnesota turned two turnovers into touchdowns to take a 17-14
lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   It only proved to be a brief respite before the storm. Tony
Horne opened the second half with a 95-yard kickoff return for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   A Faulk touchdown run and touchdown passes to tight end Jeff
Robinson, former TCU lineman Ryan Tucker and tight end Roland
Williams followed, as the Rams blew the Vikings out of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The three fourth-quarter scores by the Vikings, including two by
receiver Randy Moss, who finished 188 yards receiving, meant
little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry the final minutes went so long,'' Vermeil said. ``We
held you guys up and delayed cocktail hour. They kept battling.
But, the game was over.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the coronation begin.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
