u a BC-NY-CARDINAL-TRIBUTE-4     01-16 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-TRIBUTE-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CELEBRATION FOR A CARDINAL'S 80TH BIRTHDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the people who turned out in tuxedos, furs and
jewels for a $1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner Saturday night to
the ones who trekked to St. Patrick's Cathedral in subways from
neighborhoods all over the city on Sunday morning, New Yorkers
honored Cardinal John O'Connor this past weekend, as much in loving
farewell as in celebration of his 80th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the dais in the Waldorf-Astoria's grand ballroom
Saturday night, the cardinal surveyed a crowd of 1,500 of his
wealthiest and most influential supporters from church, business
and political circles, poking fun at himself and a retirement he
did not appear to welcome, but seemed to accept as inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   He promised not to ``fade into the woodwork.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go one day,'' he told the crowd. ``Some wonder how
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it prompted laughter at the dinner, the cardinal's
retirement has fueled intense, if hushed, speculation in recent
months. Upon turning 80, cardinals lose their eligibility to vote
for the next pope, and so, after 16 years leading the Archdiocese
of New York's 2.4 million Roman Catholics, O'Connor is expected to
retire swiftly. His successor will probably be named at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Seated with O'Connor were most of the cardinals from the United
States, along with fellow archbishops, some of whom _ like
Archbishop Justin Rigali of St. Louis and Archbishop Edwin O'Brien,
head of the archdiocese for the military services _ have been
mentioned as possible successors.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's presumed final months running the New York
Archdiocese have been marked by personal trials. Last summer he
underwent surgery to remove a brain tumor, followed by radiation
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, he was briefly hospitalized for fatigue and missed
Sunday Mass for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He is now taking medications with side effects that cause his
body and face to swell, so physically he appears far different from
the trim, forceful advocate of the church's positions that New
Yorkers have known.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's friends said the illness, or rather the outpouring of
warmth that it prompted, had changed the man profoundly, bringing
out a softer side. For the first time in O'Connor's life, people
stopped to think about him, and to show their appreciation, said
Auxiliary Bishop Patrick Ahearn of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never got that before, and I see he likes it,'' Ahearn
said. ``It's in his eyes. It's in his smile. He's delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested that it was not so much the cardinal who had
been changed by illness, but rather those around him, who had been
reminded of his mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's made us more attentive to what he's tried to
do,'' said Timothy Rooney, the president of Yonkers Raceway Corp.
and an owner of the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dolan, the chairman of Cablevision Systems Corp.,
agreed. ``Before, we just didn't see him,'' Dolan said. ``His
illness has helped us to see him better.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After a series of tributes, including a videotape of his life
prepared by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., O'Connor told his followers that
New York was a complex city, where poverty could take many forms,
spiritual and physical, and the rich could prove saintly through
works of charity.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking without notes, he urged his admirers to continue their
``quiet works of mercy'' after he stepped down, and joked that he
was not at all ready to surrender the ``fancy digs'' he enjoys
behind St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will soon be evicted,'' he said. ``I will have the
distinction of being the first living cardinal who will be thrown
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try to pretend I enjoy it,'' he continued. ``I will try
to pretend I'm happy to be relieved of the responsibilities. I
won't enjoy it. I won't be happy to be relieved of the
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening raised $5.2 million for a new Cardinal's Legacy
Fund, which will finance educational and social programs, as well
as endow a chair in Hebrew Studies at St. Joseph's Seminary in
Yonkers.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrations continued Sunday morning at St. Patrick's
Cathedral with a tribute to O'Connor from the papal nuncio to the
United States, Archbishop Gabriel Montalvo. ``Even now, in this
time of infirmity, your eminence continues to teach us all by
example,'' Montalvo said.
</P>
<P>
   After Mass, the vast doors to the cathedral were opened, letting
in the crisp winter breeze as 3,000 worshippers sang ``Happy
Birthday'' to the cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime thing to see,'' said Teresa
Schiraldi, 71, who had taken the subway and the bus from Queens to
attend Mass. She said the cardinal's dramatic final months as
archbishop had made her more aware of her own blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kavulich, 62, had come in from Scranton, Pa., where
O'Connor had served as bishop for 10 months before coming to New
York. ``It's the first time I sang `Happy Birthday' in church,''
Kavulich said with a laugh. ``He's up and working, and he's been
ill for the past year. He's an inspiration to the church.''
</P>
</TEXT>
