<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLTS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE, BUT TRUE, TITANS' RUN CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Quarterback Peyton Manning was frustrated, and
probably a little sore. It was the third quarter, and his
Indianapolis Colts trailed the Tennessee Titans by 4 points.
Manning and one of the best offenses in football had been limited
to three field goals, dumbfounded by an aggressive and smart Titans
defense.
</P>
<P>
   When Manning's upper body was slammed into the turf on a pass
play by the 270-pound defensive lineman Kenny Holmes, the entire
crowd at the RCA Dome held its breath. Manning was not seriously
hurt, but he was angry, pounding his fist on the ground in
frustration, then getting up quickly to have a few words with a
wide receiver who had run an errant route.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating. Dizzying. But true. The favored Colts, playing
before a rabid home crowd, were beaten Sunday by the Tennessee
Titans, 19-16, in an American Football Conference playoff game. The
Colts were outcoached, outhustled and outmuscled by a team that has
a whisper of destiny about it.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a dominating third quarter by the power back Eddie
George, who had a 68-yard primal run up the gut of the defense for
a touchdown and 162 yards over all, the Titans advanced to the AFC
championship game at Jacksonville next Sunday with their sixth
consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   The game sets up an intriguing matchup. The Jaguars' only two
losses this season were to Tennessee (15-3).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Colts will wonder why they played so sloppily and
with such little passion. Coach Jim Mora, who guided his team to a
13-3 regular-season record, still has not won a playoff game in
five attempts going back to his days as the coach of the New
Orleans Saints. Indianapolis players dropped passes, and the Colts'
key players _ Manning, running back Edgerrin James and wide
receiver Marvin Harrison _ were never a factor.
</P>
<P>
   George was. He broke open the game when the Colts were leading
by 9-6 in the third quarter. When linebacker Michael Barber blitzed
up the middle, thinking it was a pass play, a huge hole was left
for George to squeeze his large frame through. He showed why he is
so dangerous, because his bulk is accompanied by a lot of speed. He
was untouched, and the Titans took the lead for good on his
touchdown at 13-9.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee added an Al Del Greco field goal of 25 yards early in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that the Colts were back in the game when Terrence
Wilkins took a punt return down to the Titans' 3-yard line. But
replays showed that he had stepped out of bounds at the Colts' 33;
Coach Jeff Fisher challenged the initial call, and the return was
correctly called back.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts did not score on that drive and Del Greco added
another field goal, this one from 43 yards with less than five
minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The only mistake George made was a fumble late in the game that
was recovered by the Colts, who later scored on a 15-yard run by
Manning with less than two minutes to play. The ensuing onside kick
by Indianapolis was unsuccessful as Tennessee wide receiver Yancey
Thigpen grabbed the ball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manning completed 19 of 43 passes for 227 yards. Harrison, who
had 115 catches in the regular season, had only five Sunday for 65
yards. James was held to 56 yards on 20 carries and one catch for 8
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans may have been lucky to be playing the Colts, but here
they were, thanks to a certain trick play at the end of their
playoff game against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Titans' coaches and veteran players were concerned
that the team remained too giddy about that last-second touchdown
in Nashville _ a kickoff return off a lateral thrown across the
field, now known as the Music City Miracle _ constantly discussing
it with friends and reporters, basking in the play's dramatic glow.
The danger for Tennessee was that the team was not focusing on the
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Titans awoke from their dream state, it did not take
them long to figure out the task ahead. Indianapolis is difficult
to stop because of the three-headed monster of Manning, James and
Harrison. Load up the line of scrimmage to try to stop James, and
the Manning-to-Harrison combination can incinerate you. Spend an
inordinate amount of resources on flooding the secondary with extra
bodies to stop Manning and Harrison, and James will light up the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee does possess a formidable weapon in Fisher's brilliant
defensive mind. Fisher has devised schemes to stop the vaunted
offense of the Jacksonville Jaguars, and coming into this game he
viewed James as the Colts' biggest threat, mainly because once
James gets going, it opens up the Colts' deadly play-action passing
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans began playing eight men near the line of scrimmage,
slowing James, and simultaneously clogging the middle passing lanes
because the Colts' receivers run a lot of short crossing routes.
The Titans' scheme had early success. Every time James approached
the line of scrimmage, he was met by a wall of Tennessee defenders.
Confident in his secondary, Fisher called for a lot of single
coverage on Colts' wide receivers, something few teams have tried
this year, but for Tennessee it worked well.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's influence was also seen in the Titans' blitzing
schemes. On a first-down play in the second quarter, Manning was
forced to use a timeout when several Colts seemed confused by
Tennessee's pre-snap look. Tennessee's great defensive play led to
the Colts looking out of sync, and even sluggish, at times.
</P>
<P>
   All Indianapolis could manage in the first half were three field
goals by Mike Vanderjagt, two from 40 yards and one from 34.
Tennessee, using a conservative game plan that called for a healthy
dose of George, had two Del Greco field goals in the half, from 49
and 37 yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 9-6 halftime score was in stark contrast to some of the
other explosive divisional playoff games this weekend. The first
half also showed this was not going to be easy for Indianapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
