<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-COLTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS END DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Tennessee Titans yesterday were able to do
for their 77-year-old owner of 40 seasons, Bud Adams, what the
Houston/Tennesee Oilers hadn't been able to do since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   They're now in the AFC Championship Game against the
Jacksonville Jaguars Sunday, following a 19-16 victory against the
Indianapolis Colts at the RCA Dome. The Colts were favored by 5 1/2
points.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Adams was asked how this one ranked in all-time
franchise victories?
</P>
<P>
   ``At my age, it ranks No. 1,'' said Adams, who turned 77 on
earlier this month. ``If we're going to go to the Super Bowl, I'd
rather not go in a wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee will be an underdog, just as they were a 5 1/2-point
underdog yesterday against the Colts. These Titans, if they're
anything, are resourceful.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, they used four field goals from 38-year-old Al Del
Greco, including what proved to be the game-winner from 43 yards
out in the final 4:19, along with a defense that kept the NFL's No.
4-ranked offense out of the end zone until the final 1:51 of the
game, to defeat the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days earlier, the Titans produced one of the wildest
endings in NFL playoff history _ scoring on a 75-yard kickoff
return which included a handoff and a lateral _ to defeat the
Buffalo Bills, 22-16.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game ball for Tennessee didn't go to running back
Eddie George, who rushed for 162 yards, including a game-turning,
68-yard touchdown run up the middle in the first two minutes of the
second half, as the Colts were caught in a blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game ball for Tennessee didn't go to Del Greco. Or
to Adams. Or to coach Jeff Fisher, whose instant-replay challenge
of what appeared to be an 87-yard punt return to the Tennessee 5 by
Terrence Wilkins with 11 1/2 minutes left in the game was reviewed
and brought back 61 yards to the Colts 34 because Wilkins stepped
out of bounds in front of the Titans' bench.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game ball instead for Tennessee went to 39-year-old
left guard Bruce Matthews, in his 17th but not necessarily his last
season for the same team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce Matthews got the game ball,'' said an emotionally
charged Fisher, ``because he has been with this team forever (1983)
and has never before gotten to the conference championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Matthews is in it now, along with Adams, Del Greco, Eddie
George and Jevon Kearse. The latter was in kindergarten in 1979
when the Oilers lost on a controversial call in the AFC
championship game at Pittsburgh. The so-called ``Mike Renfro Game''
was the model that the NFL used in deciding that instant replay was
needed in the game to reverse bad calls made on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' franchise isn't without its storied past of hard knocks
and battle scars.
</P>
<P>
   And now to get to what would be its first Super Bowl, the Titans
are being asked to defeat a Jacksonville team that scored 62 points
against the Miami Dolphins on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we beat Jacksonville three times (in the same season)?''
Titans' offensive tackle Brad Hopkins asked incredulously. ``What
do you expect me to say? `Oooh, Jacksonville ... 62-7 ... no, man,
I don't think we can.' Of course, I think we can win. People have
tabbed us `mediocre' and `average' all season long.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' vagabond team has had four different home fields in the
past four season: Astrodome (Houston), Liberty Bowl (Memphis) and
Vanderbilt Stadium (Nashville) before moving this season into its
new downtown stadium in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we've needed is a chance ... (and) good fans,'' said
Hopkins. ``Playing out of somebody's garage every year didn't give
us any advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, they took advantage of an Indianapolis defense that
ranked 18th in the NFL against the run. Somebody should have seen
it coming, as the Colts were ripped by the run in their final two
regular-season games against lowly Cleveland and Buffalo, barely
defeating the Browns (29-28) and losing to the Bills (31-6).
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning threw for 227 of the Colts' 305 yards of total
offense, but the only time they could get it into the end zone was
on a 15-yard scramble by Manning with 1:51 to play. The ensuing
onside kick was not successful.
</P>
<P>
   So the Titans are now four quarters away from their first Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And their 77-year-old owner would like to get there while he's
still walking under his own power.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
