u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     01-16 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SEASON TURNS ON THE WIDTH OF A SHOE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Terrence Wilkins thinks his foot width is EE, and
polite as he was after the game Sunday, he was not about to take
off his suede civilian shoes to peek inside.
</P>
<P>
   If his right foot were one size slimmer, he might not have
nicked the boundary between green field and white sideline, and the
Indianapolis Colts might still be open for business.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wilkins' acrobatic 87-yard punt return early in the
fourth period was downgraded, via the glory of instant electronic
replay.
</P>
<P>
   As a direct consequence of the videotape, the wild-card
Tennessee Titans won this playoff game, 19-16, to move into the
American Football Conference championship game next week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Wilkins' foot were less wide, he might not have
had the marvelous balance to keep himself propelled forward at
sprinter speed, eluding much bigger men trying to slam him all the
way to Fort Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts were down by only a touchdown, and they might have
been only three yards from a tying touchdown, if only instant
replay did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   However, the rookie from the University of Virginia had skirted
the line on the Tennessee side of the field, which was even worse
for the Colts because in his wake he left witnesses from the
visiting team, large men who pointed large forefingers at the scene
of the alleged perpetration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was I out?'' Wilkins asked after the game, saying he never had
a good view of the play on the giant screen in the dome.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody from the Colts argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches felt it was a legitimate decision,'' said Jim
Mora, the head coach. ``He stepped out of bounds, and when you do,
it gets called back.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true, but in the dark ages, when there was no instant
replay, the fallible mortals in zebra costumes could not be peering
down at every potential fumble, every sideline scamper.
</P>
<P>
   A play like this is why the National Football League has
returned to the device of instant replay, and why the league must
keep it in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   A recent league poll on the Internet produced an 88-12 response
that the instant replay should be retained. Of course, the margin
would have easily been reversed by the sad and angry patrons who
wore blue and white for the first home playoff game ever played in
this town since the Irsays slipped out of Baltimore in 1984 under
cover of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   After Coach Jeff Fisher of Tennessee made his official request
for a replay, Referee Johnny Grier stuck his head in a box on the
sideline and peered into the official league replay, and could see
what millions and millions of people already knew in comfortable
dens and smoky bars all over this football-loving country: Wilkins
had clipped the sideline at least once with the outside of his
right shoe.
</P>
<P>
   The fans booed, but if you stuck truth serum in them, they would
admit they were booing fate rather than booing the system or the
judgment of the referee. Justice prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   By this most narrow margin, the playoffs turned. Instead of
being within a few yards of a tying touchdown, the Colts began in
normal territory downfield _ the Titans' 33-yard line _ and on
Sunday afternoon young Peyton Manning was not about to pull off a
miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Manning was asked if the reversal by instant replay had
affected the Colts' momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to let it,'' said Manning, about the most mature
second-year player anybody will ever encounter. ``What I do is, I
expect the worst. We still had good field position, but we couldn't
make any long drives.''
</P>
<P>
   This sudden reversal of fortune has happened before for the
Titans _ last week, to be precise. They stunned Buffalo with a
75-yard touchdown on a sandlot lateral play on their own kickoff
return.
</P>
<P>
   Although technically a wild-card team, the Titans had 13
victories in 16 games, and have now won two more. They are the only
survivors from the first round of playoffs a week ago, the cash-cow
wild-card round.
</P>
<P>
   The first three games of the long weekend only confirmed
suspicion that the first week of the playoffs is essentially a
space filler, however sporadically interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins, who beat Seattle last week, resigned from
football on Saturday one day before their coach. They lost, 62-7,
to Jacksonville, and Sunday it was Jimmy Johnson's turn to retire.
Johnson, who more and more has begun to resemble Boris Yeltsin in
facial expression, can now retire to his South Florida dacha and
never ever think about his last game.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, which drubbed Detroit last week, looked inept in
losing to Tampa Bay, 14-13, on Saturday, losing when long snapper
botched the exchange for what might have been a game-winning field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the early game Sunday, with St. Louis
winning, &QC; 49-37, after Minnesota made it appear close in garbage
time.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, Tennesse then went out and won one for all the
wild-card, dark-horse, long-shot types in the world. Except the
Titans won't go for that characterization.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether that extra week of football, all the
pounding and the preparing, will sustain the Titans as they travel
to Jacksonville next Sunday for the conference championship game.
They have the momentum of crazy laterals and instant-replay
success. This is not your average wild-card team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
