<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOPE FOR KING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL GONZALEZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lingering hurt in Chandler more than two years after
the notorious July 1997 ``roundup'' of illegal immigrants by
Chandler police and federal immigration agents.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to complaints about illegal immigrants disturb ing
the peace, officers stopped hundreds of brown-skinned peo ple _
including U.S.-born His panics and legal immigrants _ and asked
them to prove their citizenship, an action that dam aged relations
between the His panic community and city leaders.
</P>
<P>
   To help still the waters, Mayor Jay Tibshraeny reactivated the
Chandler Human Relations Com mission and appointed 11 resi dents to
serve on the multiethnic panel.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the commission launches its most ambitious at tempt
at restoring unity: a series of events honoring the Rev. Mar tin
Luther Jr. and the civil rights movement he led.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Chandler has officially organized a
Martin Luther King event. The highlight of the week is a
$50-a-plate dinner Thursday at the Sheraton San Marcos in Chandler,
featur ing the Rev. Jesse Jackson as keynote speaker.
</P>
<P>
   As suburban populations be come more diverse, a growing number
of municipalities in the Phoenix area are forming human rela tions
commissions. The commis sions are intended to help protect civil
rights by offering citizens a forum for voicing concerns and
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Don Logan, who heads Scotts dale's Diversity and Dialog Of fice,
will recommend creating a human relations commission in Scottsdale.
Mesa and Tempe cre ated similar commissions re cently.
</P>
<P>
   Logan, who lives in Chandler, volunteered to serve on the Chan
dler commission to gain expe rience in forming the Scottsdale
commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community needs to know that government is in tune with
its needs and is receptive to their feedback,'' Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   Logan is hopeful the Martin Luther King event this week will
help inspire the healing that still hasn't taken place in Chandler,
where one in five residents is Hispanic. Jackson, a former pres
idential candidate, has been a leader of the civil-rights move ment
since the 1960s and was an assistant to King.
</P>
<P>
   But the roundup remains a divisive issue. It spawned two
civil-rights lawsuits. The city paid out $400,000 to settle one;
the other is pending.
</P>
<P>
   For 32 years, Chandler Human Relations Commissioner Sylvia
Encinas watched as Chandler changed from a sleepy farming town
rimmed by cotton fields and grazing sheep into a sprawling
high-tech manufacturing city of 175,000 known for big-name em
ployers like Intel and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growth, the city retains an air of friendliness that
kept Encinas and her husband, Albert, rooted to the same house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very good city to live in,'' Encinas said.
</P>
<P>
   But Encinas and some other commissioners say it will take more
than a few Martin Luther King events and a speech by Jackson to
erase the hard feel ings still festering 2{ years after the
roundup.
</P>
<P>
   They say the mayor, the police chief and the city manager should
be taking bold steps to reach out to the Hispanic com munity,
beginning with public apologies delivered in person at neighborhood
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do hundreds of events. But if they don't sit down with
them and take out their hurt, nothing is going to change, and they
are hurting,'' Encinas said during a testy meeting Mon day at the
Trinity Christian Fel lowship Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for the leadership to get involved _ past time,''
said Dennis Flaherty, another com mission member.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the commission, in cluding Chairman Kevin Hartke,
pastor of Trinity Christian Fel lowship Church, feel the mayor has
apologized enough for the roundup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If satisfaction was as simple as `I'm sorry,' well, that was
offered, and it wasn't satisfac tory,'' Hartke said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, however, will meet with the mayor and other city
leaders in February and ask them to do more to reach out to the
Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   Tibshraeny said he has already apologized to the Hispanic com
munity and doesn't see any rea son to do it again. The apology was
recorded on videotape shortly after the roundup when Hispanics
jammed a City Council meeting to complain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think an apology is an apology,'' he said. ``It stands
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Tibshraeny said he has met with members of the Hispanic
community individually and in groups numerous times since the
roundup and has offered to meet them at any time.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Tibshraeny pointed out, he voted against a $238,700
monument because some people said it slighted contributions by
Hispanics. The monument will include a life-size statue of re
nowned architect Frank Lloyd Wright, a friend of city founder A.J.
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one example where on a specific issue I've worked
with the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he also partici pated in Spanish classes offerred
to city employees and pushed for hiring more bilingual employees.
</P>
<P>
   While both Tibshraeny and City Manager Lloyd Harrell ac
knowledged that some members of the Hispanic community re main
unsatisfied, they dismissed them as a vocal minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a small group, I think, that is still complaining
about this, and that's fine,'' Tib shraeny said. ``You're never go
ing to get 100 percent agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Harrell: ``I would charac terize them as a small, very
active group of folks who con tinue to raise objections to every
city action. I don't know if they will ever be satisfied. I hope
that they will be, but that remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides reactivating the Hu man Relations Commission, the city
appointed a police officer to serve as a liaison between the
Hispanic community and the Po lice Department, Harrell said. The
city also instituted a Citizens Police Academy for Spanish-speaking
residents that exposes citizens to all operations of the Police
Department, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell said city officials are hamstrung by the pending law
suit from speaking too openly about the roundup.
</P>
<P>
   But Flaherty said the lawsuit shouldn't keep city leaders from
reaching out to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor and council are public servants,'' he said. ``I just
don't believe that the only ap proach is to say nothing. There has
got to be another answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, meanwhile, has made progress on several fronts,
he said, like beefing up diversity training for all city employees.
</P>
<P>
   Encinas said the kind of trust-building required to move for
ward still hasn't taken place. She said many in the Hispanic com
munity remain distrustful of city leaders, especially the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are supposed to be someone you can go to with a problem.
I've heard people say, `If I need a police officer, I'm not going
to call them,' and that's scary,'' said Encinas, who is ac tive in
her neighborhood church _ St. Mary's _ and who has worked as a
clerk for more than 20 years at Hartford Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the Hispanic com munity, the roundup brought back
memories of discrimination in the 1940s, when Hispanic workers
labored in the cotton fields outside Chandler, Encinas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this to be settled once and for all. I believe that if
they did (reach out) the people would back off from the second law
suit,'' she said. ``The mayor, city manager and the chief of police
need to get together with the neighborhoods and say, `We want to be
your friends. Where can we start?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Garcia agrees. Garcia, a retired Mesa police officer who
owns a video store downtown, was one of the Chandler resi dents who
filed the initial $35 million lawsuit against the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Hispanic commu nity as a whole is still hurting,''
Garcia said. ``They are still very suspicious. They are not very
trusting of the police depart ment.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler artist M.R. Diaz said his father was one of those
questioned by police during the roundup. A police officer stopped
him as he was backing out of his driveway one morning on the way to
work. In the aftermath, Diaz created a painting depicting
baton-wielding police officers getting ready to go after illegal
immigrants. A comic strip-like caption over the painting reads,
``Time for a roundup, boys.''
</P>
<P>
   But Diaz says something good came out of the roundup. It brought
the Hispanic community closer together, he said. Since the roundup,
two Cinco de Mayo festivals at A.J. Chandler Park and a mariachi
conference at the Chandler Center for the Arts have been organized
by the Chan dler Coalition for Civil and Hu man Rights. The group
was formed in response to the roundup.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the roundup, we sort of banded together,'' Diaz said.
``When I go to the mariachi festival I see my neighbors. Be fore
that, no one ever got out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the mariachi conference, however, Encinas couldn't help
noticing that the mayor wasn't there. Tibshraeny said he had a
family obligation that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been the mayor, I would have been there from morning
till night,'' Encinas said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
