<HEADER>
A7656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ART-575&AMP;ADD-(     01-16 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ART-575&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY LOOKS FOR VOTES OF BLACK IOWANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Iowa _ Bill Bradley, who has made an appeal for racial
unity one of the pillars of his campaign for the Democratic
presidential nomination, said here Sunday at a birthday
commemoration for the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. that the job
the assassinated civil rights leader began almost half a century
ago was far from finished, but that strong leadership from the
White House would help bring it to a speedy conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for votes in one of the few places in Iowa with a
significant black population _ 6 percent _ the former New Jersey
senator declared that the ``silence of good people,'' one of King's
favorite phrases, was often the reason for inaction on crucial
issues and that should Iowans help him become president, he would
speak up, loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am trying to do in my campaign,'' Bradley said during a
reception that preceded a commemorative dinner, ``is make good
people come forward and join us so that our voices can be heard. If
you believe you are your brother's keeper, you have to walk the
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's remarks were received with applause, and many blacks
in the audience had good words for him, aware that he has been a
strong proponent of racial causes going back to the days when he
played professional basketball, a sport heavily dominated by black
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's speaking up, walking the talk,'' said the Rev. John Ford,
associate minister of Corinthian Baptist Church, whose congregation
is mostly black.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to competing with Vice President Al Gore for
black votes in Iowa's caucuses on Jan. 24, or winning black votes
in any state, for that matter, Bradley nevertheless faces a tough
task.
</P>
<P>
   In most national polls, Gore wins the approval of at least 2 of
every 3 black voters. He also has picked up the endorsement of a
good many of the nation's top black leaders and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Many blacks say they genuinely like and admire Bradley. But they
are quick to add that when it comes to voting, they plan to stick
with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill Bradley is a good man and all that,'' said
Reginald Haywood, a department store salesman. ``But I like Al Gore
better. I've been with him for almost eight years as vice president
and he and Bill Clinton have made good on promises, on things
important to me. So I'm sticking with him now. You don't change
horses when the journey is going well.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Black allegiance to Gore can be traced in part to President
Clinton's great popularity with blacks. But over the past seven
years, Gore himself also has spent much time addressing black
concerns, frequently going into heavily black areas to campaign for
black candidates or to unveil Clinton administration programs
designed to improve things that worry blacks most, such as job
opportunities, schools, health care and housing.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday before he heads for Des Moines, for example, where he
and Bradley are scheduled to debate racial issues, Gore will
deliver remarks in Atlanta in honor of King at one of black
America's most hallowed shrines, Ebenezer Baptist Church. The
church is where King preached and is buried.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is scheduled to spend the early part of Monday attending
a King ceremony in Des Moines and then leading a discussion about
race at Drake University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore sent a surrogate, Lynn Cutler, a former Democratic
Committeewoman who hails from Waterloo but now is a White House
aide, to speak for him at Sunday's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   She told the dinner crowd of about 1,000 people that she had
only a brief but pointed message to deliver. ''My two bosses,'' she
said, ``get up every morning and then they work very hard on
programs to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley closed his remarks Sunday by speculating on what King
might think should he suddenly find himself in Waterloo at the
start of a new American century. Would he find progress in race
relations? ``Yes,'' Bradley began, answering his own theoretical
proposition. ``But now he would find the racism more subtle. But
equally bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bradley continued, the issue is not whether a black
person can go into a restaurant and buy a meal. The issue, he said,
is whether a black person can obtain a loan to buy the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much left to do if we are to live up to the memory of
Dr. King,'' Bradley concluded. ``We have to change ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
