<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES PREVAILS OVER INJURY AND TELESCO
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The site was unique, the stage at Radio City Music
Hall, but the performance by Roy Jones Jr. was familiar. By
dominating David Telesco over 12 rounds to keep his undisputed
light-heavyweight championship on Saturday night, Jones reconfirmed
that he is beyond peer in that division and must now seek
challenges in other weight classes.
</P>
<P>
   Jones (41-1) earned the unanimous decision, winning all 12
rounds on all three judges' score cards, despite fighting mainly
with his right hand. He had fractured his left wrist three weeks
ago in a motorcycle accident and had hidden that fact from New York
State Athletic Commission officials before the fight. He said he
did it because he was looking forward to fighting in the first
boxing match ever at Radio City Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me, we don't see an opponent that seems to be a great
challenge,'' Jones said. ``I have to challenge myself. Fighting
here at Radio City Music Hall was something that I refused to let
go. I would have to almost break my hand off to turn it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones wanted to bring down the packed house of 5,923 with a
knockout, but he couldn't send Telesco (23-3) to the canvas. He
kept feeding Telesco a steady diet of right hands, like so many
spoons of ice cream. But Jones couldn't deliver the left hook,
which would have been the cherry on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had two hands, one of us would have had to go to the
hospital,'' Jones said. ``Either I would have really broken it or
he was going to go out of there. I could hit him with the hook
anytime. My hook is my favorite punch. My hook is my best punch.''
</P>
<P>
   As Telesco's frustration mounted, he began trash-talking with
Jones. Jones said he started talking back to Telesco, because he
didn't want Telesco to keep up a one-sided conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was saying all kind of stuff,'' Jones said. ``Asking me if
I had ever been to prison. I said, `No, and I don't plan on going.'
That's a heck of a thing to ask me. Do I look like I want to go to
prison? What's fun in there for me? I don't plan on doing nothing
to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Telesco, 31, of Port Chester, N.Y., spent three years in prison
in upstate New York for possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute. This was supposed to be his big chance to win a world
title, and he had hounded Jones for the chance. But when he got
Jones in the ring, Telesco could barely touch him because of Jones'
incredible speed and amazing ring skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expected more of himself,'' said Joe DeGuardia, Telesco's
manager. ``He's very disappointed in himself. He felt like he let
down his fans.''
</P>
<P>
   After dispatching Telesco, who was probably the strongest of the
light-heavyweight challengers Jones has faced, the question for
Jones now becomes, what next?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever shows up; I hope it's that Dariusz Michalczewski,''
Jones said, regarding the World Boxing Organization champion from
Germany. ``I have to let my hand heal up, because I'm going to beat
him worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who turned 31 Sunday, believes it will take a month for
his hand to heal properly. If Jones does not meet Michalczewski or
Graciano Rocchigiani, the World Boxing Council No. 1 contender,
also of Germany, then there is a chance he could drop down from the
175-pound weight class to 169 pounds and fight Bernard Hopkins, the
International Boxing Federation middleweight champion. Jones
defeated Hopkins on a 12-round decision at 159 pounds in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, the heavyweight Derrick Jefferson (22-1-1)
punched himself out over the first eight rounds and was out on his
feet for the start of the ninth round. That paved the way for David
Izon (25-3) to score a victory on a technical knockout when Referee
Arthur Mercante Jr. stopped the bout at 11 seconds of the ninth
round. Jefferson was so tired in the eighth round that Izon sent
him to the canvas with a slight push.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson threw more punches in a little less than nine rounds
than Jones threw over 12 rounds in his bout. Jefferson threw 498
punches, connecting on 210, while Jones threw 494 punches and
connected on 293, according to statistics by CompuBox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so tired that he told me he had lost all bodily
functions the round before it was stopped,'' said Lou DiBella, the
senior vice president of programming for HBO/TVKO. ``He said he
literally thought he was going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson caught boxing fans' attention with a spectacular
knockout of Maurice Harris last September. He tried to repeat that
performance against Izon, but Izon's chin was much more durable
than Harris' chin. Jefferson was ahead on all the judges' score
cards when the fight was stopped.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
