<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINRICHS TO BE COACH OF U.S. WOMEN'S TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ April Heinrichs, one of the early stars of
women's soccer in the United States, will replace Tony DiCicco as
head coach of the women's national team, American soccer officials
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs, who will be the first woman to coach the women's
national team, will be formally announced as the new head coach at
a news conference in New York on Tuesday. DiCicco resigned in
November, four months after winning the Women's World Cup, saying
he wanted to spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs was a star forward on the American team that won the
inaugural Women's World Cup in 1991, bringing a tenacious style
that has become the trademark of the United States team. She scored
38 goals in 47 games with the national team. She has coached the
past four seasons at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows what it takes to win,'' said Hank Steinbrecher,
secretary general of the United States Soccer Federation. ``She has
very strong leadership, and she's incredibly passionate about the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the United States soccer community doubts that
Heinrichs, 35, has the potential to be an exceptional coach. The
question is whether she is ready now, with limited international
experience and the Summer Olympics approaching in eight months in
Sydney, Australia. She was the American team's second assistant
coach at the 1995 World Cup and the 1996 Summer Olympics, and she
is head coach of the American under-16 youth team. Her teams at
Virginia have reached the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament in each of her four seasons but have not reached the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   In hiring Heinrichs, the soccer federation passed over Lauren
Gregg, who had been the assistant coach for the United States team
for all three Women's World Cups and the 1996 Olympics. She was
also the head coach of the under-21 team for two unofficial world
championships. DiCicco had recommended Gregg as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after winning the Women's World Cup, the American
team now finds itself without its head coach and top assistant from
the tournament, and with its players on strike over what they
consider to be an inadequate salary offer from the soccer
federation. The federation has faced heavy criticism for its
handling of the contract negotiations and the hiring of a new
women's coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called the last bastion of chauvinism since Bobby
Riggs,'' Steinbrecher said, adding that he did not believe the
criticism was justified. ``We're confident we've done what we are
able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of embracing the World Cup victory, the federation
reacted tepidly to the women's success and for two months did not
offer DiCicco a contract extension. He eventually declined.
Officials in the federation were upset that the women announced
their own indoor tour rather than play in an international tour
that the federation was proposing in Egypt and South Africa. The
federation threatened to sue the women before a compromise was
reached on the indoor tour.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco has said he thought the federation's anger over the
indoor tour extended to its dealings with him, and that it was
looking for a scapegoat. Some people speculated that Gregg's
candidacy suffered for similar reasons and that the hiring of
Heinrichs amounted to an elegant compromise, allowing the
federation to look progressive by hiring a woman, but a woman other
than Gregg. Neither Heinrichs nor Gregg could be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrecher said he had felt all along that a woman should be
hired to replace DiCicco. ``You've got to be bold as an association
and break the ceiling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Heinrichs was hired over the more experienced Gregg,
Steinbrecher said, ``It's a matter of April being a dominant force
in the interview, and showing a great deal of strength and rising
to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speak specifically of Gregg's candidacy. Soccer
officials and some players have said privately that they preferred
Heinrichs over Gregg because she was less volatile as a coach and
that they thought the United States needed a change in coaching
philosophy with the rest of the world catching up. Heinrichs is
expected to keep together the core of players who defeated China in
penalty kicks to win the World Cup last July, Steinbrecher said,
while adding some younger talent.
</P>
<P>
   The American women are next scheduled to play on Feb. 6 against
Norway in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., but the regular players are still
without a contract. Steinbrecher said a meeting is scheduled for
Jan. 24 in Los Angeles and that a ``fair and equitable'' offer
would be made. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
