<HEADLINE>
SPORTING DIPLOMACY IS GIVEN ANOTHER TRY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif.)   (jw) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ In a rematch of a defeat at the 1998 World
Cup, the United States rallied from an awkward start to forge a 1-1
tie with Iran on Sunday before a crowd of 49,212 at the Rose Bowl
that was heavily in favor of the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, many of whom are in the off-season of their
professional careers in Major League Soccer, appeared rusty and
slow-footed in the early going. After Cobi Jones hit the post in
the second minute, the Iranian forward Khodadad Azizi began
sprinting right through a sluggish American defense. In the seventh
minute, Azizi played a clever pass to Mehdi Mahdavikia, who split
two American defenders and beat Brad Friedel with a hard-angled
shot from about 10 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   After defensive adjustments, the Americans settled down and did
not give up another goal. The United States tied the score three
minutes into the second half, when Jones crossed a pass from the
right flank that Brian McBride appeared to flick to Chris Armas,
who scored his first international goal.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition result did not compensate for the 2-1 loss to
Iran at the 1998 World Cup in France. But the American coach, Bruce
Arena, said he was satisfied with the performance of the United
States in the final 65 minutes and did not mind a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do that well, so kissing my sister isn't the worst
thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arena did say he was disappointed at the lack of American
support in the crowd, which consisted overwhelmingly of
Iranian-Americans dressed in red, white and green and cheering for
the visiting team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get behind soccer in this country,'' Arena said
Sunday. ``It's disappointing we don't have more people out here
today supporting soccer in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra security was on hand, including agents from the FBI in
plainclothes among photographers around the field, according to
officials of the U.S. Soccer Federation. The atmosphere, however,
was festive and peaceful, and the only protests against the Islamic
regime of Iran appeared to be people handing out leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian federation has extended an invitation to the
Americans to play a rematch in Iran. If the political and
scheduling logistics could be worked out, Arena said he would be
happy to play Iran again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would look forward to another opportunity,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
