<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RAE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVELIST CATHERINE RAE DIES AT 85 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Conn., N.Y., Colo., N.J., Texas)  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Catherine M. Rae, a writer who published her first novel at 73,
died on Dec. 25 at the Connecticut Hospice in Branford. She was 85
and lived in Guilford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after earning her Ph.D. at 65, Ms. Rae wrote her first
book, ``Edith Wharton's New York Quartet,'' a work of literary
criticism about the writer, who with Eudora Welty served as Ms.
Rae's inspiration. The book was published in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Her first attempt at fiction went unpublished after an editor at
St. Martin's Press suggested it was beyond repair and she should
write another.
</P>
<P>
   This resulted in ``Brownstone Facade,'' a mystery romance in the
style and tone of her beloved Wharton set on the Upper East Side of
Manhattan in 1920. It was published in 1988 and called ``a cozy,
intelligent diversion'' by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other novels followed, among them ``Flight From Fifth
Avenue'' and ``The Hidden Cove'' in 1995 and ``Sunlight on a Broken
Column'' in 1997; an eighth is being edited for publication. Often
set against the backdrop of fin de siecle New York society, her
works frequently centered on a historical event like the Triangle
Shirtwaist Factory fire. Ms. Rae's literary papers _ she was an
avid researcher _ will be donated to the Berg Collection at the New
York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Manhattan and graduated from the Horace Mann
School in 1931. She received a bachelor's degree from Barnard in
1935, a master's degree in teaching from Manhattanville College in
1970 and a Ph.D. in English literature from Denver University in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rae's husband, Gene, died on Nov. 13. She is survived by a
son, David, of Ridgewood, N.J.; three daughters, Lucy Rae Ricciardi
of Greenwich, Conn., Catherine Rae Reed of Littleton, Colo., and
Mary Louise Rae Arnold of Fort Worth, Texas; and eight
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
