<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-KINGHOLIDAY-VERDICT     01-16 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KINGHOLIDAY-VERDICT-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER CONSPIRACY VERDICT AS NATION CELEBRATES KING
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Martin Luther King Jr. High School in Manhattan, students are
more than well versed in the life and death of their school's
namesake. So when a jury in Memphis decided last month that King
was not the victim of a gunman acting alone, but was instead the
victim of a far-reaching conspiracy that included the U.S.
government, it made for spirited debate in James O'Brien's law and
justice classes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of O'Brien's students wasted no time in declaring that they
had suspected a conspiracy all along. Others said they were
unwilling to exonerate James Earl Ray as the gunman, unconvinced by
the jury's verdict in the wrongful-death case brought by King's
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had lively debates in class,'' O'Brien said. ``This was
a fascinating turn of history that we could get kids involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, hundreds of commemorations are planned Monday
to honor the life and legacy of King, as they are every year. But
this year's national holiday, marking what would have been King's
71st birthday, comes just weeks after the controversial verdict was
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, people invested in King celebrations, teaching and
scholarship have found themselves reconciling the verdict with
their own views about what happened, sometimes in discomfiting
ways.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, in the days leading up to Monday's
holiday, a time filled with assemblies and spirited recitals of
King's well-known speeches, a prevailing view has been that there
are greater truths in King's legacy than in the lingering
speculation over who killed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus is primarily on Dr. King's life,'' said O'Brien, a
part-time lawyer who seized the recent verdict as a current events
topic for his students. ``There's a sense of obligation that each
person has to continue on and to make the world better for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta, where King preached his
gospel of nonviolence, the Rev. Joseph Roberts Jr. said the verdict
confirmed what he had always suspected: that King's assassination
was a conspiracy. But the minister said he saw no need to raise
that issue during Monday's celebration, which is scheduled to
include Vice President Al Gore. ``I agree with the family that it
is time to move on,'' Roberts said. ``I got a big Bible to dwell
upon.''
</P>
<P>
   King's widow and children have long questioned Ray's 1969
conviction, and hoped that their civil suit would change the legal
and historical record of the assassination. And on Dec. 8, a
Memphis jury seemed to give them what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The jury declared that Loyd Jowers, 73, a retired Memphis
restaurant owner, was liable in King's death for purportedly hiring
a Memphis police officer, now dead, to kill King. The jury also
found that unnamed others, including government agencies, had been
involved, in effect accepting the King family's contention that Ray
was innocent, despite his guilty plea. Jowers, through his lawyer,
has said he participated in a conspiracy but did not know it was a
plot to kill King. The jury awarded the King family members the
damages they had sought: $100, which they say they will donate to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we know now what happened,'' Dexter Scott King, the
youngest son of King and his wife, Coretta Scott King, told CNN in
an emotional interview shortly after the verdict. ``And for us,
this is a final chapter. This is all we asked for, was a jury of 12
independent people, ordinary people, would hear the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But the verdict followed an unusual four-week trial that was
notable for the passivity of the defense, the prevalence of
secondhand and thirdhand accounts and the propensity of the judge
and jurors to nod off during testimony. In an unlikely alliance,
the King family was represented by William F. Pepper, who had been
Ray's lawyer. Without facing a jury, Ray pleaded guilty in 1969 to
killing King, but later recanted. He died of liver disease in
prison in 1998 while serving a 99-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   To some observers of the King holiday, the Memphis jury's
verdict was no thunderbolt. It did nothing more than reaffirm
long-held beliefs in a conspiracy. For others, the decision was an
irrelevant distraction, an unhelpful bit of hysteria that should
not be inflamed.
</P>
<P>
   And a great many people have reached their own verdict: that the
King holiday is not the time to dwell on such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, a spokesman for the Martin Luther King Jr. Center
for Nonviolent Social Change said the center's staff members were
rushing to put the entire testimony from the trial on the center's
Web site by month's end. But the spokesman said he was unaware of
any specific plans for the King family to address the verdict.
Throughout Atlanta, there are plans for concerts, dinners, parades
and public service projects sponsored by the King Center as well as
by colleges and schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, at the National Civil Rights Museum in the old
Lorraine Motel, where King was shot on April 4, 1968, the script
for the tour guides who will shepherd crowds Monday is to be
changed to make note of the recent court case, said Beverly
Robertson, the museum's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will probably tack on the fact that the recent court
findings suggested that there might have been someone else
involved,'' Ms. Robertson said. ``That's all we're going to say at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP and a longtime civil rights
advocate and historian, said he hoped that people would use the
holiday to do something that King might have wanted them to do. In
his view, the trial in Memphis was so flawed that the verdict did
not deserve notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a comedy, ridiculous,'' he said. ``I don't think it
enlarged in any way our understanding of Dr. King's death or of Dr.
King himself. We're a conspiratorious country, and with these big
assassinations, King and Kennedy, it is hard for us to think that
one insignificant person could have brought down these mythic
figures, but that's what happened in this case.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Branch, a Pulitzer Prize-winning author who has
chronicled King's life in ``Parting the Waters'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
1988) and ``Pillar of Fire'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1998), the first
two volumes of a planned trilogy, said he had not once referred to
the verdict in the many speeches about King that he had given since
the verdict. And he said he did not plan to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a distraction,'' Branch said. ``There was plenty
of cynicism about the federal government even before the verdict
among black people and white people, and the verdict only adds to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Memphis jury was the first to hold someone
accountable for playing a role in King's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the disagreement about its conclusion, it is a formal
part of the judicial operation,'' said Russell Adams, chairman of
the Afro-American studies department at Howard University, a
historically black institution in Washington. ``This Memphis
verdict for a lot of people amounted to a formal ratification of
informal opinions which were shaped the day the man was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the verdict provided a ``forlorn but satisfactory
closure'' to the question of whether a conspiracy was at work. But
in the public speeches on King that he presents, Adams said, the
verdict is unlikely to warrant more than two lines. He, for one,
sees a measure of hope in the state of race relations and in the
progress that African-Americans have made through the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a higher standard of deciding what is bad,'' he said.
``Our standards have gone up in terms of what has been done and
what is expected. It doesn't mean I'm happy. I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lischer, a professor of divinity at Duke University,
said that if the question of who killed King could be resolved
definitively, Americans could concentrate fully on his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is the accusation of a massive
government-sponsored conspiracy, we will never get beyond this
climate of distrust in this country,'' said Lischer, author of
``The Preacher King'' (Oxford University Press, 1995).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
