<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS HOPE THEY DON'T MISS A BEAT WITH RAP SONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rap song several members of the Jacksonville Jaguars recorded
back in November blared over the stadium speakers in the waning
moments of the Jaguars' staggering 62-7 demolition of the Miami
Dolphins in Saturday's American Football Conference divisional
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   This particular tune, ``Uh-Oh, the Jaguars' Super Bowl Song,''
caused no small amount of discussion in the week leading up to the
game, with questions about whether the song _ which offensive
tackle Leon Searcy, one of the rappers, claimed was never supposed
to be made public _ would be a distraction or whether the Dolphins
would take it as a sign of disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins did not have to look far for disrespect once the
game began, not when the Jaguars' Fred Taylor was making three
defenders miss him near the line of scrimmage on a draw play that
was supposed to pick up maybe 10 yards and instead resulted in a
90-yard touchdown run. Not when Mark Brunell and the Jaguars
offense _ which entered the game wondering how the battered
quarterback's knees might limit him in the face of the Dolphins'
pass rush _ capitalized on the many Dolphin mistakes to effectively
put the game out of reach before the first quarter was complete and
advance to the AFC championship game against the Tennessee Titans
in Jacksonville, Fla., next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Could the offensive line provide both pass and run protection
with Tony Boselli out and Searcy playing on a sprained ankle? No
problem. The Jaguars outgained the Dolphins by 257-21 on the
ground, Brunell, wearing two knee braces, stood in the pocket
against the Dolphins' early blitz efforts and the final tally of
yardage was 520-131.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the second quarter, Brunell exposed the
Dolphins' defense in all its confusion. This was a unit that had
sacked the quarterback six times in Seattle and finished the
regular season fifth against the pass in the league. But on
third-and-14 from the Dolphins' 39-yard line, Brunell was in the
shotgun formation. The ball was snapped, the Dolphins blitzed and
Brunell dumped a simple screen pass to Taylor, who juked his way
past four tacklers on his way to another touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars led by 31-0 and, only 12 seconds into the second
quarter, Brunell put on his baseball cap and had a seat for the
rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the Seattle film,'' Searcy said. ``The Dolphins had
a halfcourt game. Run on first down, run on second down. Our game
is all about the fast break. We wanted to control the line of
scrimmage. Hopefully this is a turn of events. The last couple of
games in the regular season, we didn't play our best. We had no
enthusiasm, no desire. It's refreshing to see how we played. This
is an example of what we can do when we stay focused.''
</P>
<P>
   The postseason records set give weight to the domination: most
first-half points (41), second-most points in league history (62),
longest run from scrimmage (90 yards), most opponent fumbles
recovered (5), second-largest margin of victory (55 points) and
most points allowed by the Dolphins in franchise history (62).
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, the rap song seemed the perfect
accompaniment for the new swagger and fun of the previously robotic
Jaguars. They lashed out afterward, angry that some had doubted
them because they had not beaten a winning team all season, and
because their only losses came to the only winning team _ the
Titans.
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued that the Jaguars still have not faced a
winning team _ not when the Dolphins played one of the most
listless games in memory _ but for now, doubts about the Jaguars'
ability have been erased. Perhaps other teams have played more
difficult schedules, but it is hard to imagine a more thorough,
all-around beating than the one the Jaguars administered to one of
those tested teams Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all season long that if we hadn't played anybody yet,
then we'd play what you call good teams in the playoffs,'' Jaguars
receiver Keenan McCardell said. ``We'll see how good we are then. I
guess we showed it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
