<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MAGUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES MAGUIRE, 95, FORMER LOYOLA UNIVERSITY CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ill., Ind., Ohio)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. James Francis Maguire, chancellor emeritus and the
president of Loyola University Chicago during 15 years of robust
growth, died on Jan. 10 at the Colombiere Jesuit Community in
Clarkston, Mich. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire's leadership was credited with bolstering the
university's academic standing among Roman Catholic institutions of
higher learning and greatly expanding its size and offerings. He
was president from 1955 to 1970, and then was chancellor to 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Under his guidance, Loyola Chicago added a medical center in
suburban Maywood at the cost of $50 million, which exceeded the
university's assets at the time. It was his decision to build the
center, complete with a hospital, medical school, dental school and
outpatient services.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, the university, which was established in
1870, became one of the United States' largest Jesuit universities.
It doubled enrollment to more than 14,500, more than doubled the
faculty, raised the operating budget to $37 million from $4
million, expanded its Lake Shore and Water Tower campuses, and
added laymen to its governing board.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire started new academic programs and departments, including
a school of education, a department of anthropology, an institute
of pastoral studies, a center for research in urban government and
Loyola's Rome Center for the Liberal Arts. He started an MBA
program as well as graduate programs in biology, nursing and
classical studies.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as chancellor, he began Loyola's first fund-raising
campaign. And as chancellor emeritus he was in charge of fund
raising and public relations for the university and its hospital
until 1998, when he retired to the Colombiere community in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   James Maguire was born in Chicago, received B.A. and M.A.
degrees at St. Louis University as well as a Licentiate in Sacred
Theology from St. Mary's College in Kansas. He entered the Jesuit
order in 1922 and was ordained a priest in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   He taught religion, Latin and English and served as an assistant
athletic director in Detroit and Cincinnati schools. He was
president of West Baden College, a seminary in Indiana, from 1943
to 1949, and president of Xavier University in Cincinnati from 1949
until 1955.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves no immediate survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
