<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-BUCS-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      01-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCS-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BUCS, IT STARTS AND ENDS WITH DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Buccaneers are many things _ slow starters but
tenacious finishers, for example _ but more than anything else they
are a defensive creation, a team whose core is a balanced,
throwback defense with traditional up-the-middle strengths.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's National Football Conference playoff game against
Washington, the Buccaneers' defense _ hobbling from nagging
injuries and behind for three quarters _ was scrambling to keep up
with the skilled Redskins. Suddenly, three of Tampa Bay's Pro Bowl
defensive players _ a safety, a linebacker and a tackle _ changed
the game in the span of 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When they were done, the Buccaneers were on their way to
Sunday's NFC championship game with a 14-13 victory. They will face
the St. Louis Rams, far and away the National Football League's
most productive offense. It's a big assignment, but expect Tampa
Bay, with the NFC's top-ranked defense, to tackle it with resolve.
</P>
<P>
   It's what got them through the game against the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you what was going on in the huddle,'' Warren
Sapp, Tampa Bay's three-time Pro Bowl defensive tackle, said after
the game. ``It was getting pretty late and we were being pushed
around. Guys weren't saying much, just looking at each other like
they were going to explode if this didn't change soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what each other was thinking: when is somebody going
to make a play? Because we hadn't made one on defense yet. And we
were going to lose if that didn't change.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading in the third quarter by 13-0, Washington was on the move
again when a careless pass by quarterback Brad Johnson was
intercepted by Tampa Bay safety John Lynch, another Pro Bowl
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch gestured to the crowd at Tampa's Raymond James Stadium
after his interception, then ran toward his teammates on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do something to fire up the offense,'' Lynch said.
``So I ran over to our sideline and spiked the ball as hard as I
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Coach Tony Dungy called the interception the turning
point. ``You could feel the energy go from John to the crowd and
back to our team on the field,'' Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
   Six plays later, the Buccaneers had their first points, a Mike
Alstott touchdown run that cut the Redskins' lead to 13-7.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was linebacker Derrick Brooks' turn to impose his will
on the game. On the Redskins' next possession, Brooks, the weakside
linebacker and another Pro Bowl choice, stopped Washington's Brian
Mitchell with a brilliant open-field tackle on a screen pass,
preventing the Redskins from converting a third-and-10.
</P>
<P>
   On the next Washington series, Brooks tackled running back
Stephen Davis for a 2-yard loss on first down, one of an astounding
12 solo tackles that Brooks made.
</P>
<P>
   On the next play, with Washington starting to play a little
harried, Johnson was forced to try a throw on second-and-12. He was
sacked by defensive end Steve White and fumbled. Sapp, the National
Football League's defensive player of the year, recovered the loose
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to win right then,'' said Sapp, who also
had a sack in the game and two key tackles in the waning minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers' game-winning touchdown drive followed Sapp's
fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a great second-half team,'' Brooks said. ``I'm telling
you, even after they took that 13-point lead, we didn't panic. And
what did we get? An interception, a fumble recovery, two
touchdowns. We win. That's our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy said: ``We've had a good defense for a while, but a belief
and confidence has started to kick in. We get behind by 3 points,
we feel at home. Down by 3, that's a good score for us. These guys
believe, with good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Against St. Louis, being behind by only 3 points might indeed be
what the Buccaneers are rooting for. The Rams' high-powered offense
and dangerous return game will surely test Tampa Bay's confident
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, part of me hopes it is St. Louis we
play,'' Sapp said before Sunday's Rams-Vikings game. ``Bring on the
best to play the best. If you want to go to the Super Bowl _ the
greatest show on earth _ then you've got to figure on going through
the biggest challenge. Washington was the second-best offense, and
the only touchdown they scored was on a kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who we play, but you know that St. Louis' offense
has been the big story all year. Maybe it figures our defense meets
them at center stage.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
