<HEADLINE>
BERNHARD WICKI, 80, EUROPEAN FILM DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernhard Wicki, one of the best-known film directors of postwar
Germany, died on Jan. 5 at his home in Munich. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure after a long illness, his wife,
Elisabeth Endriss, told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Though he began his career as an actor, Wicki rose to prominence
as a director with the critically acclaimed ``Die Bruecke'' (``The
Bridge''), his 1959 anti-war movie about a group of high school
students conscripted to defend a bridge in the last days of World
War II. He also directed, with Ken Annakin and Andrew Marton, ``The
Longest Day,'' the 1962 Hollywood war epic with John Wayne, Robert
Mitchum, Henry Fonda, Eddie Albert and Richard Burton.
</P>
<P>
   A Swiss citizen, Wicki was born in Sankt Poelten in Austria and
grew up in Vienna, where he attended the Reinhardt drama school. In
1938 he applied to the Berlin state drama school, led by the German
actor Gustav Gruendgens.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his acceptance Wicki was deported to the
Sachsenhausen concentration camp because of his previous membership
in a Communist youth organization and his association with the
Bauhaus school of architecture. Through the efforts of Gruendgens,
he was released 10 months later.
</P>
<P>
   During the war Wicki acted in the theaters of Munich; Salzburg,
Austria; and Zurich and Basel, Switzerland. Movie parts followed in
the 1950s, most notably his role as the partisan leader in Helmut
Kutner's ``Letzte Bruecke'' (``Last Bridge'') in 1953. His success
with that film took him to Hollywood, where his roles included a
dying writer in Michelangelo Antonioni's ``Notte'' in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 he adapted Friedrich Duerrenmatt's play ``Der Besuch der
Alten Dame'' (known in English as ``The Visit'') for the screen.
Starring Ingrid Bergman and Anthony Quinn, the film was poorly
received in the United States, and after his 1965 work
``Morituri,'' with Marlon Brando, Wicki returned to Germany. He
directed until 1986, when he suffered a cerebral hemorrhage. His
last movie, ``Das Spinnennetz'' (``The Spider's Web''), was
released in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
