<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GEORGE-TITANS-TEX     01-16 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-TITANS-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By Ray Buck c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When it mattered most, in the sudden-death NFL
playoffs, Tennessee's Eddie George outdueled 1999 NFL rushing
champion Edgerrin James of the Indianapolis Colts yesterday at the
RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   George rushed 26 times for 162 yards and a 68-yard touchdown run
on the third play of the second half that put the Titans ahead for
the first time in the game, 13-9, and they never looked back in
winning 19-16.
</P>
<P>
   George, who couldn't help looking ``up'', acknowledged that used
the end-zone Jumbotron television screen to see if anybody was
going to catch him from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I shouldn't have done that. I tried to focus on just
pumping my legs and not letting a turf monster trip me up,'' said
George, who ran a misdirection play to his left, cut back behind
right tackle Jon Runyan's block, broke into the secondary and was
never caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just caught us in a blitz,'' said Colts coach Jim
Mora. ``(The Titans) called the right play at the right time, and
(George) popped it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans are now 20-5, including 7-0 this season, when George
rushes for 100 yards or more. This includes the past two weeks in
playoff victories against Buffalo and Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Titans coach Jeff Fisher pulled George aside about 10 minutes
before the game and issued a personal challenge to the fourth-year
running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fisher) asked me to relive Draft Day 1995 and to remember why
he drafted me ... to lead this team to the brink of where we are
now,'' said George. ``He challenged me to live up to those
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   George did.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie James did not, rushing 20 times for only 56 yards.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ray Buck
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
