<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYS AS A TIGHT END PAY OFF FOR RAMS' TUCKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ For St. Louis Rams backup center Ryan Tucker, it was
just like old times.
</P>
<P>
   He checked into the game at tight end in the goal-line offense,
faked a block and curled to the back of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   All he had to do was catch and squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   For the third-year veteran Tucker, who played tight end in high
school and as a freshman at TCU before moving to tackle as a
sophomore and center his final two years, it was like riding a
bike.
</P>
<P>
   His 1-yard touchdown pass from Rams quarterback Kurt Warner was
part of a 35-0 run that buried the Minnesota Vikings. Tucker's
score was the fourth of five consecutive second-half touchdowns for
the Rams and made the score 42-17 with 13:36 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lined up as a tackle eligible,'' Tucker said. ``They really
weren't looking for it. But they should have, I guess. This was a
really special touchdown for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second of the season for Tucker. He also had two as a
freshman at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Rams coach Dick Vermeil said the tackle-eligible play is nothing
new, but he said it's a great play for the Rams because of Tucker,
who he called ``a tremendous athlete who is going to be a good
football player for us.'' BAD-BOY MOSS While the Vikings didn't
live up to expectations, Minnesota receiver Randy Moss lived up to
his advance billing in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, considered by many to be the league's most explosive
receiver, had 9 catches for 188 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The two scores of 44 and 2 yards were part of a 21-point Vikings
fourth quarter to help narrow the score from 49-17 to a more
respectable 49-37 final score.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who was passed over by many teams in the 1998 draft
because of his off-field behavior, showed in the fourth quarter
that his bad-boy nature still remains. Upset because an official
didn't call pass interference after an incompletion, Moss squirted
the official with water, drawing a 15-yard unsportsmanlike penalty.
RAMS' IMPACT SPECIAL Not only did the Rams gash the Vikings on
offense but they hurt them on special teams as well.
</P>
<P>
   Punt returner Az-Zahir Hakim had a 34-yard return in the first
half and kickoff returner Tony Horne ran back four kicks for 174
yards, including a 95-yard touchdown return to open the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vikings cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock: ``It changed the
momentum big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 17-14 at halftime, the Rams scored 35 consecutive points in
the second half. Horne started it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect Horne to score,'' Rams coach Dick Vermeil
said. ``But I appreciated it.'' GAME'S SPECIAL LYGHT Nobody could
put into words what yesterday's game meant to the Rams better than
safety Todd Lyght. And even he had trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Lyght, the most senior member of the team, likes to call himself
the Last Man Standing. He was drafted in 1991 and had never played
in a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting on this moment all my life,'' Lyght said.
``I'm excited for the team. But it's so big for me personally. I
knew the experience was going to be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyght said he's far from satisfied. His goal is to play in the
Super Bowl.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
