<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Jan. 17. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BORDER-2 (Phoenix) _ Arizona is America' newest drug mainline. Pot,
methamphetamine and heroin roll across the southern border so fast
and in such large quantities that almost no part of the state is
unaffected. In Nogales, storm drains pro vide a smuggling
superhighway, with traffickers parking over sewer grates to load
cars through holes in the floorboards. A barrio on the east side of
town has begun to empty because of the violence wrought by a
narco-gang whose leader lives just across the fence in Sonora, on a
hill overlooking town. Thickets along the normally dry Colorado
River bed south of Yuma conceal a maze of trails from Baja
California. When the river flowed with runoff last spring,
smugglers ferried loads across by boat. Near Douglas and Naco,
agents exchange gunfire with drug ``mules'' and get into smash-ups
with those running the border by car. By PAT FLANNERY AND DENNIS
WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MLK (Chandler, Ariz.) _ There's a lingering hurt in Chandler
more than two years after the notorious July 1997 ``roundup'' of
illegal immigrants by Chandler police and federal immigration
agents. Responding to complaints about illegal immigrants
disturbing the peace, officers stopped hundreds of brown-skinned
people _ including U.S.-born His panics and legal immigrants _ and
asked them to prove their citizenship, an action that dam aged
relations between the His panic community and city leaders. To help
still the waters, Mayor Jay Tibshraeny reactivated the Chandler
Human Relations Com mission and appointed 11 resi dents to serve on
the multiethnic panel. This week, the commission launches its most
ambitious at tempt at restoring unity: a series of events honoring
theRev. Martin Luther Jr. and the civil rights movement he led. By
DANIEL GONZALEZ. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   AGE (undated) _ Advances in gerontology may make it possible for
people born today to live to be 150 years old. What are the
implications of an ``I'm Dick Clark, You're Dick Clark'' world? By
MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``L'' categories.
With sidebar AGESIDE, experts redefine old age.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews.
By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   VALUES (undated) _ William J. Bennett has popularized
virtues-by-the-list, Richard Nilsens contends that lists of virtues
don't necessarily point the way to real virtue. By RICHARD NILSEN.
Story will move in the ``K'' and ``L'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   MCBAIN-IS-HUNTER (undated) _ An interview with author Ed McBain,
focusing on his lastest police mystery, ``The Last Dance: A Novel
of the 87th Precinct.'' McBain is the same as author Evan Hunter
(``The Blackboard Jungle'' and ``Sons''). By THOMAS ROPP. Story
will move in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TOLERANCE (undated) _ Today, there's &QL; no question that the
religious &QL; 
landscape of the United States is more diverse than it's ever been.
More Muslims now live in the &QL; nation, for &QL; example, than
Presbyterians. But does
this &QL; pluralism mean that Americans are becoming more tolerant of
each other's
faiths? Over the past two weeks, American Muslims have celebrated
iftars _ dinners that celebrate the ``fast breaking'' end of the
holy month of Ramadan _ at the Pentagon, on Capitol Hill, and at
the White House. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright hosted the
first Ramadan dinner for American Muslim leaders last month at the
State Department. Public events such as these suggest a growing
openness. Shifting U.S. immigration patterns, interfaith marriages,
growing numbers of converts to non-Western religions and, thanks to
the Internet, easily accessible facts on diverse faiths, have
changed the look of the national religious landscape. However, says
Rabbi Robert Kravitz, executive director of the American Jewish
Committee's Arizona office, there's a big difference between
tolerance and respect. And understanding this difference is the
challenge people face in this increasingly diverse religious
climate. By MAUREEN JENKINS. Story will move in the ``L'' and ``K''
categories.
</P>
<P>
   DESERT-BOOK (undated) _ A 1901 classic, ``The Desert: Further
Studies in Natural Appearances,'' by John C. Van Dyke (Johns
Hopkins, $16.95) has been reprinted. Richard Nilsen takes a look.
By RICHARD NILSEN. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL;
</P>
