<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEASE OFFERED TO COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of who owns the Phoenix Coyotes, Jerry Colangelo said
Sunday that he is willing to draw up a new, temporary lease
extension that will allow the team to remain at America West Arena
until a new venue is built for the National Hockey League fran
chise in north Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' lease at America West Arena expires after next
season and owner Richard Burke has said he has no intentions of
keeping the team there beyond the 2000-2001 season, at which point
a five-year lease agreement would kick in automatically.
</P>
<P>
   But a disagreement between Burke and the Ellman Cos. on
financing and a construction schedule for the $535 million re
development project at Los Ar cos Mall, anchored by an 18,000-seat
hockey arena, might make it impossible for the Coyotes to move in
until the 2002-2003 season.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with that alternative, and mounting annual losses re
portedly $10 million to $15 mil lion, Burke recently informed the
Ellman Cos. that he would be willing to sell the franchise and step
out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Burke has gone pub lic as saying he wouldn't go back
to America West Arena,'' said Colangelo, president of the NBA's
Phoenix Suns and managing gen eral partner of Major League
Baseball's Arizona Diamond backs. ``But now that there is
speculation of the team being sold or is in the process of being
sold, we certainly aren't going to put the Coyotes out in the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was never our intention. Our intention was to always re
tain them. But if they are set on moving, we'll do what we can to
help them through the transition. If that means working something
out for them to stay for an additional year or more, we're more
than happy to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said that stands whether the Coyotes are owned by
Burke or someone else, such as entertainment mogul Barry Kemp, who
has expressed inter est in the past of buying the hockey team. Kemp
owns a 6 per cent interest in the Suns and is a former executive
director of the Phoenix Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, however, could not be reached for comment to confirm
whether he is one of at least three prospective buyers Burke said
have approached him in the past two weeks. Burke has re fused to
identify the possible new investors.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he had person ally contacted Burke with his offer,
Colangelo said, `No. I'm telling you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, tell him I appreciate that very much, it's magnani mous,
and that I will give him a call,'' Burke said. ``Tell him, `Thank
you.' That will get fac tored into the equation and it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Because America West Arena is operated by the Phoenix Arena
Development Co., an entity of Suns' ownership, Colangelo basi cally
serves as the building's landlord.
</P>
<P>
   `WE'LL TRY TO HELP'
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spirit of cooperation, we'll try to help them here,''
Colangelo said. ``Having been through this process myself, hav ing
built a couple of venues such as America West Arena and Bank One
Ballpark, I know agreements have to be in place, negotiations have
to be concluded, land has to be cleared, and plans drawn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling tells me it's going to take a little longer
than people think (for the Los Arcos project to get under way).''
</P>
<P>
   Burke reiterated Sunday that his selling of the Coyotes, which
he purchased along with former partner Steven Gluckstern five years
ago for more than $70 mil lion, is not written in stone.
</P>
<P>
   `BEST INTEREST OF TEAM' ``I'm going to do what's in the best
interest of the team, making sure that it stays here, and getting
that arena built,'' Burke said. ``That's it in a nutshell. If I can
own it and the circumstances allow it, I will. If not, then I'll
make sure it's somebody who's committed to here and this proj ect
and that it gets done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now, (the Ellman Cos.) is not on the same schedule
as us and I don't know what their schedule is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
