American countryside. They are being replaced by metal storage
buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on charm. Experts
on farm life say that more than half of the nation's wood barns
have already been lost. In large part, the loss of the old barns
reflects the declining number of farmers. (Rodney White/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON, Iowa -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-1 --
``I know it's a beautiful landmark, but for what?'' John Berdo asks
of the barn built by his great-great-grandfather in rural Iowa.
``It's a shame to see the beautiful old barns go, but they're
useless,'' says Berdo, whose family has been farming here for seven
generations. Long the epitome of agrarian life, old wood barns are
vanishing from the American countryside. They are being replaced by
metal storage buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on
charm. In large part, the loss of the old barns reflects the
declining number of farmers. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ARGUN, Russia -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- CHECHNYA-RUSSIA --
Nikolai Koshman, 55, center, a Russian deputy prime minister,
visiting a damaged oil refinery near Tolstoy-Yurt as he toured
liberated areas of Chechnya. Koshman is the man the Kremlin has
charged with re-establishing normal life in the Russian-controlled
regions of the breakaway southern republic of Chechnya. It is more
than a humanitarian mission. It is also to secure the loyalty of a
wary population, depriving the separatist militants of the popular
support they need to wage a long guerrilla war. (James Hill/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-COLUMN --
BeautyJungle.com's Edward R. LaHood, chairman and chief executive
and Jo Anne Kauffman, the president, show off items in their
Chicago office. BeautyJungle.com, a beauty goods retailer that
debuted last November, sells products through five different
boutiques within its online store. Last week's purchase of
Beauty.com by Drugstore.com for $42 million in stock marked the
first of what could be a rash of consolidations among online retail
categories cluttered with well- financed but poorly patronized Web
stores. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- SUB-MONUMENT-SCAFFOLDING-2
-- Visitors passing the Washington Monument where workers have
begun dismantling the scaffolding. The strongest issue in sight
these days in Washington is whether the restoration scaffolding
surrounding the monument has proved to be a more glorious
attraction than the monument itself. For the past 18 months, the
scaffolding, created by the architect Michael Graves, has delighted
the city as an entirely free-standing structure, a lacy workplace
unattached to the monument that served to elegantly mime and
highlight the shape of the 555-foot obelisk. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- SUB-MONUMENT-SCAFFOLDING-1
-- The strongest issue in sight these days in Washington is whether
the restoration scaffolding surrounding the Washington Monument has
proved to be a more glorious attraction than the monument itself.
For the past 18 months, the scaffolding, created by the architect
Michael Graves, has delighted the city as an entirely free-standing
structure, a lacy workplace unattached to the monument that served
to elegantly mime and highlight the shape of the 555-foot obelisk.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- COLOMBIA-AMBASSADOR --
Colombian Ambassador Luis Alberto Moreno-Mejia, 46, hates his
country's reputation among Americans. ``I'm sure that if you did a
poll, the first thing that would come to mind is the association
with cocaine,'' he says. ``I think the self-esteem of Colombians is
very much hurt when we are perceived this way.'' An important
victory for Moreno-Mejia came last week, when President Clinton
announced a $1.3 billion emergency aid package to Colombia to help
the government of President Andres Pastrana in its war against
narcotics traffickers and the leftist guerrillas who control much
of the cocaine trade. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
