<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANTS-2 --
Music fans crowd Broadway below the MTV studios in Times Square,
hoping to see their favorite rock stars or be filmed during live
broadcasts of the show. The daily MTV throng often attracts hooky
players, but the New York City Police Department says they are more
wholesome than the truants of a decade ago. Unlike truants of the
past, looking for pornography or fake ID cards or even drugs, many
students today are cutting classes to seek out the glitz and
glamour of exciting events offered by corporate America in the new
Times Square. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANTS-1 --
German Patino, 13, left, and Juan Carlos Morales, 14, ride back
home to Queens after a day of Times Square truancy and as Morales
says ``checking out girls, man.'' He and his friends managed to
check out only one girl before they were rounded up by the New York
City Police Department's truancy patrol. ``I guess we learned our
lesson today,'' Juan said sarcastically upon his release. Unlike
