<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON, Iowa -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-4 --
John Berdo's family barn, in Washington, Iowa, epitomizes agrarian
life and the beauty of the American countryside. The barn built by
his great-great-grandfather in the1850s will be bulldozed in
February and the old boards will be burned. Modern metal storage
buildings which are cheaper and bigger are taking over the
landscape, if short on charm. Farmers today rely on high-powered
machines, much too large to be stored in the old wood barns, while
livestock is often confined to low-slung metal sheds, which look
nothing like the old barns. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-3 -- A metal
barn and a couple of old fashion barn just south of Ames, Iowa.
Long the epitome of agrarian life, old wood barns are vanishing
from the American countryside. They are being replaced by metal
storage buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on charm.
Experts on farm life say that more than half of the nation's wood
barns have already been lost. In large part, the loss of the old
barns reflects the declining number of farmers. (Rodney White/The
New York Times)
</P>
