<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-16 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-TOLERANCE-AZR &LR;      01-16 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOLERANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN U.S., A GROWING RELIGIOUS DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITORS: THIS STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``K'' CATEGORY) 
 By MAUREEN JENKINS  
   
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, the religious landscape of the United States is more
diverse than it'sever been. More Muslims now live in the nation,
for example, than Presbyterians. But does this pluralism mean that
Americans are becoming more tolerant of each other's faiths?
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, American Muslims have celebrated
``iftars'' _ dinners that celebrate the ``fast breaking'' end of
the holy month of Ramadan _ at the Pentagon, on Capitol Hill, and
at the White House. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright hosted
the first Ramadan dinner for American Muslim leaders last month at
the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Public events such as these suggest a growing openness. Shifting
U.S. immigration patterns, interfaith marriages, growing numbers of
converts to non-Western religions and, thanks to the Internet,
easily accessible facts on diverse faiths, have changed the look of
the national religious landscape.
</P>
<P>
   However, says Rabbi Robert Kravitz, executive director of the
American Jewish Committee's Arizona office, there's a big
difference between tolerance and respect. And understanding this
difference is the challenge people face in this increasingly
diverse religious climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tolerating means, `OK, my neighbor is different, obnoxious and
stupid, and I'll tolerate that he lives there,' '' said Kravitz,
also a member of the steering committee of the InterFaith Action
Coalition of Arizona, with members belonging to more than 10
faiths. ``That's not a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Kravitz is encouraged by the relationships built among clergy
within the InterFaith Action Coalition and by the school programs
that encourage students and teachers to celebrate diversity. But he
says society still has a long way to go when it comes to real
interreligious respect.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 4, he stormed out of the mayoral and City Council
inauguration ceremony at Phoenix's City Hall because an invocation
from a Lutheran pastor and songs by a Lutheran school choir made
him, a Jew, feel left out. Rather than just seethe about it, he
dashed off letters to Mayor Skip Rimsza and the chairman of the
city's Human Relations Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of hearing, `Oops, I've made a mistake,' ''
Kravitz said. ``There's absolutely no excuse for these types of
incidents to keep occurring. We are all to be included, not
excluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is optimistic is that there is an awareness that when
something is insensitive, someone will usually say, `Oops' _ and
they usually are not members of the offended groups. That means
people are really beginning to care about their neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's in learning about the vibrant faiths of these
neighbors, Kravitz says, that real acceptance can come. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIVERSITY NOTHING NEW &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although today's religious scene is changing rapidly, the United
States has, from its earliest days, been home to diverse faith
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   It's never been the monolithic Christian nation that some claim,
says Charles Lippy, author of the forthcoming ``Pluralism Comes of
Age: American Religious Culture in the Twentieth Century'' (M.E.
Sharpe,$34.95).
</P>
<P>
   From Roman Catholic Spanish mission builders to New England
Puritans, from Chinese immigrants in the West to the Native
Americans already here, America has been an ethnic, cultural and
religious stew.
</P>
<P>
   But many scholars say that 1965 amendments to the Immigration
and Nationality Act are most responsible for the religious
diversity that now exists. These changes opened the doors to people
from Asia and the Middle East, who brought faiths such as Islam,
Buddhism and Hinduism with them.
</P>
<P>
   What's most remarkable now, Lippy says, is that today's
immigrants aren't trying to dissolve in a mythological melting pot.
He says they practice and celebrate their faiths on their own
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see happening with Muslims and Hindus is that those who
bring their religious traditions don't (feel) like they have to fit
in,'' said Lippy, also professor of religious studies at the
University of Tennessee-Chattanooga. ``They're going to do their
own thing. I don't see new religious expressions defining
themselves against Protestant and Christian hegemony.''
</P>
<P>
   And because Muslims are building mosques and Hindus and
Buddhists are constructing temples in neighborhoods across the
country, Harvard University professor Diana L. Eck says, mainstream
Americans are getting a firsthand look at faith traditions they
know little about.
</P>
<P>
   Eck directs the Pluralism Project, a Harvard-based research
group that studies and documents U.S. religious pluralism. For the
past decade, students have done ``hometown'' research in cities
such as Denver, Houston and Phoenix, delving into various faith
communities to show the complexity of the nation's religious
fabric.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that surprises me is that this rather radical
transformation is happening in all sorts of places,'' said Eck,
professor of comparative religion and Indian studies at Harvard,
and one of the nation's best-known scholars on religious diversity.
``It's no longer just the big cities that are the ports of entry _
we're beginning to see this everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Chattanooga _ heart of the Southern Bible Belt _
now is home to three Islamic mosques, one Hindu temple, and a
Church of God that holds worship services in Filipino, Lippy says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, these communities can be here and flourishing
and folks not know they exist,'' Lippy said. ``An awful lot of
Southern folks were not aware how much this had penetrated. They
might be glad to have a good Indian or Thai restaurant in their
neighborhood, but they don't necessarily connect (them to)
flourishing Hindu and Buddhist religious expressions.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLURALISM TO ENGAGEMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Eck says, members of minority religious faiths are
moving into the American public sphere. She mentions the recent
Ramadan celebrations in Washington as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense in which we have begun to acknowledge in
public ways that Islam is a religion of America,'' Eck said. ``One
might say these things are ceremonial and pro forma, but they are
the kind of indications of the fact we have an Islamic population
that's making a bid for participation in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Hindus, Sikhs, Native Americans and Muslims are
establishing political advocacy groups. They run for public office.
They petition companies they feel disrespect their religious
traditions. They're working within the system to bring about
awareness and, they hope, understanding.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Shabbir Mansuri, founding director of the
California-based Council on Islamic Education, did 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbed because of inaccurate depictions of Muslims in his
then-sixth-grade daughter's social-studies book, this native of
India quit his chemical-engineering job to help textbook publishers
include balanced views of Islam for elementary and high school
students.
</P>
<P>
   Using state-mandated standards, 18 university scholars do
research for the organization and provide it to publishers such as
Houghton Mifflin and Prentice Hall for social studies and world
history texts. They also maintain speakers bureaus and hold
education workshops for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system allows us to sit at the table and contribute,''
Mansuri said. ``To me, it is the most incredible way one can
correct if there is misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mansuri thinks religious slights come from ignorance rather than
malice. And by taking a personal step to move beyond offense,
Mansuri's group now influences thousands of teachers and students
nationally each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to address the issue in terms of complaining,
but to provide the information so it would be accurate in the first
place,'' he said. ``Publishers say, `My God _ this is the answers
to our prayers.' And what I call this is our American way. I think
we need to participate in that spirit.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Maureen.Jenkins(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8307. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
