of their classmates, in the year 2000. (Todd Buchanan/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANTS-2 --
Music fans crowd Broadway below the MTV studios in Times Square,
hoping to see their favorite rock stars or be filmed during live
broadcasts of the show. The daily MTV throng often attracts hooky
players, but the New York City Police Department says they are more
wholesome than the truants of a decade ago. Unlike truants of the
past, looking for pornography or fake ID cards or even drugs, many
students today are cutting classes to seek out the glitz and
glamour of exciting events offered by corporate America in the new
Times Square. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANTS-1 --
German Patino, 13, left, and Juan Carlos Morales, 14, ride back
home to Queens after a day of Times Square truancy and as Morales
says ``checking out girls, man.'' He and his friends managed to
check out only one girl before they were rounded up by the New York
City Police Department's truancy patrol. ``I guess we learned our
lesson today,'' Juan said sarcastically upon his release. Unlike
truants of a decade ago, looking for pornography or fake ID cards
or even drugs, many students today are cutting classes to seek out
the glitz and exciting events offered by corporate America in the
new Times Square. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BROADBAND-INTERNET -- Cable
executives like Trey Smith of Time Warner's Roadrunner unit are
backing broadband via modems. Elizabeth Fetter, president of
NorthPoint Communications, promotes the phone industry's DSL
technique. Despite fits and false starts, the broadband industry is
now moving very quickly - due in part to the power of competition.
In this case between the cable television industry and the local
telephone business. (Left, Marty Katz/The New York Times. Right,
Jenny Thomas/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON, Iowa -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-4 --
John Berdo's family barn, in Washington, Iowa, epitomizes agrarian
life and the beauty of the American countryside. The barn built by
his great-great-grandfather in the1850s will be bulldozed in
February and the old boards will be burned. Modern metal storage
buildings which are cheaper and bigger are taking over the
landscape, if short on charm. Farmers today rely on high-powered
machines, much too large to be stored in the old wood barns, while
livestock is often confined to low-slung metal sheds, which look
nothing like the old barns. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-3 -- A metal
barn and a couple of old fashion barn just south of Ames, Iowa.
Long the epitome of agrarian life, old wood barns are vanishing
from the American countryside. They are being replaced by metal
storage buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on charm.
Experts on farm life say that more than half of the nation's wood
barns have already been lost. In large part, the loss of the old
barns reflects the declining number of farmers. (Rodney White/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-2 -- A metal
barn and an old fashion barn just south of Ames, Iowa. Long the
epitome of agrarian life, old wood barns are vanishing from the
American countryside. They are being replaced by metal storage
buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on charm. Experts
on farm life say that more than half of the nation's wood barns
have already been lost. In large part, the loss of the old barns
reflects the declining number of farmers. (Rodney White/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON, Iowa -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- BYE-BYE-BARNS-1 --
``I know it's a beautiful landmark, but for what?'' John Berdo asks
of the barn built by his great-great-grandfather in rural Iowa.
``It's a shame to see the beautiful old barns go, but they're
useless,'' says Berdo, whose family has been farming here for seven
generations. Long the epitome of agrarian life, old wood barns are
vanishing from the American countryside. They are being replaced by
metal storage buildings, which are cheaper and bigger, if short on
charm. In large part, the loss of the old barns reflects the
declining number of farmers. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ARGUN, Russia -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- CHECHNYA-RUSSIA --
Nikolai Koshman, 55, center, a Russian deputy prime minister,
visiting a damaged oil refinery near Tolstoy-Yurt as he toured
liberated areas of Chechnya. Koshman is the man the Kremlin has
charged with re-establishing normal life in the Russian-controlled
regions of the breakaway southern republic of Chechnya. It is more
than a humanitarian mission. It is also to secure the loyalty of a
wary population, depriving the separatist militants of the popular
support they need to wage a long guerrilla war. (James Hill/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO -- Jan. 16, 2000 -- ECOMMERCE-COLUMN --
