</P>
<P>
   Too fuddy-duddy and pre-millennial? Some prefer instead the Y2K
(Year Two Thousand) as the first of the D2K, and the D2k the first
of the C2K.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a terrible shame: no sooner had we rid ourselves
of the perhaps-awful-but-certainly-awfully-named Y2K bug than we
would be bugged by a whole algebraic era.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, faced with that ghastly prospect, favor various
permutations of zeroes instead. Yet the ohs, triple-ohs, trios,
noughts or the (minimalist) nils and nulls all fail to inspire _
although the zeroes were reckoned, by one British polling company,
to be a popular choice among the public.
</P>
<P>
   Equally the 0-0s, pronounced as the ``uh-oh,'' are really too
apprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, some good names remain available. The millies, or
the millie-nillies, could be popular and appropriately millennial.
But they are surely too flighty.
</P>
<P>
   One can proudly boast of being a child of the swinging sixties;
who would want to be a child of the silly millie-nillies?
</P>
<P>
   The aughts or naughts could also tempt, but lack the satisfying
``ties'' which give other decades' names a pleasing ring at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   So there can be only one solution, which fortunately can already
be found on the popular lists: a name which has the right tone,
rhythm and sense of fun, yet won't saddle the next generation with
distracting connotations.
</P>
<P>
   It must be the naughties. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this pithy 500-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
