<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-ORGANIZED FORBES CAMPAIGN COURTS IOWA CONSERVATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Iowa _ The Knights of Columbus hall and bingo parlor
isn't quite full. Still, more than 100 people interrupted a weekday
morning to make time for a politician. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes _ part candidate, part celebrity, entirely rich man
_ had brought his hunt for caucus voters to town. He baited the
hall with a modest chili lunch. His aides made sure the Iowa and
American flags would frame his backdrop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an age when most campaigns can barely afford to hand out
stickers, this one gives away pin-on Forbes buttons. Wait around
afterward and the candidate will gladly autograph your Forbes mouse
pad or a staffer might hand over a blaze-orange Forbes T-shirt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the come-and-get-it freebies don't offer enough appeal,
Forbes' speech is calculated to soothe the Iowa conservative. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Full of applause lines, it bashes politicians and politics (nods
and clapping). It slams the tax system _ ``the infernal, I mean
Internal Revenue Service'' (laughter backed by applause). It
promises parents the chance to use vouchers to help pay for sending
their children to private school (more applause). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' second presidential candidacy is determined not to
repeat the mistakes of the first, four years ago. Where the first
was long on advertising and short on organization, the second is
long on both. Where the first was a one-idea mantra _ flat tax _
the second trumpets several themes popular among conservatives. And
where the first one failed for lack of enthusiasm from social
conservatives, the 2000 bid preaches primarily to that voting
bloc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the core remains the wealthy candidate, the man who has
successfully led the publishing empire he inherited. The
52-year-old publisher and father of five is articulate, but his
manner of speaking is unexciting, his hand gestures stilted. He
seems almost trapped behind his thick glasses and uncomfortable, if
unendingly friendly, in meeting voters one-on-one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' strength, beyond the personal millions poured into the
campaign, is clarity of message and the often aggressive tone he is
willing to take. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in 1996, when his January lead in the Iowa polls proved
fleeting, Forbes has anchored his campaign on his so-called flat
tax. His plan would eliminate nearly all deductions and tax all
Americans at a rate of 17 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to let the American people keep more of what you
created in the first place,'' he tells audiences time and again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in 2000, his message is more sophisticated. Gone is the
robotic repeating of his promise of ``hope, growth and
opportunity.'' In its place comes a more spiritual appeal _ ``the
cause of redeeming America'' _ likely to score well among socially
conservative Republicans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If America gets it right,'' Forbes likes to say, ``the rest of
the world has a chance to get it right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference in Forbes' current strategy is his stand
on abortion. Last time, it was an issue he responded to in moderate
terms, and he was criticized from the party's right flank for not
making more specific pledges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This run he is all promises on the issue, all hard-line. He will
only pick a running mate who opposes abortion rights. His judicial
nominees must oppose it as well. He hammers regularly at
front-runners George W. Bush and John McCain for not making the
same pledges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His speeches noticeably avoid the word abortion, preferring
instead to talk of ``the life issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pro-life and I believe in the life amendment'' to the
U.S. Constitution banning abortion, he says. ``The first baby
picture for most couples nowadays is the sonogram. It visually
demonstrates a separate person with a separate soul....The new
birth of freedom should start with the freedom to be born.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 12 days to go before the caucuses, he began airing his
first TV ad on the issue. In it, one woman gushes about the results
of her ultrasound, ``my tiny child's heart beating, arms waving.''
Another mother says ``just because someone doesn't want them
doesn't mean that these children aren't still alive.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ads began airing the day after Forbes used a debate to
accuse Bush of hedging on the issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also has bought air time to bash the Texan on taxes _
accusing him of breaking a no-tax pledge as governor in a way that
hints of former President George Bush's ill-fated ``read my lips''
promise of no new taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 30 seconds, Mary C. Williams of the Houston-based Taxpayers
for Accountability speaks _ her voice nearly breaking _ of how Gov.
Bush signed a pledge in 1994 not to raise business or sales taxes
and then signed a bill increasing them in 1997. The ad, repeated in
radio form on stations across Iowa, does not note that the
increases were made to offset property tax cuts in Texas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If being negative means telling the truth, then I will tell
the truth,'' Forbes said in defending the spots. ``(Bush) made a
pledge in Texas that he would not raise the sales tax. He broke
that pledge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Forbes dubs Bush and McCain the ``timid
tax twins'' because they don't endorse his flat tax. And, to a
degree, scrapping the federal income tax system rests at the heart
of Forbes' hopes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do away with the (inheritance) tax. I like to say,
no taxation without respiration.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes wants to give workers more control over their Social
Security contributions, suggesting they be allowed to put at least
part of those payments into individual retirement accounts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So even somebody making $25,000 a year could begin to build up
something that when they reach retirement is hundreds of thousands
of dollars. We'd have real nest eggs for real working people as
never before,'' he tells his audience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each speech, Forbes calls on a local organizer to
take the microphone to encourage people to sign cards that will put
them in the Forbes data bank. They're reminded of the date of the
caucuses, of the time and that it might be some place other than
where they usually vote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has recruited more than 4,000 precinct captains across
Iowa's 99 counties. That, says one scholar of the caucuses, makes
it the best-ever organization in the state. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in the race very late'' in 1996, Forbes told reporters.
``The difference between this time and '96 is we've had the time to
build up genuine grass roots support.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That translated into Gene Strohman being lured to Forbes' stop
in Washington by a friend and ``the chance to see somebody
famous.'' Strohman, a retired farmer, was pleased that Forbes
``didn't look as dorky as he does on TV.'' He liked, too, the flat
tax and that the candidate ``is a successful businessman instead of
just a politician.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Strohman said he is torn between Forbes and Bush. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what Forbes says better,'' the farmer said. ``But I
think Bush is more connected and might know how to get things
done.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Strohman said, Forbes has his attention. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000116.0185 </DOCNO>
