<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BLAST-KAN &LR;      01-16 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS THINK FIREWORKS, CHEMICALS CAUSED KC HOUSE
EXPLOSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fatal explosion that rattled a south Kansas City
neighborhood Saturday evening was tripped by a basement stash of
fireworks and the chemicals used in their manufacture, a spokesman
for the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms said Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have not identified the victim, whose body was
pulled from the debris of a house at 1112 E. 77th Terrace about 11
a.m. Sunday. The house exploded about 5:30 p.m. Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The body could not be removed until an ATF investigator arrived
from Chicago to identify what chemicals remained in the basement.
Authorities were concerned about potential harm they posed for
personnel at the scene from the Kansas City police and fire
departments, the ATF and the Environmental Protection Agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the victim and the cause of death won't be
determined until after an autopsy and examination of dental records
or X-rays, which probably will be done today, said Tom Hensley, an
investigator for the Jackson County medical examiner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The force of the blast was apparent Sunday afternoon. Boards and
other bits of wreckage were lodged in the topmost limbs of a tree,
perhaps 100 feet tall, that overhangs the collapsed house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other boards and shingles ripped from their moorings were found
as far as three blocks away. Windows were blown out of many houses
in the same area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The series of explosions _ one neighbor reported hearing three _
also heavily damaged the house next door, which was then destroyed
by fire. The occupants, Calvin Barber and his mother, Edith Barber,
received minor head injuries and were staying with relatives Sunday
night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No damage estimate has been compiled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators had not determined why the victim had
commercial-grade fireworks and related chemicals in his basement,
one neighbor said he believed the man was in the fireworks
business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pages from ``American Fireworks News'' and order forms for
explosives littered a yard just behind the flattened house on
Sunday. Also amid the burned and soggy clutter were a
computer-aided design instruction manual and a copy of the magazine
``Log Home Living.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also warned residents in the neighborhood to be on
the lookout for debris in their yards that could be dangerous. They
were especially concerned about commercial fireworks,
high-intensity explosives that are used in municipal fireworks
displays. They found several such devices in the victim's yard and
one on a neighboring property a short distance away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATF spokesman Larry Scott said anyone finding such devices
should not handle them and should immediately notify authorities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping such explosives in one's home is illegal, Scott said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Workers for the Environmental Protection Agency removed several
drums of explosive chemicals from the basement. Although the
chemicals found on the premises are not difficult to purchase,
Scott said it is illegal _ and extremely dangerous _ to store them
in a residential area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize the damage it could do,'' Scott said.
``Static electricity can set it off. Heat, friction, any open
flame. We can't wear nylon clothes when we deal with this stuff
because of the static electricity buildup. It's so
unpredictable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victim was practically unknown to his neighbors. Wallace
Tillman, who lives a few houses away, thought the man was about 40
years old and was employed as a welder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I cut the grass, I'd see him welding back there,''
Tillman said. He remembered seeing the victim welding a section of
pipe and assumed it was part of the improvements he was making to
the house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victim had lived in the house for about a year, according to
the Rev. Toby Gray, another neighbor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The day after the blast, neighbors were in varying states of
distress and dislocation. Shards of glass lay in the front yard of
a house across the street where Robert Shaw lives. Windows in the
living room and several bedrooms had been blown out, and one
visitor inside huddled under blankets to counter the cold. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he will stay with his grandmother until the windows
are replaced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Ross Reaves lives behind the destroyed house. Reaves had
just returned from a movie Saturday evening and was mostly
undressed when the first blast shook her and cut the electricity
off. Then came the second explosion, and Reaves suddenly saw fire
all around outside. Not sure if the explosions were from without or
within, she was uncertain where to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A third blast hurled objects out of cabinets and caused pictures
to fall off the walls. Reaves grabbed a robe and shoes and ran
outside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the daylight Sunday, she said her house looked surprisingly
habitable. But she wasn't planning to move back in just yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
