<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     01-16 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-WEAPONS (Washington) _ In a sharp departure from its
previous assessment of Iran's nuclear capacity, the CIA has told
senior Clinton administration officials that Iran might now be able
to make a nuclear weapon, according to several U.S. officials. By
James Risen with Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BYE-BYE-BARNS (Washington, Iowa) _ Long the epitome of agrarian
life, old wood barns are vanishing from the American countryside.
They are being replaced by metal storage buildings, which are
cheaper and bigger, if short on charm. Experts on farm life say
more than half of the nation's wood barns have already been lost.
In Iowa alone, some 1,000 old barns disappear each year. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT6,7,8,9) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMES-SQUARE-TRUANTS (New York) _ The police roundups are never
accompanied by a reading of the suspects' Miranda rights. Instead,
the lieutenant in charge usually asks: ``Do you want to work at
McDonald's for the rest of your life?'' The suspects are junior
high and high school students, and they are playing hooky in in the
kind of place that has lured truants for more than a generation: a
shiny new mall. The only difference is that this place is called
Times Square. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT11,12) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EPA-BIOTECH-CROPS (Undated) _ In a decision anxiously awaited by
farmers, environmentalists and the biotech industry, the
Environmental Protection Agency on Friday announced a series of new
regulations to be enacted this spring for the planting of Bt corn,
a plant genetically engineered to produce its own insecticide. The
new measures were viewed by many as an acknowledgment by the agency
of the rising concern over the safety of biotech crops. By Carol
Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   5THGRADE-PROPHECY-REUNION (Highland Park, Ill.) _ Seventeen
years ago, Carl Berg asked the 27 students in his fifth-grade
class, ages 10 and 11, to write essays imagining their lives and
jobs, and those of their classmates, in the year 2000. They also
made a promise: that when Berg called at the turn of the century to
take attendance, they would make every effort to avoid being marked
absent by their teacher, who would be 48. Now ages 27 and 28, all
but five of those graduates of Sherwood Elementary kept their word
this weekend, reuniting in this suburb of Chicago to read their
essays and determine whether anyone's predictions had come true. By
Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT13,14) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KINGHOLIDAY-VERDICT (Undated) _ Debate over conspiracy verdict
as nation celebrates Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday. By Lynda
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-GORE-LABOR (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Al Gore can be thankful
that this state is more than an unending field of corn. Punctuating
the prairies are dozens of industrial plants that serve the
agricultural economy, and the heavily unionized workforce in these
farm-equipment factories and meat-packing plants is a major factor
behind the Gore camp's confidence that the vice president will win
Iowa's Jan. 24 caucuses, the first big test in this year's
presidential campaign. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-TOWN-BUSH (Red Oak, Iowa) _ George W. Bush puts a small
Iowa town on the map _ for a day, at least. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-BATTLE _ The annual fight over the federal budget is
about to get under way. Once again, the numbers-crunchers will
predict larger than expected surpluses, and Congress and the White
House will grapple with how to use it: to cut taxes, to increase
spending or to pay back the national debt. The arguments are
familiar, but with an election looming, the outcome could be
different. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   WWII-REFUGEES _ The story of European Jews who spent years in
displaced persons camps after World War II is one of the little
known chapters of the Holocaust era. It was the subject this
weekend of a three-day conference and reunion in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENT-SCAFFOLDING _ One of the most anticipated changes to
the capital in the upcoming year is the new unveiling of the
restored Washington Monument, which has been wrapped in scaffolding
for over a year. But so many people love the scaffolding itself
that Target, the discount store, is planning to buy it and put it
up somewhere in Minnesota. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT2,3) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ZELTSER-PROFILE (Undated) _ A look at Emanuel Zeltser, the
primary news source in the Russian money-laundering case against
the Bank of New York, a man whose credibility seems increasingly
questionable. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND-INTERNET (Undated) _ ``Broadband: How Broadly? How
Soon?'' The mantra for the AOL-Time Warner merger, and presumably
for other alliances that may follow, is broadband _ the ability to
carry Internet traffic at high enough speed to support high-quality
sound, video and other TV-like material, but with two-way
interactivity. Cable companies are renovating their systems to
carry such traffic, and so are telephone companies, with a
phone-network technology called DSL. But how soon will most
American households have the opportunity to ``go broadband''? By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
