<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TRADE-KAN &LR;      01-16 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMS OF NAFTA TRADE CENTER RUN INTO DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interstate 35 cuts through America's heartland like a concrete
artery, connecting Mexico with Canada. Local business executives
have dubbed it the NAFTA highway, invoking the multinational trade
agreement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The highway lies at the center of efforts to make Kansas City an
inland international port. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce is pushing to create
a high-technology import/export facility that would allow trucks
and trains to bypass border crossings and get processed in Kansas
City. The area is seeking $1.2 million in federal funds to design
the center and the technology it would use. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mid-America Regional Council, meanwhile, has snagged $1
million in federal funds to investigate how the six states
connected by I-35 can expedite trade by using computers to
communicate with truckers about road conditions and the contents
and safety of their loads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for all the time, money and energy being put into making the
I-35 corridor into a primary international trade route,
transportation and trade experts say it faces some doubts about its
potential. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, they say most of I-35 is outside the North American
Free Trade Agreement's trade mainstream. And that makes I-35 a hard
sell to receive scarce federal funds for the $10.6 billion in
improvements, needed mostly in Texas, to move traffic and trade
efficiently along the highway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you factor in trade around the world, it mostly moves
between centers of population and centers of manufacturing,'' said
John McCray, a professor and transportation consultant from the
University of Texas at San Antonio. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the centers in the U.S.? A third of the population
lives in the 13 original colonies. If you fly over Kansas City on
your way to Seattle, you see the lights go out pretty quickly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trucks carry the vast majority of trade with Mexico. And
research McCray did based on 1996 traffic showed that most of the
truck freight generated by NAFTA trade flows from Texas to the
northeast. His work was incorporated in a study by Kansas-City
based HNTB Architects Engineers Planners that pinpointed the
improvements I-35 needs to be an efficient trade corridor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Kansas City shouldn't be interested in
international trade, McCray said _ but the hard work is in getting
U.S. and Mexican businesspeople together to forge deals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The greatest potential comes from developing service and
information jobs, McCray said. Intellectual property doesn't move
by truck or train. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather be the finance and insurance center than the
distribution center,'' McCray said. ``All trucks are, are
pollution.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Promoters of the potential of Interstate 35 and a
trade-processing center here are undeterred. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doug Luciani at the Kansas City chamber gets exasperated by the
``mind-set'' of the trade bureaucracy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see studies that appear to confirm what has always
been,'' he said. ``Two hundred years of history show goods go where
the most people live, and always will, but that doesn't mean there
isn't a better way to move some of those goods.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Kansas City's economic history been shaped by
transportation, said Kansas City transportation consultant Michael
Webber _ its future depends on it. The city's location for moving
goods is its most compelling competitive advantage, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone in Kansas City will work in transportation, but
everyone will work here because of transportation,'' said Webber,
with TranSystems Corp., which headed a study evaluating the
potential for the trade-processing center concept. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that I-35 between Mexico and Dallas is one
of the busiest NAFTA trade routes in the United States. The problem
for Kansas City is that only a smidgen of that trade continues
north of Dallas along I-35. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 135 trucks a day move international trade between
Dallas and Kansas City. But 10 times that much moves from Dallas to
Nashville, Tenn. And much of what doesn't get siphoned off at
Dallas is siphoned in Oklahoma, onto Interstate 44. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The HNTB study predicts that by 2025, Kansas' share will have
grown to 610 trucks a day. That compares with the 1,400 trucks a
day moving between Dallas and Nashville _ today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Webber said that looking at existing NAFTA traffic misses
the point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about getting freight from Mexico to Atlanta,'' he
said. It is about capturing increased shipments to and from the 10
or 12 states around Missouri to Mexico and Canada. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas City doesn't make the investments needed to get this
growing trade, boosters say, other cities will. Then the area will
not only miss an opportunity to grow, it will face losing the trade
it now gets and the benefits that provides. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a common scenario in cities with strong shipping,
Webber said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``First you get a 15-person call center for a company,'' he
said. ``Then that becomes a 75-person distribution center, then a
150-person assembly center, then a 250-person manufacturing center,
then a bigger manufacturing center.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technology will make processing goods in the Midwest cheaper and
more efficient than at congested border stops and deep-water ports,
Luciani said. If some of the goods can move through those sticking
points unfettered and be inspected and unloaded in places like
Kansas City, it will serve as a safety valve on the ports and
benefit places like Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't prove it, because we haven't done it yet,'' Luciani
said. ``I know I sound defensive. We run into these arguments
frequently, particularly at the federal level.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While officials here concede that highway funds are getting more
difficult to snag, they point out that Kansas City has hitched its
concept to U.S. efforts to use technology to streamline the export
paperwork mess. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shippers fill out separate forms for the U.S. Customs Service,
the Food and Drug Administration and the Department of Agriculture.
The Treasury Department is developing a computer system that would
allow everything to be filed electronically. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the director of the Treasury office developing that
computer system, Robert W. Ehinger, has supported Kansas City's
plan, Luciani said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The chamber and other business groups like the idea of putting
some elements of the proposed trade-processing center at
Richards-Gebaur Memorial Airport to build off the increased NAFTA
trade that the Kansas City Southern Railway expects to move through
a new intermodal facility there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Voters in August approved a plan for the city to close runways
and lease part of the airport to Kansas City Southern so it can
build a larger intermodal truck-and-train loading facility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern's system connects with the interior of
Mexico through Laredo, Texas. The intermodal facility deal has been
delayed for months by opposition, but the airport was closed Jan.
9, and construction is expected to begin soon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Harrison, an economist at the University of Texas at
Austin, said Kansas City's rail facilities should help it attract
more trade to and from Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, who is doing research on inland ports, said about 75
percent to 80 percent of trade from Mexico moves by truck, because
Mexico doesn't have the infrastructure to handle freight containers
that can be moved by truck, train or ship. He predicts that will
change and that Kansas City's rail facilities could then expect
more Mexican trade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, McCray said the ``if we build it, they will come''
argument makes him nervous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These deals are almost completely driven by political
interests,'' McCray said. ``I would only do I-35 and a business
center if businesspeople say they want it. It is the business
players who create economic development.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
