<HEADER>
A7837 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-16 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRANIAN-AMERICANS HAD PLENTY TO CHEER ABOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ They've followed their team from afar for the
past few years, ever hopeful (but never fully convinced) they'd see
a day like this. Sunday, all their illusions became astonishingly
real.
</P>
<P>
   Years of darkness and then this: Their dream developing like a
vibrant Polaroid picture as they watched entranced, the twinkle in
their eyes, the gleam of nostalgia and, yes, perhaps a little
longing, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rams fans weren't the only ones who found pride and conciliation
on the football field Sunday. At roughly the same time the Rams,
formerly of L.A. and Anaheim, were in St. Louis cruising to their
first playoff win over Minnesota since 1978, many expatriate
Iranians were at the Rose Bowl, getting their first glimpse of the
Iranian national team since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   If thousands of Iranian-Americans weren't bashful about wearing
the old or new Iranian flags as their sleeves, it was
understandable. If they rooted without reserve for Khodadad Azizi
and Hadi Tabatebei and Mehdi Mahdavikia, they weren't being
ungrateful.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in cheering for the Iranian team, they were rooting also
for the freedoms they've found (at no small cost) in the U.S. For
so many Iranian-Americans, it was as if they came for therapy and
an entertaining soccer match broke out.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 50,181 ringed the Rose Bowl to watch the Iranians and
the U.S. national team play to a 1-1 tie in a friendly that was
just that. It was more polite than political, more mirthful than
militant.
</P>
<P>
   The black-gloved salute Iranian-Americans were urged to give
during the Iranian national anthem to protest the governing Islamic
regime appeared to have fallen on mostly deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto the pleas of critics of the Iranian government to refrain
from waving any flag save the ones being handed out at the
entrances that consisted of the American flag on one side and the
pre-revolution Iranian flag on the other.
</P>
<P>
   It was as though Iranian-Americans felt they were making a
powerful statement with their mere presence. They came, they
cheered, they celebrated the triumph of the human spirit over
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many of them, it ticked off U.S. coach Bruce
Arena. ``We need to start getting behind soccer in this country,''
he said. ``It's disappointing we didn't have more people out here
supporting the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens in this country when soccer is pitched as a
mere game.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian-Americans clearly saw it as something more. So it
shouldn't have been surprising that the crowd was so conspicuously
tilted in the visiting team's favor, the Iranians seemed to be
running downhill most of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Their counter-attacking style had the U.S. players on their
heels for most of the first half. Mahdavikia accepted a beautiful
pass from Azizi and swooped in on goalkeeper Brad Friedel in the
seventh minute. Friedel futilely tried to stop the shot _ he would
have had a better chance of stopping the intermittent raindrops _
and just like that the Iranians were leading in more than the crowd
count.
</P>
<P>
   The fans' loyalties, it should be said, were like those
two-sided flags so many of them were holding in their laps. They
loudly saluted the six acrobatic stops the Iranian goalkeeper,
Tabatabei, made but also cheered appreciatively for the shot that
got away. That would be the one Chris Armas booted with his left
foot off the cross from Cobi Jones in the third minute of the
second half to even the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their fans were very nice. They seemed to be cheering both
teams,'' U.S. captain Claudio Reyna said. ``It was a very nice
atmosphere to play in.''
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Reyna is too young to remember when
Iranian-American relations were downright toxic. He was 6 when the
U.S. severed diplomatic ties with Iran after students seized the
U.S. embassy in Teheran and took hostages on Nov. 4, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He can't remember, as we do, students on college campuses openly
questioning why their Iranian classmates were allowed to remain in
their midst. Unlike so many of the fans in the stands, Reyna had
neither heard the hatred nor felt the tension of that time.
</P>
<P>
   So it was easy for Reyna to blithely ignore the bigger picture
that the snapshot of Iranian and American players posing together
before the match represented.
</P>
<P>
   The political import of the match _ the first of its kind to be
held on U.S. soil since 1979 _ ``was never mentioned once all
week,'' Reyna said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity, that. After all, the first step toward grasping
history is recognizing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't concern ourselves with the politics,'' Arena said.
``If it helps promote peace in this world, terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   If head coach Mansour Pourhaidari had any real diplomatic pull,
he'd have extended an invitation to the U.S. to play in Iran.
``Obviously I can't say `yes' or `no' '', he said of turning the
happening into a home-and-home series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there is a return game,'' he added, ``so we can beat
them better than the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pourhaidari was laughing as he said that. The day was about
mending bad feelings, after all, not creating new animosities.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the next question didn't wipe the smile from
Pourhaidari's face. Did he think he would have been fired if Iran
had lost the game?
</P>
<P>
   For some people, obviously, diplomacy extends only so far. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-00 2353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
